Bodybuilding & Muskelaufbau - Wie oft muss man trainieren?


Wer schnellen Muskelaufbau erreichen m\xc3\xb6chte, muss regelm\xc3\xa4\xc3\x9fig ein Bodybuilding Training durchf\xc3\xbchren. Aber wie oft muss man wirklich ins Training gehen? Wichtig f\xc3\xbcr den Muskelaufbau ist, dass jeder einzelne Muskel immer wieder bis zum Muskel Versagen trainiert wird - und das am besten ein bis zweimal pro Woche. F\xc3\xbcr das Bodybuilding Training ist weniger die L\xc3\xa4nge des Muskelaufbau Trainings entscheidend sondern vielmehr die Intensit\xc3\xa4t des Muskelaufbau Trainings. Wenn Du bei jedem Training im Fitness Studio wirklich bis zum Muskel Versagen trainierst, brauchen deine Muskeln auch entsprechend Zeit sich nach dem Bodybuilding Training zu erholen. Von daher ist meine Empfehlung f\xc3\xbcr Muskelaufbau und Bodybuilding ein 3er oder 4er Split Trainingsplan zu verfolgen und diesen innerhalb einer Woche abzuarbeiten. Bei einem 4er Split ist es auch so, dass der Muskel einmal aktiv und einmal passiv trainiert wird. Zum Beispiel wird der Bizeps beim Arme Training aktiv trainiert, w\xc3\xa4hrend der Bizeps Muskel beim R\xc3\xbcckentraining passiv trainiert wird.

Weiter Tipps zum Muskelaufbau und Bodybuilding findest Du auf meinem Youtube-Kanal. Darum gleich den Kanal abonnieren und keinen Bodybuilding Tipp verpassen! Deine Fragen rund um Muskelaufbau und Bodybuilding kannst Du mir gerne auf Facebook posten http://www.facebook.com/esskarl

... und vergiss nicht, meine neue Webseite unter http://www.KARL-ESS.com zu besuchen. Dort findest Du weitere Muskelaufbau Tipps und Tricks.

Karl Ess (natural Bodybuilding Coach)'

Title: b"Cathe Friedrich's STS Mesocycle 1 Disc 1"
Description:
b'Order or learn more about STS at: http://www.cathe.com/sts

STS Workout Overview
 STS features three mesocycles, each lasting four weeks. Each mesocycle is designed to stimulate your muscles and body in a different way.
The STS program is designed to be simple and easy to use. Every STS DVD is numbered so that you can easily identify which DVD you will need for that days workout.
Each week combines exercises you have done in the previous weeks with totally fresh exercises that you havent done before. This way you always have some exercises that you are familiar and more comfortable with and new exercises that will keep your bodys muscles always guessing and challenged in new ways.
You will notice that every workout in the STS series has an information bar located at the bottom of your screen that will appear at the beginning of every break and will then disappear once the break is over. The information bar will always display how much time is left before the next exercise begins and will tell what the next exercise is as well as what equipment you will need. Other information like percentage of one rep max, reps and targeted muscle groups will also be displayed.
Mesocycle 1
Mesocycle 1 is all about muscle endurance. You will lift weights that are 6070% of your 1RM during these four weeks. Each week will feature a different workout for every muscle group. Your rep range will be around 15 reps or more for most exercises, but to total failure for many others like push ups, pull ups and band work. This cycle is divided into three muscle groupings with four workouts per grouping:
#1 Chest, Shoulders and Biceps
#2 Back and Triceps
#3 Legs
These nonstop workouts are sure to test the endurance of even an advanced exerciser and feature training concepts like drop sets, 21s and rest periods of 3045 seconds between exercises. You will do one set for each muscle group and have only about 30 seconds of rest before moving on to the next body part.'

Title: b"Intermittent Fasting and Cutting Pro's and Con's | Nutrition and Diet Topic"
Description:
b"So it's been a while since I last did an Intermittent Fasting / Lean Gains video. Since I have finished my cutting whilst doing Intermittent Fasting a month ago I figured now would be a good time to look back and break down the pro's and con's I have experienced.

Straight into it then...

Pro's:

- Increased Satiety. Having such a large amount of calories in such a small time frame leaves you feeling fuller and more satisfied, reducing hunger pains and cravings.
- More Muscle Retention. I found that I kept more lean mass whilst doing Intermittent Fasting than compared to a conventional diet and especially more so than when I did the Ketogenic Diet. 
- More Strength Retention. Directly proportionate to the increased muscle retention, I found that I managed to keep around 90% of my strength throughout the cut. 
- More Definition whilst Fasted. I found that the difference in my body composition when fasted vs non fasted was really noticeable. I had much more definition during the fasting periods.
- Smooth Energy Levels. During the fasted windows I had constant, smooth energy. 

Con's:

- Bloating. Having the large meals during the eating phase I often found myself becoming very bloated and uncomfortable at times.
- Energy Crash after Eating. Some times I found that after a particularly large meal I would find myself very tired and lethargic almost immediately. 
- Loss of definition during Feeding Window. 
- Sociable Eating Restrictions. If you are trying to stick to your windows you may find that social events do not tie in with when you can and can't eat / drink calories. This can be overcome by making Intermittent Fasting fit around your life, not you around it.

Verdict:

All in all, I preferred doing Intermittent Fasting as a method of cutting than following a conventional 4-6 meals a day. I will definitely be using it again next year when I cut and currently I am using it for my bulk which I will do a video on in a few weeks.

Thanks for watching!

Title: b'I Need To Gain Weight: 3 Crazy Tricks That Worked For Me'

In this video, Fitness model Troy Adashun reveals 3 secrets that he has used to go from a naturally skinny 130-pound high school kid to a ripped 190-pound fitness model.

So many skinny guys have come up to Troy over the years and said, "I need to gain weight." They also ask, "How many calories do I need to gain weight?" and "How can I gain weight fast?" These questions are always on the minds of every naturally skinny guy.

Troy has been through the struggles of gaining weight and has come up with a huge list of outside-the-box tricks that have helped him get a rapid body transformation.

Troy discusses the importance of the post-workout insulin spike. If you need to gain weight fast, you have to understand the importance of spiking your anabolic hormones at the proper times. Watch the video as Troy breaks down everything that goes into his 1,000 calorie breakfasts. This is one delicious way to gain weight fast!

Title: b'Side Kick Internal & External Rotation | Pilates Workout'
Description:
b"Watch more How to Do Pilates videos: http://www.howcast.com/videos/505920-Side-Kick-Internal-and-External-Rotation-Pilates-Workout



Last in the intermediate sidekick variations is internal external rotation. So right after beats, you'll lift your top leg up, hip height and hold it there. Turn your toes up towards the ceiling, so this is external rotation and then turn your leg back to parallel. Now this is really a parallel position but we call it internal rotation because you're returning from external rotation. True internal rotation looks like this, where the toes are pointing down, the heel is lifted. But that position does not exist in classical Pilates. So, flex the heel, turn the toes toward the ceiling, inhale, then exhale turn the leg back to parallel. And again. That's it, turn the heels parallel. Keep your leg completely still and long so the knee and ankle are right in line with the hip. One more time Madeline. Now hold it here, and lower your leg back down. 

So once you've learned all of the intermediate side kick variations, you can do the entire beginners series of side kick variations add on all of the intermediate variation. Again in the side circles bicycle beats, internal/external rotation. Do that whole thing and then switch to be other side. So let's see the whole sidekick series on the other side. 

All right. Starting with our dinner variations, the heel's forward off of the edge of the mat. Hover the top leg up here hip height. The front back, kick two times to the front, point the toes and reach back. Two more times here, kick, kick, point back . One more time. Kick, kick point reach back. Now bring the top leg over the bottom leg for up, down. Lower the leg, flex the heel, lift the leg up, point the toe and lower it. Two more times. One more time here and point to lower. Now reverse this. Point to lift, and flex to lower. For two, one more time. 

Now we'll go into circles so you'll hover the heel up hip height and do three small circles to the front brushing the thigh three, two, and one. Now reverse this for three, for two, for one and lower your leg down. Moving into intermediate variations we'll start with inside circles, so turn the toes up, slide the heel up the knee stepping on the mat, then lift your top heel up here, flex the heel, and go into three small circles. For three, for two, and one. Then reverse this. Three, and two, and one. Hold the leg here and lower it down. 

Now stretch your top leg over the bottom leg, for bicycle. Lift the top leg up here, bend the knee toward the chest, extend the leg long in front of you, sweep the leg back behind you, pull your heel into your seat and the knee toward the chest and again, two more times. That's it, keep working on your form, keeping the hips steady and the abdominals drawn in up. Now reverse this to the back for three, around and forward. Emphasis the stretch through the legs here and the control. One more time. 

Now bring your top leg over your bottom leg, for beats. So lift both legs up off the mat, feel your abdominal draw in and up and begin to beat the heels here. Eight, seven, six, five, four, three, two, one, hold it here; lower both legs to the mat. Now flex both heels parallel, lift your top heel up for internal/external rotation. You'll turn the toes to the ceiling, this is your external rotation, turn the leg back to parallel for internal rotation and again. Toes to the ceiling and parallel, you're turning the leg up in the hips socket for this exercise. One last time. Hold it here, then lower your leg all the way back down. And that's the beginner and intermediate side kick series."

Title: b'Testing My Vert'
Description:
b"You never know until you try. I didn't really know my vert officially until after the post training. I started off with an about 38 inch vert and was able to increase it by 3 inches. Post training I was able to record a 41 inch vert. This goes to show that if you train well you can see results. For those who were wondering I was training with Donny 3 times a week, typically Monday, Wednesday, Friday, and I trained for about an hour or hour an a half depending on the exercises I needed to do.

If you just train so you can jump higher and want instant results, you're not going to reach your goal and you will be disappointed. Train humbly, be patient, and be consistent and persistent and you will see gains for sure.

Now going into jump training I already knew it was gonna be hard for myself to see increases in my vert but getting stronger, more flexible, and taking care of my body were big steps in gaining inches I didn't have. I now know how important it is to lift weights, do the proper exercises, and how to keep my body in its top shape so I can perform at my highest level for longer ranges of time.

Good luck and thanks for watching!

Here's Donny's Channel:
https://www.youtube.com/user/ElevateYourselfNow/featured

Here's his latest jump training video (featuring me!): 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Ar_F8QonZM

Here's myself testing my vert about 3 years ago:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=saI_yw0km48"

M\xc3\x81S INFO SOBRE SENTADILLAS: http://bit.ly/beneficiosmusculossentadillas----- 

DESCRIPCI\xc3\x93N DEL V\xc3\x8dDEO -----

Las sentadillas son un ejercicio b\xc3\xa1sico que deber\xc3\xada estar en vuestras rutinas. Es muy completo pero tambi\xc3\xa9n peligroso si se ejecuta mal.
En esta v\xc3\xaddeo tutorial aprender\xc3\xa1s c\xc3\xb3mo hacer una sentadilla y qu\xc3\xa9 ejercicios realizar si es la primera vez que lo haces.

T\xc3\x89CNICA:
-Pies anchura de las caderas (o un poco m\xc3\xa1s).
-Pies ligeramente orientados hacia fuera si se desea.
(Mayor apertura y orientaci\xc3\xb3n hacia fuera implica una mayor incidencia en los gl\xc3\xbateos y adductores).
-Espalda siempre recta (contraer el abdomen para ello).
-Cabeza mira al frente.
-Peso sobre los talones (para evitar llevar las rodillas por delante de la punta de los pies).
-Llevar el culo hacia atr\xc3\xa1s (como si fu\xc3\xa9semos a sentarnos en una silla), hasta dejar los muslos a 90\xc2\xba grados (si no llegamos no pasa nada).
-Al subir, contraer gl\xc3\xbateos.

EJERCICIOS PARA PRINCIPIANTES:
-Con un fitball, nos sentamos en \xc3\xa9l. En cuanto el culo toque la pelota, contraemos gl\xc3\xbateos para subir.
-El mismo ejercicio anterior pero con una silla.
-Sentadillas mir\xc3\xa1ndonos al espejo para ver qu\xc3\xa9 tal nuestra alineaci\xc3\xb3n (no hacerlo siempre as\xc3\xad porque la vista ha de mirar al frente)

Wie gef\xc3\xa4hrlich sind S\xc3\xbc\xc3\x9fstoffe oder Zucker-Alternativen? Raffinierter Zucker an sich ist alles andere als Gesund. Denn der Zucker geht direkt in die Blutbahn und erh\xc3\xb6ht dort den Blutzucker-Spiegel. Das Problem ist, dass der Zucker dem K\xc3\xb6rper nur "leere" Kalorien liefert. Au\xc3\x9fer schnell verf\xc3\xbcgbaren Kohlenhydraten hat Zucker weder Vitamine, noch Minerale oder sonstige Stoffe die die Gesundheit f\xc3\xb6rdern w\xc3\xbcrden. Im Gegenteil! Forscher vergleichen mittlerweile Zucker mit Sucht-Stoffen wie Heroin von der Wirkung auf das Gehirn. Grund genug f\xc3\xbcr viele Menschen sich die Zucker-Alternativen - die S\xc3\xbc\xc3\x9fstoffe - n\xc3\xa4her anzuschauen. S\xc3\xbc\xc3\x9fstoffe gaukeln dem Gehirn vor, dass die Nahrung Kohlenhydrate in Form von Zucker enth\xc3\xa4lt. Der K\xc3\xb6rper wird dadurch nach mehr und mehr Zucker verlangen - und sich vor allem nicht mit dem S\xc3\xbc\xc3\x9fstoff an sich zufrieden geben. S\xc3\xbc\xc3\x9fstoffe bestehen aus einer rein chemischen Verbindung - sind also eher als Chemikalie und weniger als Lebensmittel anzusehen. Darum solltest Du auch Zucker-Alternativen meiden. Es gibt auch nat\xc3\xbcrliche Zucker-Alternativen wie z.B. Stevia. Anders als bei chemischen S\xc3\xbc\xc3\x9fstoffen ist Stevia rein pflanzlich. Am besten isst Du nat\xc3\xbcrlich einfach s\xc3\xbc\xc3\x9fes Obst. Wenn Du aber auf Kalorien verzichten m\xc3\xb6chtest, dann doch lieber Stevia nehmen anstatt chemische Zucker-Ersatzstoffe.

Weitere Tipps f\xc3\xbcr mehr Gesundheit findest Du auf meinem Youtube-Kanal. Gleich abonnieren und keinen weiteren Gesundheits-Tipp oder Fitness-Tipp verpassen. Besuch mich auch auf Facebook unter http://www.facebook.com/esskarl

und auf meiner neuen Homepage unter http://www.KARL-ESS.com

Karl Ess

b'Ejercicios para gluteos y piernas de Pilates Mat para hacer en casa'
Description:
b'- Pilates Mat - Figuras laterales - Prof. Marina Mesina
- Pilates: Fortalece las articulaciones. Permite alcanzar la armon\xc3\xada entre el cuerpo y la mente. Corrige las malas posturas. Mejora la agilidad, la coordinaci\xc3\xb3n, el control, la destreza, el equilibrio corporal y la flexibilidad, 
Estimula la circulaci\xc3\xb3n sangu\xc3\xadnea y el retorno venoso. Desarrolla la concentraci\xc3\xb3n. Modela el cuerpo. Tonifica. Sirve para rehabilitar lesiones.
El m\xc3\xa9todo Pilates es una t\xc3\xa9cnica de movimiento muy completa, trabaja el cuerpo en su totalidad. 
Es una combinaci\xc3\xb3n de movimientos basados en t\xc3\xa9cnicas de gimnasia, yoga, ballet y kinesiolog\xc3\xada..
Trabaja los m\xc3\xbasculos de adentro hacia fuera, contrariamente a lo que sucede con la gimnasia tradicional.
Forma cuerpos longil\xc3\xadneos, esbeltos, flexibles y fuertes por dentro.
Oxigena correctamente con la respiraci\xc3\xb3n tor\xc3\xa1xica lateral.
Puede ser practicado por personas de la tercera edad, embarazadas y gente con problemas f\xc3\xadsicos (Patolog\xc3\xadas).
Es un entrenamiento intenso muy utilizado por los bailarines. 
Mantiene en todo momento el control desde el power-house (faja abdominal y lumbar) hacia las extremidades. 
- La t\xc3\xa9cnica de Pilates Mat b\xc3\xa1sicamente es la misma que Pilates en Camas, en mat se trabaja sobre una colchoneta con la fuerza del propio cuerpo, aunque se pueden incorporar elementos (mancuernas, bandas el\xc3\xa1sticas, pelotas) mientras que en reformer se utiliza una camilla con un sistema de poleas y resortes de distintas intensidades.
Pilates mat se puede realizar en clases grupales, personalizadas o en tu propio hogar.

Title: b'Gym Wreck Volume 1 DVD Trailer'
Description: b"Here's something a little different. A sneak peak preview of a promotional DVD that is being used to raise funds for 3 boxers upcoming trip to two national tournaments in February. The DVD has 1 1/2 hrs of interviews, sparring, training and some recent bouts. One boxer will be traveling to the National Silver Gloves in Independence, Missouri and the two others to the Under-19 Tournament in Cincinnati, Ohio. The winners of the National Silver Gloves become the #1 ranked boxer in the US in their division. It is the only advancing tournament for 10-15 year old other than the Junior Olympics (15/16 year olds). The winners of the Under-19 will represent the US at the Youth World Boxing Championships Baku, Azerbaijan from April 12 25, 2010. That is the only qualifying tournament for the 2010 Youth Olympic Games that will take place in Singapore from August 14 to 26, 2010. \r\n\r\nFor more info on how to support these boxers or getting a DVD made email dcboxing@gmail.com."

Title: b'When to Take Rest Days - With Lee Labrada'
Description:
b'When to Take Rest Days?- With Lee Labrada== FREE 12 WEEK PHYSIQUE TRANSFORMATION PROGRAM :http://www.labrada.com/12weekleanbody 

Ask Lee Q & A #1) http://www.labrada.com/asklee

ALL Labrada supplements here: http://www.labrada.com/store/

Please feel free to ask any questions you may have regarding Fitness or Nutrition and I will be happy to try and answer them. Here's where you can ask.. http://www.labrada.com/asklee

Hi I'm Lee Labrada your lean body coach. If you're like me, you have a passion for working out. And if you've been bitten by the workout bug, you look forward to getting to the gym. 

That's why this weeks question, from Tom Mithson of Los Angeles is timely.

QUESTION: Tom asks, "Lee, I'm confused about taking days off from training. Everybody seems to have a different opinion. Some people say to take a day off once a week, while others say to take two or more days off. What is the right amount?"

ANSWER: Tom, the short answer is: you should take enough days off from training to allow your body to fully recuperate from the workload you're putting on it in the gym. That's going to vary from person to person, and it will depend on factors such as the amount of sleep you're getting, the amount of protein and calories you're consuming each day, and how good your metabolism is.

Here's what you should keep in mind. In the gym, you stress your muscles by putting a load on them with weights, in the hope that you will stimulate them to grow. Outside of the gym, during your rest time, is where your body adapts to that stress, and when muscle repair and growth actually occurs.

I generally like to take a day off from resistance training, after two or three days in the gym. In my 12 week lean body videotrainer, which you'll find on bodybuidling.com, and in my book the lean body promise, I recommend that people train with weights for two days, followed by a day of rest. 

On the day of rest, I encourage people to perform 20 to 30 minutes of cardio. The cardio amounts to active rest, which helps to move your blood around and encourage recovery. 

Fight the urge to skip rest of days. Rest days are needed in order to allow the body to fully recuperate, and most importantly, for your muscles to grow. If you never take a day off, chances are that you will eventually find yourself overtrained.

Being overtrained is like getting a sunburn, it's counterproductive. Muscle tissue gets broken down, but not built back up. You'll know if you're overtraining, if you're constantly achy, and rundown. Extreme overtraining can actually make you sick, and susceptible to catching colds and other bugs easily. 

If you're an older athlete, the rest days become increasingly important, as your ability to recover from exercise may be slower. More is not always better. Some trial and error may be in order, to help you determine the optimal number of days to train before taking a day off.

So remember, even though recovery time depends on your personal needs, after 2-3 days in a row of weight training you'll probably be ready for a day off. Hope this helps. 

I'm Lee Labrada, your lean body coach. Stay lean and stay strong.

Title: b'Sterkste mannen strijden in Kerkrade'
Description:
b"Jarno Hams (37) uit Vroomshoop is zaterdagmiddag op de Markt in Kerkrade voor de zevende keer op rij uitgeroepen tot Sterkste Man van Nederland.

De twaalf sterke mannen streden op zes onderdelen, waaronder het sjouwen met 
'stones of strength', biervaten en verzwaarde tapijten van 100 kilo op een aanhanger 
laden, wandelen met een stalen 'juk' van 420 kilo en boomstammen tillen van 120 tot 
170 kilo zwaar. Winnaar Hams wist vijf van de zes onderdelen op zijn naam te schrijven.

Ondanks dat er af en toe een bui viel, kwamen er gedurende de middag duizenden mensen een kijklje nemen op de Markt in Kerkrade."

Title: b'Clean Variations'
Description:
b'http://www.traintherightway.com
GYMBOSS: http://bit.ly/YCZZU

A request.

Hang Power Cleans
Hang Full Cleans
Power Cleans (from the floor)
Full Cleans (from the floor)
-----
Some simple instructions on the difference between all of these, and lots of examples of the lifts from a side-view, at full-speed and half-speed.

Key points:
1. NEVER "pull" with the arms
2. Once the bar passes the knees, accelerate HARD by straightening up your back and legs as fast as possible - this is NOT an athletic "jumping" movement: it's just standing up as fast as you can
3. This middle portion of the lift should be identical no matter what weight you're using or what variation you're performing

Hang = start with the bar already off the floor. It can be anywhere from mid-shin to knee-height, to mid-thigh to waist-height, depending on your goals
Power = refers to the RECEIVING POSITION, which is with the legs above parallel
Full/Squat = refers to the RECEIVING POSITION, which is in a full squat
From the floor = as it sounds...
Full (also "Squat")'

Title: b'Paradiso CrossFit - Front Lever Progressions'
Description:
b'This is another fundamental gymnastic movement. You can perform this on the rings or a bar. Use an overhand grip (palms away from you) at shoulder width to get more use from your lats.

Gymnastics is all about leverage, so the progressions are based upon how long you make your body. All progressions will have straight arms and try to get the hips level with the shoulders. The progressions are as follows:

-round back/legs tucked into the body
-straight back/legs tucked into the body
-straight back/one leg extended
-straight back/both legs extended in a straddle or V
-straight back/straight legs (ie a legit front lever)'

Title: b'Pump Up Your Arm Size With Range-of-Motion Triple Add Sets'
Description:
b"http://www.thebestarmexercises.com - This unique method will result in a massive pump in your arms. You'll be targeting different aspects of the range of motion of the barbell curls and the pushdown to maximize tension on each muscle fiber type.

You'll start with a very short partial movement in the strongest part of the range for very high reps. This will target the slow twitch fibers.

You'll then rest 10 seconds then do a half-range movement, staying short of the sticking point. Do 6 to 8 reps.

Then you'll rest 10 seconds and finish with 1 to 3 reps in the full range of motion, finishing on maximum tension instead of minimum, as happens with drop sets.

This is a great way to not only pump up, but to also develop mass on the arms."

Title: b'Gym Bloppers.avi'
b'Triathlon/Laufen BalancePad Balance Zirkel mit Celia Kuch'
Description:
b'Wir beschleunigen beim Laufen bei jedem Schritt das Mehrfache unseres K\xc3\xb6rpergewichtes auf unser Standbein (Laufen = Balancieren auf einem Bein). Die Tatsache, dass wir die meiste Zeit des Tages in festem Schuhwerk stecken bereitet unsere F\xc3\xbc\xc3\x9fe nicht wirklich auf laufspezifische Anforderungen vor. Im Gegenteil. Meines Erachtens nach geh\xc3\xb6rt Einbein-/Stabilit\xc3\xa4ts- und Balancetraining - auch unter koordinativen Aspekten - in jedes Athletiktraining. 

Bei den drei dargestellten \xc3\x9cbungen habe ich ein Balance Pad verwendet, dass es f\xc3\xbcr ca 30\xe2\x82\xac zu kaufen gibt. Bei vielen Athletik-Einsteigern ist es mit gro\xc3\x9fer Wahrscheinlichkeit schon Herausforderung genug, die \xc3\x9cbungen auf einem weichen Teppich und barfu\xc3\x9f auszuf\xc3\xbchren :-)

Insgesamt mache ich drei Durchg\xc3\xa4nge mit 1.) Einbeinspr\xc3\xbcngen 10 re/10 li, 2.) Statische Halte\xc3\xbcbung 30-40" re+li; Hierbei ist es wichtig das Bein im Knie und Fu\xc3\x9fgelenk so tief wie m\xc3\xb6glich zu beugen, ohne, dass dabei die Ferse vom Boden abhebt! 3.) Einbeinige Kniebeugen mit einem nach vorne/zur Seite/nach hinten gestreckten (Knie und Fu\xc3\x9f - bis in die Fu\xc3\x9fspitzen - maximal gestreckt) 3/3/3 rechts und 3/3/3 links. Wenn man einen Durchgang mit allen drei \xc3\x9cbungen geschafft hat, f\xc3\xa4ngt man wieder von vorne an :-) Die Pause mache ich nur so lange, bis ich das Gef\xc3\xbchl habe die n\xc3\xa4chste Aufgabe bew\xc3\xa4ltigen zu k\xc3\xb6nnen.

Viel Spass beim \xc3\x9cben und verletzungsfreien Laufen!


Ich freue mich auch \xc3\xbcber jeden Besuch auf meiner Homepage http://www.celiakuch.com/'

Title: b'How to Deadlift properly'
Description:
b'Hi Team,

Glad you are all loving the masterclass videos - we will be putting these out once a week so please let us know what you want to see and have explained. Lots of people are starting the year off with the goal of improving their health and fitness, and obviously we want to make sure you safely maximise your training. 

It is an exercise which you must ensure to get the correct technique or you have the potential to really hurt yourself. As always start with a small weight, that you can lift with perfect technique and then work up, always ensuring that you can still perform correctly with the additional weight. Key points for this exercise are:

Always make sure that your posture is correct: head up, chest up. Weight through your heels and never arch your back.
When lifting remember that it is a lower body exercise, make sure that you feel the weight through your heels. You are not trying to yank the weight up with your upper body.

You can use two different types of grip: one hand over, one hand under. Or both hands on the same side. Personally I prefer to have a mixed grip. 

Have a look at our site for other tips, packages, training products and more!

Title: b'torneo fisico culturismo - fitness en villa alemana chile'
b'How to keep fit in Nigeria - Expensive & Homemade Gyms!'
Description:
b'\xe2\x96\xba Subscribe to BattaBox on YouTube: http://goo.gl/4dgy2r

(Nigeria Fitness) Locally made body building equipments produced from concrete, iron, car-wheels etc in a local gym, OR correct foreign made treadmills in a lush gym - which would you prefer? 

Our "Big Boy" Presenter - Olukayode heads to the gym in Nigeria to find out how to get fit... either in the expensive, professional gym or the home-made gym!

"Keeping fit is not only exercise," said Olaoluwa, a gym instructor at one of the high-end gyms in Lagos, as he shows kayode how to punch bags.

One of the main advantages of using a gym is the encouragement from trainers and friends - as Kayode wonders if people who have such equipment in their houses can manage their routine well enough without an instructor.

"They can't do it, because they get tired. When you come to the gym, you have other people that would motivate you, that is why every gym has an instructor," Olaoluwa explains.

"There are things I can't do before, but now I can do them, I can sleep well," says one woman one an exercise bike.

Olaoluwa explains to us that exercises like push- ups and sit-ups could also be done manually without using a machine - "if you're working on your tummy, you should always remember your sides and waistline," he adds with demonstrations.

Kayode then proceeds to try one of the machines... with exhausting results!

So he heads out to a "Made-In-Nigeria" gym, unsurprisingly, by the roadside! (oh BattaBox style!)

"We make our equipments, the dumbbells are made from concrete and we cover them with pipe," said the local gym instructor.

One of the advantages of this type of gym is that it's very cheap.

"It's just N2000 a month, and the money is just for maintenance of the equipments and for the space we're using," says the instructor.

"We don't charge much because everything here is hand-made, moreover we want to encourage people it's good for the health," he added.

Battabox viewers, watch out for Kayode's heavy chests and muscles in 3 months!! (Nigeria Fitness)

Title: b'Como Tonificar Los M\xc3\xbasculos. Entrenamiento De Pectorales.'
Description:
b'http://tinyurl.com/musculos84

Como Tonificar Los M\xc3\xbasculos. Entrenamiento De Pectorales.

PRESS EN BANCO PLANO

M\xc3\xbasculos a desarrollar: Pectoral Mayor y Menor.
\xe2\x80\xa2 Recostarse en el banco y apoyar los pies en el suelo. Si la espalda se arquea y se despegan las v\xc3\xa9rtebras lumbares del banco, se aconseja elevar los pies y apoyar los talones sobre el banco.
\xe2\x80\xa2 El agarre de la barra debe ser m\xc3\xa1s ancho que el ancho de los hombros
\xe2\x80\xa2 La barra descender\xc3\xa1 hasta tocar el pecho a la altura del pecho.
Observaciones: si la barra va a la altura del cuello, se produce mayor congesti\xc3\xb3n, pero se deber\xc3\xa1 tener mucha precauci\xc3\xb3n en este caso.

Variantes.
Press 45\xc2\xba o Press Inclinado
Trabaja las fibras superiores del Pectoral.
La barra baja hasta la altura de las clav\xc3\xadculas
Press Declinado o Invertido
Trabaja las fibras inferiores del Pectoral
La barra baja a la altura del pecho

AGARRE ESTRECHO.
Trabaja las fibras internas del pectoral, es decir la zona pr\xc3\xb3xima al estern\xc3\xb3n.
Press con Mancuernas
M\xc3\xbasculos a desarrollar: Pectoral Mayor y Menor.
\xe2\x80\xa2 Recostarse en el banco con los pies apoyados en el suelo. Si la espalda se arquea, se aconseja elevar los pies y apoyar los talones sobre el banco
\xe2\x80\xa2 Con las mancuernas se deben hacer los mismo movimientos que con la barra, bajarlas o a la altura de los hombros y subirlas hasta juntarlas en lo alto, con brazos extendidos.
Observaciones: Es necesario mayor equilibrio, por lo tanto se aconseja no realizarlo con altas cargas en el periodo de aprendizaje de este ejercicio

Variantes
Con una sola mancuerna
Para deportes que solo requieran el entrenamiento de un solo miembro, ejemplo tenis, en este caso es necesario un compa\xc3\xb1ero que sostenga al ejecutante de un lado ya que de lo contrario el sobrepeso nos tumbar\xc3\xada.

APERTURAS
M\xc3\xbasculos a desarrollas: Pectoral Mayor y Menor.
\xe2\x80\xa2 Descenderemos las mancuernas hacia los costados lo m\xc3\xa1s abajo posible, con los brazos extendidos.
\xe2\x80\xa2 Solo se puede ejercer una ligera flexi\xc3\xb3n del codo para que se produzcan lesiones en el mismo.
\xe2\x80\xa2 Las palmas ir\xc3\xa1n enfrentadas.'

Title: b'White or Wheat Bread Which is Better for You?'
Description:
b"Well, to start off that question, I want to answer it from the beginning. Straight from the beginning, I want to give you an answer. Neither are healthier for you. Both of them cause inflammation which, in turn, causes chronic diseases. That's how simple it is.

But, this is what their claim to fame is. This is what they're saying to you. The reason white bread is so much more unhealthy than wheat bread is because there's no fiber in it. 

Well, that's true. It really is, because there's no fiber in it. All the starches and, obviously, it's processed more and all that, the sugar that's in there and the fats are absorbed at a higher capacity.
Now, when it comes to wheat bread, because it has the husk over the wheat, there's less absorption because the wheat, when it goes into the intestinal tract, the wheat may not fall off the grain and, in turn, it passes right through you.

But, there are starches there. That hasn't changed a bit. The starches are still in the wheat bread. The starches are still in the white bread. Both of the starches are very unhealthy to you. There is no difference here.

So, for them to say that wheat bread is healthy, it is an absolute lie. It isn't healthy. It causes inflammation which, in turn, breaks down your immune system which, in turn, allows you to get sick. Both of them do. Not just white bread. Wheat bread does the same thing.

So, don't believe them. The fact of the matter is that wheat or white, you're going to get inflammation, you just might get a little bit more from white bread. But, you're still going to get inflammation. 

So, that's the myth. And that's the truth. Don't eat white bread or wheat bread. Eat green vegetables and eat fruits. Eat the human diet. It's going to work out for you. It works for me."

Title: b'Lunge on the Pilates Reformer for Release of Tight Hip Flexors, Core Strength, and a Long Spine'
Description:
b"https://feetforfitness.com/hips/kneepain-relief-hip-joints-mobility.html

An effective knee-down lunge is very different from an extended-back-leg runner's stretch and with the knee making contact with a surface it is much easier to align the heel effectively so that you are not pushing abusively on the thigh muscles or hip flexors, but are able to deepen the femur into the hip joint. The back heel is absolutely key to being able to stretch deeply - not just a release of hip flexor muscle tightening, but better core support for the spine. 

Here you will witness that the woman does not extend the leg back behind her - she uses her back heel and the toes of the back foot to leverage a deepening thigh bone into the hip joint.

This deepening of the femur bone into the joint releases the tightness of the hip flexor, as well as the tightness of the ITB or ilio tibial band which can cause hip pain or knee pain.

In addition, she is able to lengthen both her lumbar spine and her thoracic and cervical spine because she is upright, and not hunched over as she would be in a typical runner's stretch.

If the stretch is performed very slowly and mindfully, the ease of having the knee down rather than the potential strain of when it is extended will allow the time and focus to even the hips. Even though one foot is forward and one is back - even though the front leg is angle upwards and the back leg is angled back, she can still even out the expansion of the two heels, and the even deepening of each femur into their respective hip sockets. This is the key, because if all the pairs of parts are even - heels and femurs - and the it will create evenness between the two halves of the pelvis or the two hip joints or sockets - then what's between the two hip halves, which is the sacrum - can receive the extension of the lumbar spine in an arcing length out the tail bone. Thus, this is not merely a hip flexor stretch or tight hip joint release. The stretch is actually is a lumbar spine extension, which when combined with the activation of inner thighs which have a relationship to the psoas where they junction on the lesser trochanters, becomes a core strengthening stretch because the tighter part of the psoas which is more hip flexor lets go so that the part of the psoas which is attached to the lumbar vertebrae becomes supportive.

Title: b'Legs of Steel Workout'
Description:
b"Ready for another Angry Trainer workout? Well this one's all about the legs!

There's a reason why many people skip leg training -- it's dang hard and requires a lot of effort. But in my experience nothing is as rewarding as the sense of accomplishment after a great legs session.

But be warned - this is no ordinary leg workout. I've included just about every mode of exercise possible to really emphasize functionality and effectiveness. We've got jumps, moves that target normally weak and deconditioned areas, a little balance and even some super slow reps to tap the endurance muscle fibers. If you want a strong base of support for all of your activities, give this workout a go!

Here's the program:

The Legs Of Steel Workout

All x 5 reps, performed in succession with no rest between

1. Jump Squat

2. Alternate Reverse Lunge

3. Skater Lunge -- both ways

4. Lateral Lunge

5. One Legged Squat

6. One Legged Deadlift

7. One Legged Jump

8. SUPER SLOW 1 \xc2\xbc SQUATS

9. Rest 30 seconds

Repeat for THREE circuits

If you look closely you'll notice each exercise is just 5 reps, but there are 8 movements, so you'll be getting 40 reps in total during this non-stop circuit. I want you to try running through this circuit 3 times for a whole month, adding an additional circuit each week! Let me know how you like it.

As always, don't forget to check out rest of my FREE workout videos on my Angry Trainer Fitness You Tube channel -- become a subscriber AND spread the word to your friends!

Here's the recipe to make your very own High Protein Pumpkin Bars: 

Ingredients:
- 4 egg whites
- 3/4 cup pumpkin
- 1 tsp vanilla extract
- 2 tbs maple syrup
- 2 tbs of stevia, or sweetner of choice
- 1/4 cup oat bran
- 2 scoops of protein powder
- 1/2 tsp of cinnamon
- 2 tsp of pumpkin pie spice
- 1/4 tsp baking powder
- 1/4 cup pecans or walnuts

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 350 F.

2. In one bowl, mix the egg whites, pumpkin, vanilla extract, and maple syrup.

3. In another small bowl whisk the stevia, oat bran, protein powder, and all the spices along with the baking powder.

4. Now add this to the wet ingredients plus nuts and stir well. 

5. Pour mixture into a baking loaf pan (or can use a muffin tin) coated with cooking spray.

6. Bake about 20-25 minutes or until a tooth pick comes out dry. 

Enjoy!


Nutrition Facts:
SERVING SIZE: 1 Serving (45 grams) or (1 small square)
Calories 60
Fat 3 grams
Carbs 9 grams 
Protein 6 grams 
Fiber 1.5 grams
Sugar 5 grams'

Title: b'Working same muscle groups two days in a row'
Description:
b"http://LegendaryStrength.com - Is it a good idea to train same muscle groups two days in a row? The answers is Yes and No, as it all depends on the way you do it. 

Personally I do that all the time - even with deadlifts where I regularly hit new PR's. The idea of training divided into muscle groups/body parts is something I am not a big fan of. The last time I trained like this was over 10 years ago. Most bodybuilders work their chest one day, arms the other etc. If you think about it, you are actually working your arms on chest day to some degree, so you are basically training the same muscle group two days in a row. 

However, if you push your limits and overdo training of certain muscle group in terms of volume and intensity, you are likely to get sore and shouldn't really train that same group a day after day. In fact, this kind of training could lead to injuries and negative effect on your results, so you have to be careful not to over-train. 

Having said that, you still can train same muscle groups every day, but the volume and intensity need to be tuned down. This way, you are actually working on the skill of the particular movement and trying to get better at it each day.

Title: b'CrossFit "OPEN 15.2" WOD Demo [Highlights]'
Description:
b'"Open 15.2": http://wodwell.com/wod/open-15-2/ (183 reps)
SUBSCRIBE: http://wodwell.co/yt_sub

Zach and Stephanie scored 183 reps and 35 reps, respectively, in CrossFit Games Open workout "15.2." Zach recently re-tested the workout recently and knew what he was shooting for. Stephanie had a strategy to chip away at the chest-to-bars, but went out hotter and burned out sooner than she had planned. They did the workout together at their home box right after the official WOD announcement (Open 15.2 is a repeat of Open 14.2), then talked to us about their tips, strategies and lessons learned afterward.

"OPEN 15.2"
http://wodwell.com/wod/open-15-2/
For as Long as Possible Complete:
From 0:00-3:00, 2 rounds of:
10 Overhead Squats (95/65lbs)
10 Chest-to-Bar Pull-Ups
From 3:00-6:00, 2 rounds of:
12 Overhead Squats (95/65lbs)
12 Chest-to-Bar pull-ups
From 6:00-9:00, 2 rounds of:
14 Overhead Squats (95/65lbs)
14 Chest-to-Bar Pull-Ups
Follow the pattern until you fail to complete both rounds.

Title: b'5 Yoga Poses to Strengthen your Back'
Description:
b'Here are 5 back yoga exercises that help prevent back pain, eliminate back fat and strengthen the condition of your back. Practice daily or at least 3-4 times a week for best results.

1. Cat-Cow Variation \xe2\x80\x93 Reduces stiffness in the back and hips and relieves tension in the spine. 

Cow Pose \xe2\x80\x93 On your hands and knees, inhale and lift your head while making your back concave.

Cat Pose \xe2\x80\x93 On your exhale; tuck your tailbone, contract abs, and round your back, head down.

Child\xe2\x80\x99s Pose \xe2\x80\x93 Draw your hips back to your heels, drop chest, rounding spine, and rest your forehead on the floor with your arms in front of you. Do 6 reps of the whole cycle. Rest in Child\xe2\x80\x99s Pose for several breaths.

2. Bridge Pose \xe2\x80\x93 Stretches the abs, hips, quads, lower back and strengthens the abs.

-Lie face up with your feet on the floor about 6 inches from your butt with arms by sides, palms down.
-Inhaling, press into your feet and lift your lower body until your knees form a diagonal with your head. 
-As you exhale, contract your abs and slowly lower your spine.
-Do 6 reps.

3. Extended Leg Pose \xe2\x80\x93 Stretches the hamstrings & strengthens the abs.

-Lie face up with your knees bent, feet on the floor, and take 3 breaths.
-A. Exhale and hug left knee to your chest.
-B. Inhaling, extend left leg over hip. Exhaling, hug it in. Do 3 reps.
-Hug knee in, then lower your foot. Switch sides and repeat.
-Exhale and hug both knees to chest for 3 breaths.

4. Butterfly Pose \xe2\x80\x93 Tones abs, pelvic floor and inner thighs.
- A. Lie faceup with your soles of feet together, knees open to the sides. Inhale.
- B. Exhale and slowly squeeze thighs together. Do 6 reps.
- Do 6 more times, taking twice as long to bring your thighs together.

5. Cobra Leg Lift \xe2\x80\x93 Strengthens the back and pelvic muscles.

-Lie facedown with your elbows by your sides and hands by your shoulders.
-Rest forehead on the floor with your chin tucked slightly.
-Inhale and lift your chest using your back muscles.
-At the same time, lift your right leg as high as you can while keeping your pelvis level.
-Hold, then exhale to lower.
-Switch sides and repeat.
-Do 6 reps, alternating sides, lifting your leg a little higher each time.

Title: b'Pilates Moves - Swimming Exercise'
Description: b"How to Do Pilates Swimming Exercise - part of the women's fitness video series by GeoBeats.\n \nHello, we're Katherine and Kimberly Corp. We own Pilates on Fifth in New York City, and we would like to show you the Pilates exercise, Swimming. It's a great exercise for strengthening the muscles of the back. A lot of the things we do we're working on our vanity muscles, the muscles we can see in the mirror. And you have all sorts of muscles in your back that will keep you upright, we're homo-erectus after all. Anyway she's going to lie on her stomach to begin. Her arms are out stretched overhead and the legs are going to be slightly apart, a little bit wider then hip distance but not as wide as your shoulders. And then you're going to ever so slightly rotate your knees to face the outside a smidgeon. I'm going to start this exercise slowly just to teach the movement, and then we'll go to go into the full exercise. So, of course, of course, of course, you're pulling your abdominal muscles in and out so that that deepest layer of abdominals is working all the time. So first we're going to have her do is just do one arm and one leg at a time, nice and slow. So on the exhale she's going to lift her right arm and left leg, and extend the spine slightly. So exhale and inhale coming down, and now opposite left arm, right leg. Exhale lift, and I'm going to go ahead and teach the neck placement now, so we don't have to do while she's working. I'm moving her pony tail, you don't want to do one leg take your neck into too much extension. So think of just keeping your gaze at a normal spot and not taxing the neck there. Ok, so that's the movement very broken down, now we're going to the full swimming exercise. So she's going to inhale, think of lengthening out at the top of the head and tips of the toes. Now she's going to exhale lifting up, so she's lifting her legs off the mat and lifting her torso off the mat, and here we go. So she will inhale 2, 3, 4, 5 and exhale 2, 3, 4, 5, keep going 2, 3, 4, 5, and exhale. So because this is counter lateral movement, meaning the arms and legs are doing opposite things in the right and left side they're doing different things, the deep deep muscles in the have to work even harder and that's a good thing. It increases core strength. And we'll just do 2 more sets, and exhale 2, 3, 4, 5. Last set pulling the abs in 4, 5 and exhale 2, 3, 4, 5. As the last you are you're lengthening everything and then exhale coming down. So all the muscles in the back line of the body are targeted in Swimming. And we're going to have her press back and just relax everything. And there you have it."

Slow Push-ups (or planks): 40 seconds
rest 20 seconds
One-Leg Bridge (or bridge): 40 seconds
rest 20 seconds
Side Planks (or side planks on knees): 40 seconds
rest 20 seconds
One-Leg Squats (or squats): 40 seconds
rest one minute

REPEAT FOUR TIMES

I always warm up for about six or seven minutes first and cool down and stretch afterwards for about six or seven minutes.

Experimenta el Tango desde el centro, la respiraci\xc3\xb3n y la fluidez

Paula Pantano (Bailarina -- Lic. en Composicion Coreagrafica y Master Internacional de Pilates) junto a su pareja Pablo Lezcano (Bailarin en distintas disiplinas e Instructor de Pilates).
A partir de su experiencia como bailarines de Tango e instructores de Pilates notaron el importante aporte que el Metodo Pilates brinda a esta danza, gracias a la conciencia corporal que desarrolla con respecto a la alineacion, el centro, la disociacion, el equilibrio, la precision sin perder la fluidez del movimiento.

Title: b'How To Do Human Overhead Squats'
Description:
b"Human overhead squats take all the demanding core and shoulder elements of traditional barbell overhead squats, but trade predictable metal for a squirming, uneven, hard-to-stabilize human.

The benefits of doing any kind of overhead squats are numerous. 

They help you develop amazing shoulder stability and midline stabilization, which carries over to all kinds of other athletic pursuits. 

They do this by punishing squat weakness and and stability issues. If you can keep the weight perfectly still overhead, you'll have no problems holding it. But because you're moving around and compensating, the weight rocks, which can send it crashing to the ground if you're not capable of compensating. 

But human overhead squats take things to the next level. Even with the most stable partner, her weight will be unevenly distributed between your hands, and she'll rock as you move. 

In this video I show you how to get into a human overhead squat, and how to do one."

Title: b'Workout 20 minutes a day - 3 times per week'
Description:
b'Download Your FREE 12 Week Workout Program at:
http://www.leehayward.com/12-week-workout-program/index.htm

Friend Me Up On Facebook at:
http://www.facebook.com/total.fitness.bodybuilding

Check out my Bodybuilding Blog at:
http://leehayward.com/blog

Join the Total Fitness Bodybuilding "Inner Circle" Coaching Club at:
http://www.TotalFitnessBodybuilding.com

We've all seen those late night TV infomercials claiming that all it takes to get in killer shape is to workout 20 minutes a day, just 3 times per week. Then they feature a top level bodybuilder, fitness model, or athlete working out on what ever home gym gizmo they are promoting.

Do you really think that the model who is shown in the advertisement really got in the shape they are in by working out for just "20 minutes a day, 3 times per week" ?

I can tell you right up the answer is NO Friggen Way!

From my personal experience with working with bodybuilders, fitness and figure competitors, and athletes in general a conservative average for someone who is training to get in peak physical condition will workout for 2 hours per day. This is usually about 1 hour of cardio and 1 hour of weight training at least 4 days per week.

Again this is a "conservative average" because I know many physique competitors who will train A LOT MORE than this in order to get in top shape.

So the next time you hear the marketing claim of say that you can get a chiseled chest, ripped abs, pumped arms, and powerful legs in just 20 minutes a day, 3 times per week... Realize that it takes more work than that.

Now in the defense of the TV Infomercial folks, for someone who is brand new to exercise, doing 20 minute workouts that would be a fantastic place to start. However, as they build up their conditioning and work capacity they will quickly plateau with such a low volume of training and within the matter of weeks will have to bump things up to a higher level of training intensity and volume in order to continue making progress. Especially if they hope to get to the level of the fitness models featured in the advertisements.'

Title: b'Raw Whey Protein: Unparalleled Quality, Bio-Availability'
Description:
b'http://facelessfatloss.com/rawwheyprotein For much more information on this incredible new protein technology, click the link. I will cover this topic in greater detail, perhaps in my next video.

I love this product. Protein supplementation remains undervalued. The quality of the protein in so many of our food sources almost never matches that of a pure, clean, whey supplement such as this one. Your body recognizes this form of protein instantly, and makes use of it in all sorts of beneficial ways that go "whey" beyond that of merely muscle recovery and building.

Whey comes from cow milk. My main focus in this video is on the source of the milk for this specific whey product, and how it is made. This whey is among the very few in existence that is NOT pasteurized. This benefits us HUGELY. We now know that pasteurization of milk destroys the enzyme content of the milk, as well as the protein! This COMPLETELY defeats the purpose of taking in supplemental protein! How can the body benefit from a protein source, when that protein source has been exposed to heat sources far above and beyond any it could ever naturally experience on its own? Heat destroys. Low-to-no heat is "the" new means of food production that is proving to be far more beneficial, in helping to maintain the nutritional content of our foods.

If the enzymes in the food are tampered with...and in turn the protein in the food is tampered with...creating who-knows what kind of end result...HOW will the body "read" the food, absorb, and make use of it?

Some theories are even suggesting that these broken enzymes and amino acids could be doing us more harm than good. After all, when, during any natural cycle of events, is a food exposed to such high heat conditions, other than those conditions that happen artificially via man's intervention?

More soon on this topic.

Love, Happiness, Health and Peace...............Tim'

Title: b'High Reps VS Low Reps For Building Muscle With Hugo & Rodzilla'
Description:
b'http://www.HugoRivera.net - High Reps VS Low Reps For Building Muscle With Hugo & Rodzilla | Rodney (aka Rodzilla) & Hugo discuss whether high reps or low reps are better for building muscle.

It is best to use both high reps and low reps in order to build muscle optimally. So basically you use periodization in which should do loading phases (3-4 weeks) in which you do higher reps (10-15 reps...sometimes going as high as 20-30 reps). Research indicates that you do get hypertrophy even at the higher rep ranges. And then you should do a Growth Phase in which you cut down on the volume (limiting sets to 10 total per body part; example: 4 sets of exercise #1 and then 3 sets for exercises #2 and #3) and then in terms of reps 5-8 reps. 

Keep in mind that you need to change your routines in order to keep the results coming. By following periodization principles, you will be able to avoid overtraining. Try to finish your workouts within 60 minutes in order to keep your testosterone levels high and cortisol levels low. That, combined with proper form and muscle tension will give you the best results possible. 

Click here for a sample periodized routine: http://www.hugorivera.net/natural-bodybuilding-routine-with-periodization.html

Hope that this bodybuilding tip helps. Please let me know what other tips you would like us to talk about.

Daniel Puder, born on October 9, 1981, first made a name for himself in high school. Puder finished first place in his weight division in the Central Coast Section amateur wrestling. He accomplished this while wrestling with a broken hand. The wrestling mat wasn't the only location where Puder began demonstrating success despite the odds. As a high school student, he began his entrepreneurial career by starting several successful businesses.

Puder has never been one to settle for average in anything he does. He sought out the tutelage of MMA amateur wrestling legends Frank Shamrock, Brian Johnston, Danny Chaid, and trained at the American Kick Boxing Academy in San Jose until 2008 when Puder moved to Los Angeles and started training under the TOP MMA Heavy weight coach, Eric Paulson.

Whether it's in a business meeting or in the ring, Puder has the same attitude: Success, Heart, and Improve. He has MMA competition records of 8-0 (PRO) and 20-0 (amateur). Puder gained enormous momentum when he nearly made 1996 Olympic Gold Medalist Kurt Angle tap out on national television.
 
In October 2004 through 2006, Puder was selected from thousands of applicants to compete in World Wrestling Entertainment's first-ever $1,000,000 Tough Enough Challenge on Smack Down on UPN. The national and international TV exposure got Puder to where he wanted to be. Puder WON $1,000,000 Tough Enough and then went back to Mixed Martial Arts. In 2006, Puder started fighting and won 3 fights. He was very successful and received numerous articles and was featured on many TV and radio shows. In 2007, Puder continued to win 2 more fights. He started to earn recognition on the front pages and sports sections of many newspapers, and also was seen on KRON, FOX SPORTS, and NBC.
In 2008 Puder produced a HUGE event for Cops Care Cancer Foundation in Los Angeles, moved to Los Angeles, and joined CWS for his official fight team.

In 2009 Puder launch a new company www.fight5.com, won his 8th fight, Is getting 40,000 viewers on him name value each day, Launching his own Fight League and 5 more Youtube.com shows, Earned a 4 page spread in Mens Fitness, was on 2 more TV shows, and added 2 more charities to the Family of helping!! Puder is now living in Los Angeles and balances his extreme training schedule with one of his other passions: giving youth the opportunity to excel. Puder started his first charity when he was 19 years old and now is involved with HAWKE FOUNDATION, Toys for Tots, Stanford and San Francisco Hospital, After School All Stars, and Cops Care Cancer Foundation, San Jose Police Athletic League (PAL), Puder Strength Training, Shiners hospital, Clays for Kids and many others. No matter how busy his schedule is, he never runs out of time for others who need the attention the most. At age 28, Puder already looks to the future. Puders goals for 2010 are high as he looks to gain more exposure in his 28th year than any previous year.

INTRODUCTION TO THE FOAM ROLLER

A foam roller is simply a cylindrical piece of hard-celled foam. Basically, you just use your own body weight to sandwich the roller between the body's soft tissue and the floor. The Foam is used to stretch areas that are hard to stretch and massage.

The foam roller not only stretches muscles and tendons but it also breaks down soft tissue adhesions and scar tissue. This is called myofascial release. By using your own body weight and a cylindrical foam roller you can perform a self-massage or myofascial release, break up trigger points, and soothe tight fascia while increasing blood flow and circulation to the soft tissues. 

Your body weight provides all the pressure that you need to roll out pain, stiffness and even adhesions, or areas where connective tissue adheres to the bones.

The superficial fascia is a soft connective tissue located just below the skin. It wraps and connects the muscles, bones, nerves and blood vessels of the body. Together, muscle and fascia make the myofascia system. 

Foam rolling can provide great benefit both before and after a workout. Whether you are getting ready to perform a Spartacus Workout or stretching routine it very important that you take the time to foam roll before you do that. So always foam roll before you stretch. 

Rolling after a workout may help speed up the recovery process so the next time you work out you feel fresh and ready to go.

FOAM ROLLER ROUTINE #1

Perform this routine before your training session or workout. Set your Gymboss Timer to 30 seconds with 10 sec transition time. Go through 1-2 rounds myofascial release.

(The goal is to roll over the specific tight muscle and with hold the position or slightly roll over the tight muscle. Like Stretching, foam rolling is NOT supposed to be painful, so ease up on the amount of pressure if it begins to get to painful. You may need a few rounds on a really tight muscle)

Title: b'Back Strengthening Exercises For Hockey Players'
Description:
b"Did you know that the right upper body training can help you skate faster? Hockey strength and conditioning specialist Maria Mountain of http://www.HockeyTrainingPro.com tells you why.

The Worst Pulling Exercise You Can Do In The Gym...And What to Do Instead

When you think of your 'skating' muscles, your mid-back probably is not the first body part that springs to mind, but they actually do add more force to each stride.

Do this, the next time you are on the ice, go stand on one goal line and then skate as fast as you can to the far blue line without using your arms at all -- keep them pinned right down to your sides.

Now, repeat the same drill, but think about driving your arms powerfully forward and back. There is a huge difference isn't there? So you can see how if we build up those mid-back pulling muscles we can actually improve your skating speed.

The reason your arms help your legs is explained in the video below, but basically the connective tissue from your mid-back through to your hip extensors is integrated, so putting tension in that system from your arms, will increase the tension and the subsequent force production in the legs.

Like stretching an elastic band -- the more you can stretch it, the more it is going to snap back.
Stop Doing THIS...

If you have ever used the Seated Row Machine (the one with the pad in front where you rest your chest as you pull with your arms), please stop! This is the same as using the Leg Press to build your legs.

Although the Seated Row, might let you lift more weight because your back is supported by the chest pad -- you do not have to stabilize your torso at all, so you can teach those muscles to produce force, without having any clue how to stabilize that force or work in an integrated fashion with the rest of the muscles in the chain.
Do THIS Instead...

I have a strong preference for DB or Cable Rows for a horizontal pull and for Pull Ups/Chin Up variations for vertical pulls. Here are a few that you can try...

 Plank Position Row -- like a core plank combined with a row.
 Contra DB Row -- works your glutes and your mid-back muscles at the same time while requiring balance and stabilization. That sounds like hockey.
 Staggered Cable Row -- requires the use of your hips and back extensors to maintain a stable torso as you row.
 Body Row (or Towel Grip Body Row) -- mid-back, back extensors and hip extensors all work together with this awesome bodyweight variation. Your grip strength will get a workout too.

The exact number of sets and reps will vary based on the phase of your training, so it is tough to say, but if I were going to give you a general rep range -- 8-12 for 3 sets is where I would start.

Title: b'5s Week Deadlift & Olympic Squat Workout Ben Rice Universal Nutrition BW 203 5 9 11.mp4'
Description:
b"Planned on taking today off but realized that I will be in seattle all day tomorrow helping a friend with an elaborate proposal so I had to deadlift today instead. I was a little stiff from yesterdays pretty high volumed bench session but I made it through and got some nice PRs.

Deads
135x2/2
225x2/2
315x2/2
405x1
445x5
add belt and chalk
515x5
590x8 (5 lb 8 rep PR, might've had 9 but I might've passed out too haha)

add 3 chains (60 lbs)
pause deads (70 sec rests)
425+60x3x3
remove belt
speed pulls (70 sec rests)
425+60x3x3

Oly squats (gonna run these as a 5/3/1 on my deadlift days after pulls to add extra squat volume and frequency to try and bring up my squat/dead imbalance)
all sets were knee sleeved
225x5
300x5
add belt
355x5
405x9 (was pleasantly suprised considering that these were all as low as I could take em and I had already pulled 590x8 and done my pause and speed pulls)

BB lunges (my knees have always prevented me from being able to do these, but thanks to my new knee sleeves I can do them)

135x7/7
185x5/5
225x5/5 (these were pretty rough so you know I'll be keeping them around for awhile and I'll set a goal right now 315x5 for each leg by my october meet)

Concentric GMs Stopped doing these a few years ago because of my shoulder but I decided to give em a shot. I'm either stricter with them now or my back was jus absolutely fried because they were sooooo much harder than I remember them being)
135x10
225x7
315x3 (just plain tired at this point)

Mini farmers walk (had about 10 feet to play with because the gym was so packed.... these were just an introductory attempt
210x10 feet with 3 slo-mo alternating turns and a hold at the end

figured I had thouroghly beaten my body up and called it at that. Some really positive take aways from the workout were the realization that I can start adding back in some of my favorite training movements that I had cut out due to nagging injuries. I was really happy with the 5 lb PR on the deads especially considering how unprepared I felt to pull today and changing up the program and adding the olympic squats to my routine was much less total body destruction than I had anticipated and so I am overall very very excited to see what comes out of this new settup. I love the knee sleeves and am so incredibly happy that I made the investment. I don't feel like I get much aid from the spring in the sleeves themselves but the support and protection they proved allows me to focus more on the movement and less on the pain in my knee and so my sets are stronger regardless. All in all a good day. Tomorrow will be a settle adventure and then back to the grind on wednesday with military and Close grip bench 5s day. P.S. I'm still waiting to get the pics from last tuesdays session back from Kyle. He assures me they shall be epic and so my expectations are high, and as promised they will be posted as soon as he releases them..."

Title: b'Triathlon Training: How to Improve Your Freestyle Swim - Part 5'
Description:
b"In Triathlon Training: How to Improve Your Freestyle Swim technique training video series, Coach Karlyn Pipes demonstrates the essentials needed to develop an efficient, powerful Freestyle swim, including use of the Vasa Swim Ergometer swim training system.

Coach Pipes shows how to exit your stroke to achieve a high elbow catch (aka EVF or Early Vertical Forearm) to generate more power and efficient swimming. Sustaining the high elbow catch is critical for accessing the powerful muscles of the lats and upper back throughout a race of any distance, while reducing overload to the shoulders and biceps tendon. Todays best swim coaches, swimmers, and triathletes master the High Elbow Catch by practicing it perfectly on the Vasa Swim Ergometer and the Vasa Trainer swim bench, then integrate that efficient technique to swimming in the water.

Karlyn Pipes of AquaticEdge.org, provides swim technique clinics world wide. She holds over 200 Masters Swimming World Records. 

Since 1988, Vasa has produced premium quality exercise training equipment for sports, fitness and rehabilitation. For decades, World Champion Professionals, Olympians, and amateur swimmers, swim coaches, triathletes, triathlon coaches, Physical Therapists, doctors and conditioning coaches worldwide have selected the Vasa Trainer and Vasa Ergometer to dramatically improve performance for swimmers, Ironman triathletes, surfers, SUP paddlers, kayakers, nordic skiers, and those seeking total-body fitness. Title: b'My Home Gym self build project pt 34 (painted wall, ceiling, custom lighting and mirrors)'
Description:
b"Painted all the walls and ceiling. Had intended to put spot lights in the interior, but forgot to create space before i installed the roof deck, was left with no option but to custom build the interior lights out of bits of wood and laminate. Will seal the floor and laminate. Installed the tv and games units.

You too can build your own home gym at the bottom of your garden. I was fed-up with exercising in my old, freezing, damp, insect infested garage. So i bit the bullet and decided to get rid of it and have a home gym built in it's place. 

I'm a complete novice in the building game. My achievements or skills before taking on this task - out of sheer desperation - was that i had done the odd bit of DIY in the past, like putting up a shelf, or hanging a picture. All the skills i picked up throughout this journey were mainly thanks to being let down by builders, a little belief, a touch of determination and a shed load of desperation, but most of all, from watching YouTube clips like this journey which I've catalogued. 

Sure i made many mistakes along the way, the build isn't perfect and yeah, if i had my time again there's many things i'd do differently along the way, but my mantra in life which helps me through anything i wish to achieve is to always say to yourself when, not if and you'll find that you can achieve things way beyond yours, or anyone else's expectations. :)"

These Protein Valentine Brownie Cupcakes are exactly what Cupid would call for (he works out all day). Delicious, low in sugar, and high in fiber + protein!

Here is the Brownie Cupcakes recipe:

1 Teaspoon Ground Cinnamon
4 Tablespoons (28g) Coconut Flour
1/2 Cup (40g) Rolled Oats
3 Scoops (90g) Chocolate Protein Powder
1/4 Cup Sweetener
2 Tablespoons (10g) Cocoa Powder
1/2 Teaspoon Salt
1/2 Teaspoon Baking Powder
1/2 Teaspoon Baking Soda
1/4 Cup (61g) Unsweetened Apple Sauce
1 Medium Avocado
1 Teaspoon Vanilla Extract
1 Tablespoon (21g) Honey
2 Large Eggs
2 Large Egg Whites
1 Tablespoon (15g) Sugar Free Chocolate Chips

Here is the recipe for the Frosting:

2 Ounces (56g) Fat Free Cream Cheese
1 Tablespoon Sweetener
1/2 Scoop (15g) Vanilla Protein Powder
2.65 Ounces (75g) Fat Free Vanilla Greek Yogurt
Couple Drops Red Food Coloring (Optional)

Calories in the WHOLE recipe w/ Frosting:

Calories: 1436
Fat: 52g
Saturated Fat: 14g
Sodium: 1433mg
Carbs: 103g
Fiber: 35g
Sugar: 38g
Protein: 139g

Calories in each Cupcake w/ Frosting (if you make 12):

Calories: 110
Fat: 4.3g
Saturated Fat: 1.2g
Sodium: 119.4mg
Carbs: 8.6g
Fiber: 2.9g
Sugar: 3.2g
Protein: 11.6g

Calories in the WHOLE recipe w/out Frosting:

Calories: 1217
Fat: 51g
Saturated Fat: 14g
Sodium: 906mg
Carbs: 91g
Fiber: 32g
Sugar: 32g
Protein: 112g

Calories in each Cupcake w/out Frosting (if you make 12):

Calories: 106
Fat: 4.2g
Saturated Fat: 1.2g
Sodium: 75.5mg
Carbs: 7.6g
Fiber: 2.7g
Sugar: 2.7g
Protein: 9.3g

Combine all of your dry ingredients for your Brownie Cupcakes recipe into a bowl. Mix them together. Combine all of your wet ingredients (aside from your Chocolate Chips) for your Brownie Cupcakes recipe into another bowl. Mix them together. Slowly add your dry mix into your wet mix until mixed together thoroughly. Add in your Chocolate Chips or melt them on the stove/in a microwave (I prefer melting them) and then mix them in. Take out your silicone muffin cups and evenly distribute your mix into them. Bake on 350\xc2\xb0F/176\xc2\xb0C 18:00-22:00. To make your Frosting simply add all of your Frosting ingredients into a bowl and mix them together. Spread your Frosting onto your Brownie Cupcakes! Devour!

Tips: Let your Cream Cheese soften up a bit before you add it in (to make mixing easier)!

Title: b'Why Guys Hate Training Legs'
Description:
b"'Like' http://facebook.com/RussHowePTI Fitness Instructor Russ Howe PTI answers this week's gym question: Why do most guys hate training their legs?

Russ Howe PTI's recommended supplements for building legs: http://RussHowePTI.com/recommended-supplements/

Official Russ Howe PTI workout wear available at http://FunnyGymTshirts.com

Training your legs with weights is going to play a very important role in the overall physique you are able to achieve and, sadly, most men neglect them completely. Russ trains a variety of people in the gym each day, ranging from models, actors and bodybuilders to regular people looking to build a better body. Today, Russ gives us three proven reasons for hitting the squat rack the next time you visit the gym.

#1 Balancing your physique - don't be one of those gym guys with a nice upper body but tiny, out of proportion legs.

#2 Release growth hormone - training legs actually helps your muscles to grow all over your body. Those people who usually ignore 'Leg Day' because they want to focus on building a bigger upper body, ironically, are the ones who would get great results from it.

#3 Increase your performance on big exercises - having stronger legs and glutes will increase your ability on key upper body movements such as Bent Over Barbell Row.

Remember: SQUAT. Because somewhere out there a girl is warming up with your max.

More free fitness tips from personal trainer Russ via his new Facebook page: http://facebook.com/RussHowePTI"

Title: b'Muscle Clean for Beginners'
Description:
b'The Muscle Clean is a great exercise for developing power, strength, and even mobility. 
The major difference between the power clean and the muscle clean is that in the muscle clean there is less activation of the legs. The power is coming from the hips but a lot of the action is in the upper body most specifically the shoulders. The muscle clean is also a great exercise for beginners that are wanting to learn the traditional power clean. In a power clean there is also a catch or rebound at the knees where the weight is decelerated into the legs. The power clean is also a more difficult movement to learn. 

The muscle clean is also a amazing exercise for deltoid development. First, clean the weight starting from the hang position (bar hanging slightly above the knees) up to the shoulders. 
Use only a slight leg action to help get the bar on its way while the arms do most of the work.
So, start off by "shouldering" the bar, lifting it from the knees up to the shoulders using a slight leg drive and a strong arm action. Remember, keep the bar close to your body. Start with a light bar and practice the movement before you start to add weight.

Title: b'PiYo Workout: Pilates and Yoga is PiYo Workout'
Description:
b'PiYo Workout Get on the earlybird list http://90dayworkout.net/piyo-workout

PiYo is a music-driven, athletic workout motivated by the mind/body practices of Pilates and yoga that also includes flexibility training, strength training, complete body conditioning, and vibrant activity

Fitness lovers who take part in PiYo courses regularly can gain the exact same benefits individuals look for from Pilates and yoga: Improved strength, flexibility, balance, stress decrease, and general fitness level enhancement.

PiYo workouts have actually been instructed in fitness centers for a few years now so we are incredibly thrilled to be able to package that up into a brand-new home fitness program for you to do from the convenience of your own home.

PiYo includes 8 different workouts that you can do right at home. They are 25 to 45 minutes long, and differ in the target locations they hit. It combines the practices of Pilates and yoga to help you build strength, reduce weight, increase flexibility and have a good time doing it. PiYo was created by Chalene Johnson, the creator of the Turbo Kick system. It was made for people who really want the mind-body benefits of a yoga or Pilates workout, but with a higher-energy, higher-sweat course.

PiYo exercises are created for maximum dexterity, flexibility, core stability, and strength. The exercises mostly consist of athletic drills, sports activities, stretching and much more, set to pleasant music so you don't get burnt out with your workout regimen.

The PiYo workout will not utilize weights as devices. You'll be utilizing your very own body weight to create incredible results of a slim and lean body.

The PiYo exercise is a lot different from T25, Insanity and other programs since there's NO jumping (individuals with knee issues: rejoice!) and it's LOW impact. The program concentrates on strength, flexibility and stability without effect.

I entered into PiYo a skeptic since I'm not truly a mind-body type. Somebody recently called me "high-strung." I like to think of it as even more "energetic," but whatever. I just have an issue sitting still. Savasana? Torture. How long do I need to lay there prior to I can stand up and get an iced coffee? 2 breaths? Four? Exactly what's the method right here? But due to the fact that Chalene created PiYo, I had faith it would rock. Ohhhh, did it rock.

PiYo is due to be released i mid June

Title: b'Posi\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o 01 "The Hundred" do M\xc3\xa9todo Pilates Solo'
Description:
b'M\xc3\xa9todo Pilates Solo exerc\xc3\xadcio "The Hundred".
O foco principal do exerc\xc3\xadcio \xe2\x80\x9cThe Hundred\xe2\x80\x9d \xc3\xa9 a respira\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o, por isso ela deve ser realizada de maneira correta para recrutar o m\xc3\xbasculo transverso do abd\xc3\xb4men - atrav\xc3\xa9s da expira\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o for\xc3\xa7ada - dando suporte e estabiliza\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o a coluna lombar.
A respira\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o deve ser realizada em dois tempos, cinco tempos para a inspira\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o e cinco tempos para a expira\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o fazendo um ciclo de respira\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o completa; Este ciclo deve ser repetido dez vezes o que resulta em cem/hundred. O praticante inicial ou o avan\xc3\xa7ado pode sentir dificuldade em alcan\xc3\xa7ar esse n\xc3\xbamero, isso acontece por v\xc3\xa1rios motivos, podemos citar a franqueza da musculatura abdominal e do m\xc3\xbasculo iliopsoas, d\xc3\xa9ficit de equil\xc3\xadbrio, baixa capacidade pulmonar ou at\xc3\xa9 mesmo c\xc3\xa2imbras musculares recorrentes. 
Dica: anote constantemente o n\xc3\xbamero de respira\xc3\xa7\xc3\xb5es alcan\xc3\xa7adas e utilize-as como par\xc3\xa2metros de evolu\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o. 
A progress\xc3\xa3o do exerc\xc3\xadcio acontece quando reduzimos o \xc3\xa2ngulo formado entre as pernas e o ch\xc3\xa3o, ou seja, quando aproximamos as pernas do solo. No total, s\xc3\xa3o acionados em torno de 90 m\xc3\xbasculos neste exerc\xc3\xadcio, dependendo da posi\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o adotada para a execu\xc3\xa7\xc3\xa3o.
Siga sempre as instru\xc3\xa7\xc3\xb5es corretamente. 
Se praticar s\xc3\xb3, ou\xc3\xa7a e respeite seu corpo.

Title: b'Treadmill running technique: lateral and backward'
Description: b'Lateral running on treadmill, and backward running. This is a great alternative treadmill workout that helps improve agility as well as work the hip and thigh adductors and abductors. Reverse running works the quads and hip flexors. Start slowly, almost at a walking pace (2.0 pace, no incline); within a couple of weeks, a ten minute mile (6.0) lateral pace is easily achievable. A lot of other videos demonstrate a lateral shuffle; the technique on this video requires crossing one leg over the other.'

Title: b'Worlds Strongest Man 2008 Mariusz Pudzianowski'
b'FST-7 Routine | Back Pull Day Example Exercise'
Description:
b"In this video I am going to show you an example of an FST-7 Set performed at the end of Back / Pull type training day, using Straight Arm Lat Pull Downs as the exercise.

Pick a weight that you do comfortably for 10-12 reps (12 preferably) and set yourself up with a timer, set for 30-45 seconds (preferably 30) - this is your rest interval.

Start your first set and perform the reps in a nice controlled manner, concentrating on increased Mind Muscle Connection (MMC) and really work the isolated muscle. 

As soon as you finish, start the timer. Take this time to stretch, rest, shake about, sip water... anything you feel you need to do. Be ready to start again as soon as the timer hits, don't get prepared AFTER, be ready to lift BEFORE.

Repeat this process 7 times. This will complete your FST-7 Set.

The best exercises for FST-7 sets are pure isolation exercises, this is why I like the Straight Arm Lat Pull Down. Other good choices are Lat Pull Downs and Cable Rows, both Close and Wide grip for each is fine.

Thanks for watching.
