Title: b'Introduction to Bodybuilding | Bodybuilding'
Description:
b"Watch more How to Be a Bodybuilder videos: http://www.howcast.com/videos/492262-Introduction-to-Bodybuilding-Bodybuilding



My name is Skip La Cour; I am a 6-time national champion, drug-free bodybuilder. You can learn how to improve your bodybuilding and training efforts by visiting my websites skiplacour.com, manformation.com, massmachinenutrition.com. And today I'm going to talk to you about bodybuilding. I want to give you an introduction to body building. When you become a body builder, you want to set ambitious goals. You want to think big, get a good vision of what you want to accomplish. You want to educate yourself of the process, you want to read the body building magazines, you want to visit internet websites like skiplacour.com and bodybuilding.com. Never stop learning. You also want to surround yourself with mentors, people who can help you achieve your body building and training goals. You want to structure your lifestyle; your training, your eating habits, your rest, your recovery, your lifestyle organization in a manner that will support your body building and weight lifting efforts. You want to fall in love with body building and the training process. The more you are passionate about something, the more you enjoy something, the better you'll become. How you can do that is to set up your own self imposed standards. It's those things that you're going to do every single day when it comes to your training habits or your eating habits, and then you do them every single day you'll gain momentum, you'll gain confidence and you'll enjoy the process more and more. And always remember, you can always become bigger, you can have more muscle, you can always lift more weight, you can always lose more body fat. It's all about being the very best you can be, it's about setting those standards. living up to those standards and enjoying the process. And that's a brief introduction to bodybuilding and weight lifting."

Title: b'How to Use Your Palms | Shiatsu Massage'
Description:
b"Like these Massage lessons !!! Check out the official app http://apple.co/1IAinBB

Watch more How to Give a Shiatsu Massage videos: http://www.howcast.com/videos/508212-How-to-Use-Your-Palms-Shiatsu-Massage



In shiatsu we often use the palm of the hand as a surface area to send pressure down into the body. Basically what I'm going to do is place my palms on areas that I want to work on, and then send my weight forward into the whole palm of the hand. It's really important here not to grip with the fingers and not to send all of the weight into the wrist joint here, but to distribute the weight evenly on the whole palm. That feels more comfortable for the receiver, and it also is great for the givers health of the hand and wrist.

Evenly distributing the weight into the palm, I use this whole surface area to send pressure into which ever area I'm working on at a given point during a session. This is a way to cover the most surface area at a time by using the whole palm of the hand. You can move the palm parallel to the leg if you're working on the leg. If I'm working on the side of the spine I would want to keep it perpendicular to the spine here. Then maybe, if I want to send a specific direction up towards the head I might turn my palm that way. As well, here, opposite stretch, by sending a palm on either side of the hips.

Okay. So, palms are a great way to work on the body, and they're our most natural instinct. When something hurts, what do you do? You put your palm on it. So if it's been a long day and your shoulders really hurt we often just do that with our whole hand, and using the whole weight of the hand is really our natural instinct when something feels painful or out of balance. 

So that's what we do in shiatsu using the whole surface area of the palm to send my body weight into the receiver and create pressure through the palms."

Title: b'Training At Robert Morris University'
Description:
b"WEBSITE: http://www.synergy-athletics.com BULL STRENGTH: http://www.bullstrength.com ORIGINAL POST: http://synergy-athletics.com/effective-strength-training/one-gym-essential-you-cant-buy/

In December I laid out the ground work for Creating An Economy Gym, but I left out something important.

...And this DOES NOT COST A DIME.
MOTIVATION

If you are motivated, hell you could work out with a car tire and a garbage can lid. Nothing stops the motivated. (A good article to read about motivation was my rant about - Youth, A Fighter, And The Dying Breed.)

Weighted chin up

I need to thank Todd Hamer, the strength coach down at Robert Morris University for reminding me of that fact.

When you think of a Division I or IAA strength program, you usually image a weight room with all the bells and whistles. 

I visited the Rutgers University weight room, they must have had at LEAST 15 power racks, turf for running, tons of machines, sleds, etc. It was MASSIVE! 

While all that equipment is nice to have, I'd still set motivated coaches and athletes as FIRST PRIORITY. 

At RMU they had about 4 power racks for all their division 1 AA sports. 

Doesn't matter.

As soon as we started lifting Todd was flying around the weight room like a mad man giving everyone the swift kick in the rear that they needed. 

Robert Morris University Athletics Bench Press

We worked up to 345+ lbs on the bench and it was going up easy. Not because of the fancy bench, an expensive bar, a top of the line rack. 

It was because there was a motivator in the room! It was contagious. 

Strength Training at Robert Morris University


Now how can this apply to you?

Motivation Tips:

 * Lead from the front. Your partner wants to take the day off? Too bad, get him / her in the gym.
 * Set goals and plan your program. Its way easier to find your way if you have a map.
 * Be who you wish you are. Do you want to be the guy that constantly needs to be pushed, or the one kicking butt in the weight room? 
 * Take pride in everything you do. If you are training alone and quit on a set early does anyone know? Yes, the most important person does....YOU. 

Having good equipment is great, but without a person motivated to lift, it is all merely hunks of heavy metal.

- Joe Hashey, CSCS -

PS. Skipped training lately? Forget about it and move forward!

Title: b'Cu\xc3\xa1ntas Repeticiones Debo Hacer En Los Ejercicios Para Ganar Masa Muscular'
Description:
b'http://tinyurl.com/culturismosano
\xc2\xbfCu\xc3\xa1ntas Repeticiones, debo hacer; en Cada Serie?.
Sin importar, lo que te diga; tu revista, de fisicoculturismo favorita; el mejor n\xc3\xbamero, de repeticiones; para desarrollar m\xc3\xbasculo, en gente gen\xc3\xa9ticamente; normal, natural y sin drogas, es de, 3 a 8 repeticiones; y de, 9 a 12 repeticiones, son recomendadas. Claro, puedes obtener; buenos resultados, haciendo series; de 10 repeticiones, y lo recomiendo, para algunos ejercicios; pero es mejor apegarse, a menos repeticiones.
Dejando, de lado esos problemas; las mayores repeticiones, no ser\xc3\xa1n m\xc3\xa1s efectivas; para desarrollar m\xc3\xbasculo, aun as\xc3\xad ;(a menos que seas, avanzado y fuerte; en tal caso, puedes hacer; 20 repeticiones); porque la carga, ser\xc3\xa1 demasiado ligera. Personas fuertes, pueden desarrollar; piernas grandes, haciendo varias repeticiones; de sentadillas. El problema, como mencionaba; es que, estar\xc3\xa1s muy adolorido; despu\xc3\xa9s, de un entrenamiento as\xc3\xad; y cualquier, actividad f\xc3\xadsica; que hagas, los d\xc3\xadas siguientes; se ver\xc3\xa1 afectada.
\xc2\xbfCu\xc3\xa1nto Volumen, de repeticiones; es Suficiente?.
Evidencias reales, muestran que un total; de 50, a 100, repeticiones; a la semana, por grupo muscular; es suficiente, para estimular; su crecimiento. Eso significa, que para tu cuerpo; podr\xc3\xadas hacer, 5 series; de 5 repeticiones, en un d\xc3\xada; (25 repeticiones, en total); y 3 series, de 8 repeticiones, otro d\xc3\xada, de esa semana; (24 repeticiones, en total): y 10 series, de 3 repeticiones; otro d\xc3\xada, de esa semana; (30 repeticiones, en total). Eso equivale, a 79 repeticiones, en total a la semana; lo que ser\xc3\xada suficiente, para personas; que empiezan, a desarrollar m\xc3\xbasculo. Para personas, avanzadas; con m\xc3\xa1s habilidad, para recuperarse; podr\xc3\xadan hacer, de 150, a 200 repeticiones; en total, por cada grupo muscular; a la semana, (si tienen, gran habilidad; para recuperarse). Sin embargo, siempre debes empezar; haciendo, lo menos necesario; y ver c\xc3\xb3mo, se adapta; tu cuerpo, antes de agregarle; m\xc3\xa1s volumen de repeticiones.'

Title: b'European Step - EFPE Sommercamp in Baltrum 2008'
Description:
b'European Step. EFPE Referent Andreas (Andy) Weiss auf der B\xc3\xbchne des einmal j\xc3\xa4hrlich stattfindenden Baltrumer Sommercamps der Ausbildungsinstitution European First Place Establishment (EFPE, www.efpe-net.ch und www.efpe-net.de). 

European Step besteht - wie die gesamte Aerobic Ausbildung der EFPE - aus insgesamt drei Teilen (Basic, Advanced und Master). 

Hier ist eine Stunde nach dem Advancedprinzip zu sehen. Dieses Konzept der European Step Aerobic besticht durch einen klaren Stundenaufbau, eine hohe Trainingsintensit\xc3\xa4t und dadurch, dass die EFPE in Zusammenarbeit mit der Truewear GmbH - als einzige Firma - Steps aus Massiv-Holz bzw. MWF verwendet. 

Diese sind \xc3\xa4usserst robust, gelenkschonend f\xc3\xbcr die Nutzer, sie trainieren die Bein- und Pomuskulatur hervorragend und sind patentrechtlich gesch\xc3\xbctzt. 

Und wie auf dem Video zu sehen, sind EFPE Referenten professionell ausgebildet und technisch h\xc3\xb6chst qualifiziert. Unsere Empfehlung: Sehen Sie sich auch die European Aerobic Stunde von A. Weiss sowie den Kurzeinblick mit EFPE Referentin Nadine Theis an. 

Auch hier setzt die EFPE v\xc3\xb6llig neue Qualit\xc3\xa4ten in der Pr\xc3\xa4sentation von Sportsystemen und dem Erhalt der eigenen k\xc3\xb6rperlichen Fitness. 

European Step ist Fitnesstraining pur, Spass w\xc3\xa4hrend der Stunde und vollkommen unkompliziert. Back to the rules...'

Title: b'Minimalist Workout: Bodyweight Exercises for Fitness Anywhere'
Description:
b'Exercising is one of my favorite ways to spend my time. I am always striving to improve my fitness, liking to think of working out as "playing" as opposed to "working". In this video my friends and I demonstrate some of the bodyweight exercises I enjoy doing regularly. Performing these simple exercises, which require no equipment, we have all improved our strength, cardiovascular, endurance, flexibility and balance. 

I hope this video inspires you and gives you ideas of ways you can take your fitness on the road with you. When you are away from your gym, fitness class, yoga class, crossfit or whatever it is you are used to doing, there is no reason to abandon exercise. Have some fun with it!

Title: b'The Bodybuilding History of Jim Morris in 3 Minutes'
Description:
b"An overview of the professional bodybuilding history of Jim Morris...the 78 year-old vegan bodybuilder. 
If you would like to know more about Jim, here is a 14 minute film about him:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tUtv4slpm-U

As a professional bodybuilder for 30 years, Jim won many major titles including Mr. America, Mr. USA, and Mr. International. In 1996, Jim won the Mr. Olympia masters at age 61 as a vegetarian. In 2000, Jim became a vegan for health and ethical reasons. He continues to train regularly and works as a personal trainer in Venice, California. The film explores Jim's amazing story and his fascinating thoughts on life, aging, and personal fulfillment.

Title: b'Spine Stretch on the Ball Pilates Reformer Exercises - Onlymyhealth.com'
Description: b"For Similar Videos Click http://www.onlymyhealth.com/health-videos/spine-stretch-ball-pilates-reformer-exercises-1333443748.html\n\nSpine Stretch on the ball using a Pilates reformer - Lower back problem is the bane of many people's existence. This happens due to a sedentary lifestyle and not enough exercise. Pilate performed on a reformer is extremely beneficial in this aspect. Spine stretching on the ball using a reformer is good for all age groups. Breathing plays an important role in this exercise. According to Doctor Namita Agarwal, one must relax the back completely on the bal. The central aim of this exercise is to be able to touch one's toes without bending the knees. One must practice this routine at least 5 to 6 times and never increase the count in one routine to more than 10. Moreover, use a medium size3d ball when performing this stretch so that there is no gap between the back and the ball!"

Title: b'How to Do a Split Squat | Knee Exercises'
Description:
b"Watch more How to Do Physical Therapy Exercises for the Knees videos: http://www.howcast.com/videos/510322-How-to-Do-a-Split-Squat-Knee-Exercises



Hi, my name is Eric Sampson and I want to talk a little bit about how to do a split squat. Split squats are a very high level exercise used in the exercise population, as well as the rehab population and physical therapy clinic. It's considered a closed chain exercise, just like your traditional squats meaning your feet are on the ground and your ankle, hip, knee all have to work together to complete the task.

It's a much more challenging exercise, because it involves a lot of coordination of the three joints, as well as your trunk and your core to complete it. There's a couple of things you really have to worry about with a split squat. This is what I want to demonstrate now. So come on in to a split squat position. Like a traditional squat, you're going to worry about one important feature and that is the knee position, as you're lowering yourself down. 

The knee should not translate forward over your toes all right, but rather stay behind the toes. This will ensure that you're using your muscles of your leg optimally and you're not putting undo pressure or stress on the knee joint itself. The other factor that you want to worry about in a split squat is your position of your trunk and shoulders. You want to try and stay as tall as you can while you're completing the exercise. 

If you let your trunk lay too far forward, you're going to lose one extra factor with this stretch, and that is the ability to stretch out your hip flexor on the leg behind you, which is a great feature of this exercise. This is something that I recommend for the exercise population, to do two to three sets of ten on alternating days, but also for the running population. It's a great way to get on with this exercise just before running. You can accomplish a lot by doing just 10 repetitions on each side.
 
Again, you're going to be stretching your hip flexor, as well as strengthening and warming up your leg muscles. So a split squat easily can be progressed by doing it with hand weights or doing more repetitions or holding it longer in this position. So a great high level exercise, a great closed chain exercise. Something that you want to consider doing though, once the pain and some of the range of motion problems have been taken care of already, and that's the split squat."

Title: b"Best Muscle Building Foods? Don't Miss These 10 Best Muscle Building Foods In Your Diet!!"
Description:
b"Eating the best muscle building foods is just as important as exercise. Love that one, have a look at \xe2\x80\x9cThe Shredded Chef\xe2\x80\x9d http://amzn.to/2uSX8fR 120 Recipes for Building Muscle, Getting Lean, and Staying Healthy on Amazon.

Visit: http://www.howtobecomeskinnyy.com/7-tips-for-your-optimal-muscle-gain-diet/ for more on healthy food and diets. 

Eat plenty of good protein and healthy fats in order to build lean tissue + keep fat at bay. 

 ===== Please subscribe to my channel =====

1. Lean beef is our number 1 in best protein foods for building muscle. It also contains natural creatine to build muscle. Many people use this as supplements, but you can get it from eating lean beef too. 
100 g (3.5 oz) 250 calories, protein: 26 g, fat: 15 g

2. Chicken is among the best muscle building foods it contains an excellent protein, but remember to remove the skin + choose less fatty parts, such as the breast.
100 g (3.5 oz) 219 calories, protein: 25 g, fat: 13 g

3. Salmon comes as number 3 of best protein foods for building muscle. Salmon contains and omega-3 fatty acids that can help your body to hold on to the muscles it builds. You also get the added benefit of protecting your heart from high cholesterol + disease.
100 g (3.5 oz) 208 calories, protein: 20 g, fat: 13 g

4. Eggs, our number 4 in best foods for building muscle. Best sources of protein you can add to your diet. Make sure you eat egg yolk too which contains additional protein and also vitamin B12.
100 g (3.5 oz) 155 calories, protein: 13 g, fat: 11 g

5. Quark (low fat), a specialty soured-milk, fresh cheese product very common to Germany, and other European countries and a little known muscle building magic bullet. Quark is high in calcium, vitamin A and B. 
100 g (3.5 oz) 70 calories, protein: 12 g, fat: 0.5 g

Foods are best for building muscle: vegan or vegetarian 

6. Lupine seeds (lupini beans)
Lupins are best foods to eat for building muscle, a great plant source of protein, low in saturated fats, cholesterol and sodium and high in folate, magnesium, phosphorus and manganese.
100 g (3.5 oz) = 119 calories, protein: 16 g, fat: 3 g

7. Lentils are high in protein and fiber, but low in fat which makes them a healthy substitute for meat. They also contain essential nutrients, including folate, iron, potassium, Vit. B and more.
100 g (3.5 oz) = 116 calories, protein: 9 g, fat: 0.4 g

8. Although beans are not the very best foods for building muscle, but white beans provide a great amount of amino acids and are low in fat and full of fiber.
100 g (3.5 oz) = 139 calories, protein: 10 g, fat: 0.8 g

9. Almonds, one of the best foods you can pack in your gym bag are almonds. These nuts are a natural plant source of protein. They're considered superfoods because they're packed with so many nutrients and are so beneficial for the body.
When it comes to building muscle, they contain vitamin E that helps to prevent the damage that can sometimes result from a strenuous workout session. You only need to eat a couple of handfuls each day to get the benefit. Almonds are also filled with healthy fats that protect your heart.
100 g (3.5 oz) = 576 calories, protein: 21 g, fat: 49 g

10. You should not miss healthy oils as best foods for muscle building, because they can prevent the breakdown of muscle tissue that you've worked hard to build. This includes coconut oil, olive oil, and flaxseed oil. By using these oils for cooking or adding them to smoothies and other dishes you'll improve your physique.

Ok, not a food, but hydration is an absolute key element of a muscle building diet. You need to stay hydrated in order to build muscle tissue. We often associate protein with muscle tissue but, like all cells of the body, muscle cells are made mostly of water.

 ===== Please subscribe to my channel =====

When you're exercising and working hard to build muscle, you need to make doubly sure that you're drinking enough water to stay hydrated. Drinking enough water will help your body to make more muscle tissue and make good and fast use of the protein in the body. If your weight is 70 kg (154 lb) you should be drinking about 2 liter (70 oz) of water each day!

Every men and women should incorporate the best foods to eat for muscle building into their lifestyle to see better results from the work at the gym. The best muscle building diets includes these foods along with making sure you eat the appropriate number of calories.

I didn't include soy in the list, because of the many pros and cons on soy products these days. I would recommend buying safe meat, fresh from the butcher; antibiotics free eggs that are and organic grown veggies free of pesticides.

Hope you enjoyed these tips on the top foods for muscle building, please share the video http://youtu.be/Z0cWSqi23CA with your friends + subscribe to my channel http://www.youtube.com/user/guideebook/ for more interesting videos coming soon.

Title: b'Sprint Kettlebell Bodyweight Ladder'
Description:
b'Get SHREDDED and STRONG with this PROVEN strength-fat loss hybrid system - http://www.trainaggressive.com/28dayshred

Now, here's a nasty little Sprint Kettlebell + Bodyweight Ladder
I've got for you.

1A) Sprint 25-30 yards @ 100%
1B) Double KB Russian Swings 20, 18, 16... 4
1C) KB Push Ups 4, 6, 8... 20
***Walk back for REST

You'll start by hitting a short ALL-OUT sprint of about 25-30
yards.

As soon as you get to your kettlebells, you first hit some swings.

For reps, we're going DOWN by 2 reps each set starting at 20.

As soon as you get done with your set of swings, you go right to
push ups.

With these, you'll be going UP in push ups each set x 2 reps
until you hit 20.

After you finish the push ups, get up and walk back to the start
line nice and slow.

This is where the "strategic rest" comes into play.

We're not going for FULL recovery as this is geared towards being a
"high intensity" finisher, but we still want enough in the tank to
each round go full blast on the sprints.

We DON'T want to turn the sprints into some fast paced jogs ;)

So, there you go.

Crank this one out as a stand-alone session OR plug it in after
your main strength work like I did.

If you want to push it to the next level, grab some HEAVY KB's.

A pair of 70's would be downright BRUTAL ;)

Have fun and Go 110% H.A.M.

For a FULL 7 Week progressive Sprint Program that will get your Lean and mean, check out - http://www.shreddedin7.com

Video Transcript:

"How To Achieve Progressive Overload On Isolation Exercises?"

This is a good question to ask, but as far as I\xe2\x80\x99m concerned there\xe2\x80\x99s really no difference between the basic concept of progression when it comes to a small isolation lift in comparison to a big compound lift. 

Your focus is still to just gradually increase the weight you use over time, and assuming you\xe2\x80\x99re training and eating properly, you should be able to achieve consistent, ongoing improvements as you continue training. 

However, there are two very important things to keep in mind here... 

First off, an isolation exercise only involves the use of a single muscle group and so obviously the overall rate of progression is going to be a lot slower. And because all of the stress from those exercises is being directed at one muscle group, small increases are still very significant. 

I can\xe2\x80\x99t give a direct parallel, but for example, you could say that 2 extra reps on a tricep extension is going to benefit your triceps in the same way that say 5 extra pounds on a deadlift would benefit your back and legs. 

So you really have to lower your expectation for how quickly those isolation exercises are going to increase and recognize that any progression at all, even if it\xe2\x80\x99s just a single rep or even a half rep, that still is significant, again because you\xe2\x80\x99re only using 1 muscle group. 

And the second thing to remember is that any time you increase the weight on an isolation exercise, you\xe2\x80\x99re going to feel that increase way more heavily because it\xe2\x80\x99s a much bigger percentage jump in comparison to increasing the weight on compound lifts. 

For example, if you\xe2\x80\x99re performing side lateral raises with 20 pound dumbbells and then you increase to 22.5 pound dumbbells, you\xe2\x80\x99re increasing the total weight lifted by 5 pounds which is actually a 25% increase, whereas if you\xe2\x80\x99re deadlifting 200 pounds and then you add 5 pounds, the percent increase is only 2.5% which is 10 times less. 

So let me give you a couple tips on this issue...

First off, if jumping up to the next set of weights on an isolation exercise feels too heavy for you, then what you want to do is focus on increasing the number of reps you\xe2\x80\x99re performing first before you try to add more weight. 

So instead of trying to increase the weight on a dumbbell curl once you reach 8 reps with a certain weight, try bumping that up to 10 or 12 reps, and then increase the weight. Or if you get to 10 reps on a side lateral raise and you try to increase but it feels too heavy, then bump that up to 12 or even 15 reps before increasing. 

Another option you can use to get stronger with a given weight before going up is to decrease the rest time in between sets, or just make the exercise itself more difficult by pausing for longer in the fully contracted position, slowing down your negatives or just adding some more volume with an extra set or two. 

One more point I\xe2\x80\x99d add is the concept of \xe2\x80\x9cmicroloading\xe2\x80\x9d, which is to try and find ways to decrease the overall amount of weight you add each time so that the percentage jump isn\xe2\x80\x99t as big. 

For example if you\xe2\x80\x99re doing a machine isolation lift but the weight stack only goes up by 10 or 15 pounds at a time, then depending on the machine you could rest a small dumbbell on top of the weight stack, or you could hang a 2.5 or 5 pound plate off the pin.

Or with dumbbells you can actually purchase small magnetic micro plates that attach onto the ends, or you could even wear a really light wrist weights depending on the exercise, these are just some ideas and if you get creative then there are all sorts of ways to increase the weight on isolation lifts by only 2.5 pounds at a time as opposed to 5 or 10. 

So, bottom line here, progressive overload is the single most important factor when it comes to gaining muscle size and strength over time, and you should strive for continual progression on isolation lifts in the same way you do for compound lifts, except that the increases will happen a lot more slowly, and that\xe2\x80\x99s totally fine because even small increases on those exercises are still very significant in terms of gaining muscle because you\xe2\x80\x99re only utilizing a single muscle group.'

Title: b'9 months post op'
Description:
b'sorry for the mega delay. this is a 9 months post op video/dietary video. 

i am now doubling my protein intake(2 grams per pound of bodyweight), to help me bulk. also adding in more vegetables/carbs. if you arent working out heavily you only need 1 gram of lean protein per pound. 

eat 5-6 small meals per day!
drink 8-10 cups of water!

im not happy with chest results/pec workout results, but am stoked on the rest of my workout results. in a bulking phase for the next minute or so

eating small meals keeps your metabolism going. eating inconsistently slows it down. even if you are trying to lose weight and want to cut calories to under 1500(or is it 2000?), still spread that out in small meals so your metabolism is always working'

Title: b'Jennifer (Wolfe) More Yoga: Prenatal Vinyasa Yoga'
Description:
b"Jennifer (Wolfe) More Yoga: Prenatal Vinyasa Yoga. See full yoga video here ... http://myyoga.tv/v4qK

Whether you're a yoga veteran in search of an active yoga routine, or you're new to yoga, Prenatal Vinyasa Yoga with Jennifer More gives you all the tools to make your pregnancy journey the best it can be. Prenatal Vinyasa Yoga actively prepares women for the marathon event of childbirth, while helping women discover the power and inner strength needed during this transformative period in their lives.
Jennifer found these empowering and strengthening qualities in the soft flow of Vinyasa Yoga. In her classes, she adapts Vinyasa Yoga for the unique needs of pregnant women, providing a system that works with your body without sacrificing the intensity necessary to prepare for childbirth. By learning to link your breath and movements in a constant flow, you'll get to know your pregnant body in a new and empowering way and increase your ability to work with your body during labor and childbirth, reducing the need for medical interventions.
You will need a blanket for this class; you may need a foam block.
Please watch the Prenatal Precautions video BEFORE practicing this class and read the prenatal precautions article that accompany it.
We also recommned reading Starting A Prenatal Yoga Practice by Ariel Pavic."

Title: b'CrossFit - Muscle-Up Virtuosity Part 2 (Journal Preivew)'
Description:
b'CrossFit Journal Preview (http://journal.crossfit.com).

CrossFit Santa Cruz's Laurie Galassi is a gymnast and CrossFit coach. In this instructional video, she breaks down that most challenging CrossFit movement: the muscle-up.

After dealing with body shaping and grip in Part 1, Galassi addresses the place where everything usually goes awry: the transition.

Working from a position lying under the rings, Galassi demonstrates the transition by pulling while keeping her legs out front as she pushes the chest through and keeps the rings close to her body. Also important is a grip that allows the rings to move a little bit as you transition from a position below the rings to the bottom of a dip on top of the rings.

To help athletes feel the positions, Galassi introduces the "dream machine"\xe2\x80\x94a harness that reduces the load and allows the athlete to move more easily.

Ultimately, there is a strength requirement for a muscle-up, and you have to drill the positions over and over again.

"Do a whole bunch. Then do a whole bunch more," Galassi says.'

Title: b'Ghetto Glute Ham Raises (GHRs) at home!'
Description:
b'One of my training days prescribes me to do several sets and reps of Glute Ham Raises (GHRs). Like most commercial gyms, my facility does not have a GHR apparatus. You can either do a "ghetto" version by utilizing the seated calf raise machine (an old clip me doing this is within this video), a lat pulldown machine, or simply have someone hold your feet in place, as I did at home. My Wife asked that I blur her out of the video, hence, the blurry upper right-hand corner :).

This exercise is an excellent way to hit your hamstrings. As you strength then your hamstrings and optimize your technique, you may eventually get to the point where you don't need your hands to catch yourself falling; in fast, some guys actually do this weight small dumbbells or plates in each hand!

Thanks for watching.'

Title: b'navtej singh bodybuilder mr singh'
b"Shoulder Rehab - 8 wks - isometric shoulder and rotator cuff ex's"
Description:
b"AUG 28, 2013 (8 wks post-op)

I am continuing with the pulley and stick ROM ex's, making slow but steady progress. The ROM progress was very fast the first week, which is to be expected; now as I have to push into the end-range of the movements it gets more difficult (and painful).

I now started doing isometric ex's for the rotator cuff muscles. The current rehab protocol is for rotator cuff rehab because the bicep tenodesis is still healing and needs to be left alone for a bit more time. There does not seem to be much change or deformity in the shape of the bicep muscle, but it might be too early to tell; once I begin strengthening it may take a new shape.

But it may be that Dr. Schaefer is just an awesome surgeon, that his technique is just that good!"

Title: b'A KILLER Bodyweight Exercise for Your ENTIRE Upper Body - Back, Chest, Arms, Core'
Description:
b"http://www.thebestbackexercises.com - This is a unique version of the one-arm chin-up that is also a version of a one-arm dip.

It allows you to target your back, chest, biceps, triceps and core (and shoulders) in one movement. It's a total bodyweight attack on the upper body.

You'll need a power rackwith a chin-up bar and an olympic bar for this one. Set the safety rails to about chest height and set your bar on top (and in the middle of the rack).

You'll be gripping with a neutral grip with one hand for the chin-up. With the other hand, you'll be doing a dip. Set that hand on the bar that's in the rack. You'll need to experiment with your setup to get the proper heights and bar placement, but it's not hard to figure out.

Grip the chin-up bar and set your hand on the bar then pull with one arm and push with the other.

This also puts some nice cross-tension through the deep muscles of the core to stabilize your body as you come up. It's not weight-bearing so it's not a tremendous about, though.

This technique makes use of contralateral antagonistic muscle activation...e.g. the opposing side opposing muscle will be a bit stronger due to nervous system activation.

You'll also find that either the dip of the chin is stronger and you'll be able to push yourself a little harder on the weaker one as the stronger one helps more towards the end of the set.

This is a GREAT way to work the back and chest at the same time. Total upper body training in one exercise."

Title: b'Rest Time Between Sets'
Description:
b"Like / Share / Subscribe! It's all greatly appreciated! 
How long should you rest between sets?

Here are some pretty general guidelines and again they will differ depending on the person and their ability to recover to ensure their next set is effective.

Strength Training in the 1-8 rep range =3-5 min
Hypertrophy Training in the 8-12-15 rep range = 1-2 min
Endurance Training 12+ reps = 45-60 sec

Title: b'Parabolic Performance Exercise Series: The Bear Crawl'
Description: b'Performance Coach Justin Moore explains the bear crawl. The bear crawl is an extremely effective movement that can be utilized as part of a dynamic warm-up or as an accessory exercise toward the end of a workout. This movement activates the anterior core and glutes, improves shoulder stability, and teaches the athlete to maintain a neutral spine while moving.\n\nTo perform the bear crawl, begin on all fours with your knees under your hips and hands under your shoulders. Pick your knees up just slightly off the ground. Begin to crawl by moving one arm and the leg opposite that arm forward simultaneously. Keep your ribcage and spine neutral with each step. Move at a slow/moderate pace and focus on "driving" your knees to your chest. Avoid shifting your hips from side to side as you move by contracting your glutes and keeping your knees under your body as you crawl. Repeat for 2-4 sets of 10-20 yards. To increase the difficulty, crawl in a variety of directions. This will require greater core stabilization.'

Title: b"5 Minute Home Glutes & Hamstrings Workout - Cecile Bayeul's Leg Training Routine"
Description:
b"http://www.cecilebayeul.com - 5 Minute Home Glutes & Hamstrings Workout - Cecile Bayeul's Leg Training Routine

Leg Exercise #1: Stiff Legged Dead-lifts
+Legs at shoulder width.
+As you go down, leave the legs straight without bending at the knees.
+Go down until you feel a nice stretch on your hamstrings.
+Without using the back muscles, use the glutes and hamstrings to come up.
+Contract your glutes as you go up.
+Breathe out as you do the force and breathe in as you go down.
+Do between 8-10 repetitions.
+Start with 2 sets and as you get more advanced you can do 3.
+As you get more advanced you can use weights.

Leg Exercise #2: Wide Stance Squats
+Put your legs on a wide stance, feet pointing completely to the side. 
+Push with the heels in order to emphasize the glutes.
+Go down until you have a 90-degree angle between the calves and the thighs.
+Focus on the contraction of the glutes.
+Breathe in as you go down and you breathe out as you do the force with your glutes.
+As you get more advanced you can use a dumbbell.
+Keep the back straight.
+Do between 8-10 repetitions.
+Start with 2 sets and as you get more advanced you can do 3.
+Rest between 30-60 seconds and do a second set.


Training Splits
As far as training splits, my favorite way to train these days is:

Day 1: Hamstrings, Glutes, Quadriceps, Calves
Day 2: Chest, Shoulders, Triceps
Day 3: Back, Biceps, Calves
Day 4: rest
Day 5: Start over

In this manner you hit your body parts around twice a week each week. :)

Make sure to visit my site:

http://www.cecilebayeul.com

for free training and nutrition information.

Also sign up for my free newsletter and get 2 FREE videos on how to lose fat as you get toned."

Title: b'How much do you bench?'
Description:
b'How much do you bench?

This question seems to get thrown around often both in and outside of the gym. What it all comes down to is - Who Cares? Your muscles are NOT aware of absolute poundages and in reality trying to lift heavy weight to impress others or feel better about yourself with do more harm than help. There is no point in sacrificing muscle stimulation and proper form because you let your ego get in the way. Focus on getting stronger each workout and forget what other people say or think. Make small incremental progress week after week and you will notice much more progress and results.

Title: b"Gym-Ken Gymnastics' Epic Parkour/Tricking Sampler"
Description:
b'http://www.gymkengymnastics.com/
Gym-Ken Gymnastics is located at 184 Rockingham Rd in Windham, NH. We host Parkour classes and Open Gyms on Tuesdays and Thursdays with Mr. Jonathan as the teacher...

$15 8:30-10:30 every Thursday night Plus Pizza Prizes from Dominos Pizza in Derry, NH

Parkour is defined on the World Federation of Parkour and Freerunning's (WFPF) Website as one of three possibilities. Moving from point "A" to point be in the most efficient, direct, or creative way possible. At Gym-Ken we let you choose the way you train. 

If you want to use the least amount of energy by getting a ladder and climbing rope to get over the building in your way we support your choice. If you need to boost your strength so you can run up the building grab the top and muscle up and over we can help with the conditioning and give you a place to practice. If you are all about pure flash and want to nail the biggest tricks so you can push your creativity to a whole new level we have the technique and the know how to help you reach your goal. Even if you do Crossfit or boot camps we have what you need to get your movements to the next level.

No only do we have the most talented group of tracers and trickers in the north east, but we also have the most supportive group as well. Come down every Tuesday and/or Thursday night from 8:30-10:30pm and train with the best so you can be your best. Its only $15 for the 2 hour jams and you should be on the look out for our special guests from the WFPF that visit us from time to time.

Ce test est particulier car ici, on va tester un produit original qui est un sirop de caramel pour accompagner vos plats ou vos pan cakes !

Title: b'Flutey and Kefu sing with Heather Small'
Description:
b'London Wasps players Riki Flutey and Steve Kefu showed off their musical talents this week as they sang with soul singer Heather Small to promote the upcoming St George's Day Game.

Small, who will perform at the London Wasps V Bath Rugby St George's Day Game at Twickenham on April 23 took players Riki Flutey, Tom Rees, Tom Varndell, Christian Wade and Steve Kefu for a singing session at the club training ground this week.

England centre Flutey said: "It was a bit of fun but a few of us really enjoy singing and getting together with a guitar and she was able to give us some really good pointers. We're all looking forward to playing again at Twickenham and with Heather entertaining the crowd out there we thought we'd take the opportunity to get some lessons in ourselves from an expert!"

How do you rate Riki's singing? Let us know by following us on twitter.com/waspsrugby.'

Title: b'Below Knee Amputee Weightlifting'
Description:
b"Weightlifting was a passion of Scott's before losing his leg below the knee in 2013. TCOP was thrilled to help get Scott back doing what he loves. Check out the video for some impressive weightlifting, featuring:
 
- 650 Pound Leg Press
- 450 Pound Reverse Press Squat
- 450 Pound Hack Squat
- Treadmill at 4 MPH on a 10% Incline

***PLEASE CONSULT WITH YOUR PROSTHETIST BEFORE ATTEMPTING THIS KIND OF ACTIVITY TO ENSURE YOUR PROSTHESIS HAS THE CORRECT CONSTRUCTION AND COMPONENTRY.***


At TCOP, you will receive one-on-one care from our trained practitioners to determine what prosthetic device will be the best solution for your rehabilitation. Our practitioners will evaluate and design your prostheses and work closely with our lab technicians to fabricate the custom device in our on-site facility. 

TCOP is committed to providing the highest quality orthotic and prosthetic services to meet your individual needs and improve the health status of the people in the communities we serve.

A leading destination prosthetic facility:

-We are conveniently located 20 minutes from MSP international airport, Mall of America, Twins Target Field, Vikings Mall of America Field and downtown Minneapolis

-Hotels and restaurants nearby

-Typically we can cast, form and fit prostheses in a matter of days including gait training / analysis and adjustments (call for estimate)

-Call 1-888-221-5939 to coordinate a visit

Title: b'4 day Split Breakdown In The Gym'
Description:
b"Link to Big Play Ray's page:
http://www.youtube.com/bigplayray09

If you are new to going to the gym, you are probably how I was when I first started. Walking into the weightroom without a plan, and seeing no results. You need to have a plan/routine. Today I am outlining which muscle groups to work on which day of the week. In a future video I will outline which specific exercises to perform once you get to the gym. 

I am currently on a 4 day split, which means I workout 4 days a week. I work each muscle group once a week (except abs and lower legs). There are other splits 
you can do, but this one has worked best for me.

ask me a question and I will try to respond quickly, and if it is a question I think everyone can benefit from, then I will make a video based on your question!

danielkjeremiah@me.com

if you like the video please subscribe by clicking here:

http://www.youtube.com/djfitnesstips"

Title: b'KILLER Leg Training - Power Start Lactic Acid Training Using Single DB\nSquats'
Description:
b"http://www.metabolicsurgerapidfatloss.com - This is a DEADLY leg training workout. The goal of it is to crank out as much lactic acid as possible in order to elicit the Growth Hormone response you get from that Lactic Acid build-up.

You'll start with a moderate weight and crank out as many reps as you can, until lactic acid shuts you down. Then you'll drop the weight in half and then crank out as many more reps as you can.

Then take 20 seconds rest, and do it again. You'll repeat this pattern until you've done a total of 10 to 12 sets for the exercise.

The best exercise to use for targeting your legs is the One-Arm gripping DB squat.

In this one, you'll be holding onto a bar with one hand, to spot yourself and to keep your torso more vertical so you can keep stress off the lower back and keep it all on the legs.

This exercise allows you to push your legs to the limit without having to worry about reracking a bar or getting stuck at the bottom...because you FINISH at the bottom anyway.

Switch back and forth between hands every 5 to 6 reps or so and get ready to feel the burn.

When you're done, your legs will be absolutely cooked."
Channel Title: Nick Nilsson - the Mad Scientist of Muscle

Title: b'Kings Gym in Oakland, Ca. Boxing home of Champions'
Description: b'Andre Ward is one of many Pro boxers who trained at Kings Gym and became a World Champion. George Foreman, Joe Frazier, James Page and Gina Guidi are a few others. This iconic gym is a classic...established by Charles King after the 1989 earthquake following a move from another Oakland location. Over the years dozens of boxers have found success in the pro ranks, but mostly amateurs who seek training and fitness via the sweet science. Kings Gym was a constant call for me during 15 years of promoting in Santa Cruz and Monterey. Proprietor Charles King always helped me find fighters for the shows. From James Buggs a journeyman to former World Champ James Page, female fighting star Gina Guidi to trial horse Abaz Bey, and others along the way...I could count on Kings gym to find the pro needed for a show. The walls are decorated with fight posters, it\'s ring with thousands of sparring round history, the speed and heavy bags hit by some of the sports biggest names, and youngsters as well. True boxing gyms are a dying breed, with Martial Arts studios replacing the more primal pugilist sanctuaries of days gone by. But Kings Gym in Oakland will continue to evolve, and it\'s "Soul" remains strong.'

Title: b'News Feature on Jessica Talisman & Prenatal Pilates'
Description:
b'Prenatal & Postpartum Pilates
Deciding how to stay in shape for an impending pregnancy or how to get back in shape postpartum? Pilates coupled with a cardiovascular activity is an ideal way to reach your goals.
The body goes through incredible, exciting, and unfamiliar changes with pregnancy. While you may feel "out of control" with the physical changes during or after pregnancy, there is a safe and effective approach to fitness through Pilates. The dramatic influence of water weight, baby weight, maternal fat stores, and increased blood volume can make any pregnant woman feel bloated, tired, and just not like yourself. As the baby demands attention from all systems in the body, it is easy to feel as if your body is not your own.
The key to a successful pregnancy and postpartum recovery is balance--both mental and physical. While it may seem counter-intuitive, it is important to maintain some measure of core strength to support your growing belly. One of the most common complaints during pregnancy is back pain. By creating a natural support for the belly with strong core muscles, pregnancy, delivery, and postpartum recovery can be made easier and back pain can be significantly reduced.
Prenatal Pilates
First and foremost, any pregnant woman must get a doctor's consent before embarking on any new exercise program. It is usually recommended that the heart rate never be higher than 140 bpm for any longer than 15 minutes, and that past the first trimester the pregnant woman not lay on her back for longer than 15 minutes. There are further indications that are specific to the individual level of fitness and specific conditions of pregnancy.
Pilates is customized to individual needs and goals. However, during pregnancy you cannot expect to change your body--become thinner, or look leaner. The goals of pregnancy Pilates are to keep the core strong to support the back, hips, and belly and to help during childbirth. As a bonus, many Pilates mommies find that postpartum recovery is faster because of the existing core strength and muscle awareness. It is important that by month 6 of pregnancy, muscles are not over-stretched, as the introduction of the hormonal relaxant can give a false sense of flexibility. By six months, pregnant Pilates focuses on centering, balance, core strength, and keeping the chest and shoulders open.
As the due date approaches and it becomes more difficult to access the core, specific exercises are given to help find those muscles. Aches, pains and discomforts are addressed and a mini home exercise plan may be given. After having baby, it is important to listen to your doctor's recommendations for when a fitness program can be resumed-- every body is different and unique in it's recovery. Pilates moms find that they get back into shape faster, have fewer physical complaints during and after pregnancy, and have easier deliveries!

Postpartum Pilates
Pilates can be a fast, safe and effective way to get in shape postpartum. The Primary goal is to help the body reconnect to the walls of abdominal muscles that were stretched throughout pregnancy and train these muscles to work by pulling in, not pushing out. One of the biggest mistakes in Pilates is improper training where the student is taught to use the core by pushing muscles outwards and in fact the muscles will develop this way creating a strong and hard pot belly. This is an especially easy mistake to make postpartum as everything the body HAD BEEN preparing to do for 9 months involved expansion and pushing!
After the body connects to the core and communication is established, the postpartum Pilates program is customized to target those specific areas needing and wanting tone, strength, and stretch. Coupled with cardiovascular activity like walking, swimming, or biking, Pilates as we teach it at Studio LevityStudio Levity gives the body weight resistance training, some cardiovascular training, isometric training, and core strength training making the combination a great jump for your metabolism.
Think of your postpartum body as a blank canvas-we can help you find long lean muscles and core strength that will be useful for picking up, holding, and nursing your rapidly growing baby. Some Pilates moms find that their postpartum body is in better shape than their body before baby.

For more info, visit www.StudioLevity.com'

Title: b'Bosu Core Training'
Description: b'The Bosu Core Training is a more advanced training for the core muscles. Because the Bosu Ball is instable, these exercises activate more muscles than the same exercise performed without a Bosu Ball and are therefore more effective than their counterparts without the Bosu Ball. The muscles primarily targeted by these exercises are the m. rectus abdominis, m. obliquus externus abdominis, m. obliquus internus abdominis, m. transversus abdominis, m. erector spinae and the mm. multifidi. Because many muscles are active during these exercises, the muscles of the lower back might be felt during abdominal exercises. As long as this does not hurt, it poses no problem and is an indication that the muscles are trained. As soon as the exercise hurts, it should be stopped.'

Hi I'm Lee Labrada, your lean body coach and welcome to this weeks ask Lee. 

This week's Ask Lee question is from Tim Anderson of Miami 

QUESTION: Tim asks: "Lee, I am hearing more about casein protein lately. Can you explain to me what casein is all about, and how it can help me?"

ANSWER: Casein is a component of milk protein, which comprises up to 80% of the proteins found in cow milk. Whey protein is the other major component of milk protein, and makes up the other 20% of the proteins found in protein. Casein is commonly used to make dairy products such as cheese. 

What makes supplementation with casein protein interesting is that casein is slowly digested over several hours. This means that you get a steady release of the amino acid building blocks in the casein protein for several hours after consuming it. So the best times to take casein is when you're not going to eat again for several hours.

Because casein is slowly digested, one of the best times to take it is at night. The idea here is that consuming a slow digesting protein like casein at bedtime will help prevent muscle breakdown while you're sleeping. Nonfat, or low-fat cottage cheese is also high in casein, but not everybody likes cottage cheese, and so that's when a high-quality casein protein powder comes in handy. Just simply mix it with some skim milk in a blender and drink. 

I know that your question was about casein, but let's talk about whey protein for just a second. As I mentioned earlier way protein is derived from milk also. But unlike casein, Whey protein is digested very quickly when it's consumed, making its amino acids available immediately. This makes whey the ideal protein for consuming right after your work out.

So to summarize, use casein protein right before going to sleep, or any other time that you're not going to be eating for several hours. And use whey protein right after your workout to jumpstart recovery.

Title: b'Como Eliminar la Grasa del Abdomen - Guia Facil para Adelgazar Barriga Rapido'
Description:
b'Haz Clic Aqu\xc3\xad: \xc2\xbb\xc2\xbb http://tinyurl.com/Sacar-Abdominales \xc2\xab\xc2\xab

La grasa abdominal es la m\xc3\xa1s dif\xc3\xadcil de eliminar, porque es la que menos se metaboliza, es decir, es la sustancia que m\xc3\xa1s tarda en degradarse para pasar al torrente sangu\xc3\xadneo y ser utilizada como combustible.

Hay estudios que sugieren que la grasa en el abdomen es producto de un metabolismo lento y de ataques de ansiedad. El metabolismo lento estimula a que el h\xc3\xadgado fabrique grasa a pesar de no comer en exceso.

Por tanto nuevamente el problema es mantener bajo control los alimentos que se ingierren, y de que manera los comes. Se recomienda que se hagan 4 o 5 comidas peque\xc3\xb1as al d\xc3\xada, y aumentar ligeramente la ingesti\xc3\xb3n de prote\xc3\xadnas para acelerar el metabolismo. Las harinas y az\xc3\xbacares deber\xc3\xadas eliminarlas porque son altamente adictivas y son las probables consecuencia de los ataques de ansiedad.

Todo este programa que tendr\xc3\xadas que iniciar, debe ir acompa\xc3\xb1ado por una actividad aer\xc3\xb3bica, combinada con ejercicios de fuerza muscular. La actividad aer\xc3\xb3bica, hazla tres veces por semana en d\xc3\xadas alternos, a un ritmo de 120 pulsaciones por minuto y en un tiempo de entre 30 minutos y una hora.

Los ejercicios de fuerza se deben concentrar en los grandes grupos musculares como las piernas, gl\xc3\xbateos, espalda y pecho. Tambi\xc3\xa9n ten en cuenta el Efecto NEAT para estimular tu metabolismo. Pero por sobre todo, debes tener paciencia y perseverancia, para alcanzar poco a poco tus objetivos.

Title: b'Jedi - 1 year old - Learning Dumbbell Retrieve'
Description:
b"So I introduced the dumbbell to Jedi at 5 months old. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pBHDRoNj_bA
Since then we've struggled, mainly because Jedi would take the dumbbell and spit it out immediately. 

Last week we made a break through - Jedi held the dumbbell for 5 seconds! Then the next day, 30 seconds. Since then he has improved so much! Tonight I decided to see if he would pick the dumbbell up off the floor - yup! Then I thought I would just give a formal retrieve a shot... To my surprise HE DID IT!! It's nowhere near perfect, but I am so proud of him! He's picked it up so quickly!"

Title: b'How to do Super Sets - With Lee Labrada'
Description:
b'How to do a SuperSet - With Lee Labrada == FREE 12 WEEK PHYSIQUE TRANSFORMATION PROGRAM :http://www.labrada.com/12weekleanbody 

Please feel free to ask any questions you may have regarding Fitness or Nutrition and I will be happy to try and answer them. Here's where you can ask.. http://www.labrada.com/asklee

Today's "Ask Lee", comes from Andy Smith of Toledo, Ohio

QUESTION: Lee, What's the correct way for me to use Super Sets in my workout routine? 

ANSWER: Andy, to perform a superset you simply select two exercises for the same body part, and then you perform a set of each exercise consecutively, back to back, with little to no rest in between.

For instance, if I wanted to do a superset for my biceps, I might choose to start with a set of concentration curls, and then finish it with a set of barbell curls.

The idea behind supersets is that the first exercise tires the body part, and the second exercise overloads it, stimulating new growth.

Whenever I do supersets, I like to choose an isolation exercise for the first exercise. 
An isolation exercise is one that isolates the target muscle group. Isolation exercises usually involve motion across one joint. An example of an isolation exercise for your biceps is concentration curls. All of the motion is around the elbow joint.

Following the isolation exercise, I like to perform a compound exercise for the second exercise of the superset. A compound exercise involves two or more joints, and recruits stabilizer muscles to complete the movement. 

An example of a compound movement for biceps is barbell curls. That's because there's motion at the elbow, and to a lesser degree, motion at the shoulder joint as the movement is completed.

Another example of a superset involving an isolation exercise followed by a compound exercise is leg extensions followed by squats, for training legs. 

Once you have performed the two exercises back to back, you've completed one superset.
Supersets are a great way to increase the intensity of your work out, but be sure not to overdo them, as it could lead to over training.

Andy, I hope that helps clear up your question about supersets. I'm Lee Labrada your lean body coach stay lean and stay strong.

Title: b'Stamina Imotion Rowing Machine'
Description:
b'Get yours today http://bit.ly/Stamina_Imotion_Rowing_Machine

Video transcript: Indoor rowing is an efficient, effective, total body workout that utilizes all major muscle groups including the back, legs, arms, abdominals and buttocks. The Stamina InMotion Rower is compact with a small foot print and makes the perfect addition to any home gym.

The InMotion Rower has solid steel construction, a comfortable stitch seat and foam hand grips, the oversized foot plates pivot to help maintain the natural rowing motion during your workout.

The InTouch Fitness Monitor will keep you motivated to reach your fitness goals by tracking strokes per minute, count, time, calories burned and will scan all features during your workout.

The Stamina InMotion Rower has five levels of resistance to allow for all levels of fitness and intensity. Rowing on the InMotion Rower is as easy as 1, 2, 3. The continually none impact motion of rowing can be broken down into three phases.

The starting point or catch phrase, followed by the drive phase and lastly the finish. In the catch phase the knees are bent, shines vertical and shoulders and arms reaching forward. This phase mimics the point when the oars are being placed in the water. The drive phase is initiated by the legs, as they extend, arms remain straight till the knees are mostly extended and then the arms bend bringing the handle into the upper stomach.

In the finish, the legs are fully extended, shoulders are back, elbows are bent and the handle is against the upper stomach. For the recover, the knees don\xe2\x80\x99t bend until after the hands pass over the knees as the arms and shoulders reach forward to begin catch phase again. When finished with your rowing workout the Stamina InMotion Rower stands on end to store easily out of the way. The Stamina InMotion Rower, get in motion.'

Title: b'Mary-Anne Monckton Week 2 Post Surgery'
Description:
b"SORRY I HAD TO TAKE OUT MY VOICEOVERS BECAUSE OF COPYRIGHT ISSUES :(

Week 2- Post Surgery

This week was exciting, starting with getting the cast off and stitches out! Which means that now I am just in the moon boot until Christmas, but only on crutches for one more week! Yay

I worked out at the VIS gym for the first 3 days of the week, just to ease back into it.

At the end of the week I went in to the gym and just did some basic strength, stretching and prehab for my back and shoulders. As you can see in the video I have to have 1kg on my leg, to even out the weight of the boot...that's an extra 2kgs! 

I also started using a machine called a ProIce, which pumps ice cold water into a brace that is strapped on to your ankle, and then compresses it! It really helps with keeping the swelling down and pain levels low! 

Thanks for watching, hope you enjoy! Follow me on Instagram and twitter for more updates! @Monckton07

Hey I'm Kate Vidulich, Metabolic Training expert and Master Certified Turbulence Trainer with Fat Loss Accelerators.

In this video, I have a hybrid metabolic complex you can try today. It's perfect for people with no time and ZERO equipment.

Here's the workout plan for you. It won't take longer than 10 minutes

"The Bodyweight Booster"

Do each exercise in order with no rest. Aim for a fast, controlled pace with a smooth transition between exercises. At the end of the circuit, rest for 30 seconds. Repeat for 3-4 rounds:

A) Single leg walkout to curtsy squat x 6 each leg
B) Super Prisoner Squats x 1
C) Push Ups x 6
D) Crab crawls x 6

Why is this so effective?

You can boost your metabolism without killing any one muscle group, allowing you to burn more calories faster with total body movements. You only need one weighted resistance (such as a pair of dumbbells) and a small workout space. 

Metabolic workouts, like this one, increase the afterburn effect to significantly higher levels than traditional cardio workouts, meaning you burn more calories after the workout, while at rest.

Title: b'Short 15 Minute Chest & Back Home Workout Giantset 2'
Description:
b'http://www.HugoRivera.net - Short 15 Min Chest / Back Home Workout Giantset 2. Hugo Rivera shows you another short 15 minute chest and back home workout that you can do from the comfort of your home.

This is a great natural bodybuilding weight training routine that you can do from the comfort of your home for the purposes of gaining muscle and losing fat.

15 Minute Chest / Back Home Workout Giantset:

Instructions: Perform one exercise after the other with no rest in between exercises. Only rest 60-90 seconds after the Two Arm Dumbbell Rows with a Twist before starting over.

45-Degree Incline Dumbbell Bench Press 2-4 sets of 8-10 reps
Two Arm Dumbbell Rows (Pronated Grip) 2-4 sets of 8-10 reps
45-Degree Incline Dumbbell Flyes (palms facing forward) 2-4 sets of 8-10 reps
Two Arm Dumbbell Rows (Neutral Grip) 2-4 sets of 8-10 reps
Flat Dumbbell Bench Press 2-4 sets of 8-10 reps
Two Arm Dumbbell Rows with a Twist 2-4 sets of 12-15 reps

This routine should take you 15 minutes if you do two giantsets and 20-21 minutes if you do three.

Title: b'Como Adelgazar 10 kilos Rapido - Ganar Musculos Y Perder Grasa'
Description:
b'VISITA\xe2\x96\xba http://tinyurl.com/FactorAdelgazar \xe2\x97\x84
Adelgazar 10 kilos r\xc3\xa1pido, ganando m\xc3\xbasculos para perder grasa. Quiz\xc3\xa1s esto sea una sorpresa para algunos de ustedes, pero la manera m\xc3\xa1s r\xc3\xa1pida y m\xc3\xa1s efectiva para transformar tu cuerpo, y encender el proceso para quemar grasa las 24 horas del d\xc3\xada, los 7 d\xc3\xadas a la semana, es el entrenamiento de fuerza. No pensaste que pod\xc3\xadas ponerte en forma con solo correr durante horas y horas en la caminadora yendo a ning\xc3\xban lado, \xc2\xbfverdad? Nuestra meta con el entrenamiento de fuerza, tambi\xc3\xa9n conocido como ejercicio anaer\xc3\xb3bico, es incrementar nuestra fuerza muscular y a\xc3\xb1adir tanto m\xc3\xbasculo delgado acondicionado como podamos a nuestros cuerpos. 
\xc2\xbfPor qu\xc3\xa9 queremos a\xc3\xb1adir m\xc3\xbasculo? Bien, resulta atractivo cuando lo miras, incrementa la densidad de los huesos, algo esencial cuando envejecemos, adem\xc3\xa1s un cuerpo musculoso quema muchas m\xc3\xa1s calor\xc3\xadas en reposo todos los d\xc3\xadas que un cuerpo con menos m\xc3\xbasculo, elevando nuestra tasa metab\xc3\xb3lica basal. Este \xc3\xbaltimo hecho es un secreto sumamente importante para obtener el cuerpo que deseas. 
Tan solo medio kilo m\xc3\xa1s de m\xc3\xbasculo a\xc3\xb1adido a tu cuerpo, requerir\xc3\xa1 de 40 a 50 calor\xc3\xadas extras al d\xc3\xada para seguir con vida. Imagina si a\xc3\xb1adieras 9 kilos de tejido muscular delgado, autom\xc3\xa1ticamente estar\xc3\xadas quemando alrededor de 800 a1000 calor\xc3\xadas adicionales al d\xc3\xada, \xc2\xa1qued\xc3\xa1ndote sentado viendo la televisi\xc3\xb3n o en el trabajo! Asimismo, \xc2\xbfadivina qu\xc3\xa9 pasa cuando est\xc3\xa1s quemando m\xc3\xa1s calor\xc3\xadas de las que necesitas, para mantener tu actual peso corporal? Tienes un d\xc3\xa9ficit de calor\xc3\xadas y tu cuerpo comienza a despojarse de la grasa. 
Adem\xc3\xa1s, el proceso de crecimiento y reparaci\xc3\xb3n que sigue al ejercicio de resistencia, requiere de enormes cantidades de energ\xc3\xada almacenada en la forma de calor\xc3\xadas. Ahora sabes que vas a quemar muchas m\xc3\xa1s calor\xc3\xadas y grasa almacenadas, para desarrollar tu nueva fuerza y m\xc3\xbasculo. De hecho, despu\xc3\xa9s de que terminas un entrenamiento de resistencia, tu cuerpo utilizar\xc3\xa1 su grasa almacenada para el proceso de reparaci\xc3\xb3n.
Esto equivale a quemar grasa corporal como loco, \xc2\xa1hasta 48 horas despu\xc3\xa9s de terminado el ejercicio! 
Otro concepto importante por comprender con respecto al entrenamiento de fuerza y desarrollo de m\xc3\xbasculo, es que a medida que envejecemos, perdemos m\xc3\xbasculo naturalmente. \xc2\xbfAlguna vez has observado que un hombre o una mujer, que tiene buena condici\xc3\xb3n f\xc3\xadsica durante sus 20 y 30, comienzan a subir de peso en sus 40 y m\xc3\xa1s? Es gradual, y antes de que te des cuenta, \xc2\xa1lucen como si hubieran subido 9 kilos de grasa de la noche a la ma\xc3\xb1ana! 
El deterioro muscular es enorme. El m\xc3\xbasculo se deteriora con la edad, por cada kilo de m\xc3\xbasculo que perdemos, estamos quemando 80 calor\xc3\xadas menos cada d\xc3\xada. Tu tasa metab\xc3\xb3lica est\xc3\xa1 bajando, ahora mismo. A eso s\xc3\xbamale un periodo de a\xc3\xb1os, y podr\xc3\xa1s ver por qu\xc3\xa9 acumular grasa a medida que envejecemos, es algo desafortunadamente muy f\xc3\xa1cil de hacer.

Title: b'Increase Vertical Jump: Accelerated Squat Drop Jumps'
Description:
b'The squat drop jump is one of the most efficient ways that athletes can increase their vertical leap as it has a high transfer to normal jumping technique. 

To perform a squat drop jump properly, an athlete must "pull themselves" down towards the ground using their hip flexors, and do it fast enough that the feet end up leaving the ground. Better athletes have a shorter and more rapidly loaded eccentric phase of movement. The squat drop jump will allow athletes to learn to make their eccentric phase faster and thus store energy faster, which is released in the upwards phase of the jump. 

This type of jump should NOT be done to a parallel squat, but rather a range of motion that resembles an athletes actual jumping range of motion. This can be done with bodyweight, a power jumper, or a light barbell on the back. This is a nice exercise to use as part of a plyometric or jumping workout warmup, or to be supersetted with other exercises such as a regular backsquat. 

Once an athlete becomes proficient at this type of movement, they should take the concept into their actual jump practice.

Title: b'Echauffement musculation pectoraux'
Description:
b"Voici une vid\xc3\xa9o ou je vous montre comment bien \xc3\xa9chauff\xc3\xa9 vos pectoraux.

Vous \xc3\xaates nombreux \xc3\xa0 vous \xc3\xa9chauffer avant vos s\xc3\xa9ances d'entrainement en faisant du cardio env. 10min. Cela est malheureusement faux si vous travaillez le haut du corps

Si vous travaillez le haut du corps je vous conseille d'abord de vous \xc3\xa9chauffer les rotateurs, voici le lien de ma vid\xc3\xa9o ou je vous montre comment \xc3\xa9chauffer correctement, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ger7gQUim2w&list=UUUAHAnZ0vZxpskSa1eBtRqA

Si vous faites du cardio avant, quand vous entrainez le haut du corps, vous avez le sang qui va descendre dans les jambes et il ne sera pas focaliser dans la partie du haut du corps, cela est valable seulement si vous travaillez les jambes, et la je vous le conseil vivement de faire du cardio, v\xc3\xa9lo, tapis, stepper car \xc3\xa0 ce moment-l\xc3\xa0 le sang est focalis\xc3\xa9 dans les jambes pour avoir un maximum de pump.

Pour le haut du corps je vous conseille d'abord de vous \xc3\xa9chauffer vos rotateurs et ensuite deux s\xc3\xa9ries d'\xc3\xa9chauffement, du muscle que vous allez travailler, avant de commencer vos s\xc3\xa9ries effectifs 

Si vous aimeriez que je fasse une vid\xc3\xa9o sur un th\xc3\xa8me que vous int\xc3\xa9resse, n'h\xc3\xa9sitez pas, laissez-moi un commentaire.

Instagram http://instagram.com/pascalraemy

Title: b'Full Strength Workout (Unilateral to bilateral strength complexes)'
Description:
b"**FREE VIDEO** http://www.synergy-athletics.com/freebonus MANUAL: http://www.bullstrength.com A lot of athletes are in season in the spring, so we get a big group on Sunday to maintain strength levels (along with our older group that trains all year). 

It's been 2 months since I posted a full workout video (lower body training video below)

Full Lower Body Workout

This new video contains a great complex for building leg month and core stability. 

Here's how it works:

1. Overload a unilateral exercise
2. Complex it with bilateral exercises with different loading positions. 

The overload is important for building lower body strength. Next, the various loading patterns - even while using a submaximal weight since it is now bilateral - will build stability and core strength. 

Check out the complex in the video:
1. Front hold split squats x 6
2. Front squats x 6
3. Overhead squats x 6
4. Back squats x 6

Its been awhile since I did overhead squats, and I need to keep that tight arch, but you will get the training idea in the video!

Full Workout Clips PLUS Uni/bilateral Complex

Also, note the other clips: walking unilateral exercises, glute ham raises, core training, a high school sophmore hitting 315 x 3 on the bench, and a few other exercises going on!

- Joe Hashey, CSCS -

Title: b'Industrial Athletic: Why You Should Be Wearing Weightlifting Shoes - Richie Patterson'
Description:
b"Commonwealth Gold Medalist Richie Patterson talks lifters, and why you need to be in them.

When performing Olympic lifts (Snatch & Clean + Jerk) or Squats (Front + Back) the body become a load bearing structure.

As with any structure the stability is only ever as good as it's foundation, Olympic lifting shoes are your foundation and they serve a number of purposes

1: Base of support: A solid non compressing heel so the body/foundation does not shift under load due to a compressing sole, such as a cross trainer/running shoe.

2: Raised heel: Gives the body a mechanism to allow the knee to draw forward to a better position allowing the hip/pelvis (Centre of Gravity) to draw into the ankle (line of Gravity)
This is exceptionally important when addressing torso angle in both the clean and snatch movements and shoulder stability when in an overhead receiving position.

3: Transfer of energy/force: Were are trying to produce/provide force to the barbell, weightlifting shoes transfer your force production through an efficient transfer to the weightlifting platform allowing you to MOVE that barbell!!!

Industrial Athletic Do-win
A great readily available Weightlifting Shoe in New Zealand.

Feel: A comfortable fit, no too tight as with other models. Allowing a perfect fit for all athletes big or small, standard \xc2\xbe lifted heel to help full squat positions.

Double strap + lace system to secure the foot firmly within the shoe and looks sharp in white + grey.

I highly recommend to anyone lifting to be wearing a Weightlifting Shoe as it will give you the foundation to set your positions correctly, reduce the injury potential and look just look a little more bad ass than you already do......

Check them out here: http://bit.ly/Xe8oiH"

Title: b'Teretana Slavko Super Slide Show 2011'
Description:
b'"Slavko Gym" je non-fency i non-pozerska teretana u koju ne dolaze ljudi koji samo \xc5\xbeele da budu vi\xc4\x91eni ,ova teretana je prvenstveno namenjena ljudima dobre volje koji \xc5\xbeele da izgrade svoje telo i samopouzdanje.Biti zdrav zna\xc4\x8di biti sre\xc4\x87an i trenirati.Ostalo je na tebi.Ima tu ragbista fudbalera boksera obrazovanih itd koji ovde odra\xc4\x91uju dodatne treninge. 
Glavna odlika ove teretane je njena atmosfera i ambijent : ovde uvek vlada dobro raspolo\xc5\xbeenje me\xc4\x91u ve\xc5\xbeba\xc4\x8dima, bilo da ste profesionalac ili amater po\xc4\x8detnik ovde \xc4\x87ete uvek nai\xc4\x87i na koristan savet i pomo\xc4\x87 iskusnijih ve\xc5\xbeba\xc4\x8da ili Slavka...Niko ti ne\xc4\x87e prebaciti u \xc4\x8demu ve\xc5\xbeba\xc5\xa1 samo da se ne ose\xc4\x87a\xc5\xa1.Ambijent je jedinstven...u to \xc4\x87ete se uveriti u galeriji fotografija,zidovi su prekriveni grafitima,koje su sve napravili ve\xc5\xbeba\xc4\x8di iz ove teretane u raznim periodima od njenog nastanka.Vezbaci su raznih profesija ali sve nas ve\xc5\xbee ista volja za ve\xc5\xbebanje ili gri\xc5\xbea savesti.
Radno vreme teretane je od 7-24h bukvalno svakog dana. 
Broj treninga je neograni\xc4\x8den,nema zakazivanja termina, mo\xc5\xbeete trenirati i dva puta dnevno ukoliko \xc5\xbeelite..samo vika dreka posle 22h je zabranjena...a da se zna Salepeta radi ben\xc4\x8d na Elanovoj klupi...Teretana je opremljena sa 55 sprave renomiranih proizvo\xc4\x91a\xc4\x8da i 3 tone tegova ,od \xc4\x8dega je 90% gumirano(npr. 12 bench klupa sa olimpijskim \xc5\xa1ipkama,5 lat ma\xc5\xa1ina,bu\xc4\x8dice od 5kg, 7.5kg, 10kg...do 50kg).Tu je dzak.Nekad navrati i lepsi pol ali se kratko zadrzava...\xc5\xa0to Kaze Jedan Covek----- Nepravilno Vezbam ali Se Pravilno Razvijam ..Tr\xc4\x8dim Ku\xc4\x87i pre 24h Po\xc4\x8de\xc4\x87e mi Hormon Rasta ..........****Autor svih ovih video -materijala je SalePeta tako\xc4\x91e ve\xc5\xbeba\xc4\x8d koji je ovo uradio bez ikakve nadoknade od Slavka,radi dugogodi\xc5\xa1njeg drugarstva i dobre saradnje.

Title: b'Andy Teaches Me the Side Press'
Description: b'The combination of the Deadlift and Side Press and/or Bench Press is a full body workout. Andy has been telling me to start a weight lifting regimen for a while now but because I fight so often it hasn\'t really taken off the ground yet. But I asked him to show me the forms so that I can start doing it on my own during the week between fights. I\'ve gained a lot of muscle already, just from hitting stuff all day and doing some pullups and pushups, so this should make me strong in a very balanced, stabilizing sense. Good for Muay Thai.\nThe form here is taken from Pavel Tsatsouline, so if you have strong opinions of how to do it differently, take it up with Pavel. You can google him.\nAndy has me just using this bar right now and it\'s pretty tricky to balance it due to the length. He shows me how to safely pick it up when there is weight on it (in the future), but basically you do this exercise the way you would press a dumbbell. Start with your grip turned forward (fingers facing straight in front of you) and maintain that angle while you inhale, hold the breath for muscle tension and press the bar up over your head and bend slightly over your hip for full extension. Breathe out, take another breath and tense and use that tension to kind of "pull" the bar back down in a very controlled way. That\'s one rep; do it again 5 times, take a break and do one more set of 5 reps. According to Pavel it should be low rep, high weight and he recommends two sets of five or ten reps max however you break it up.'

Title: b'What Is Pilates Mat? | Pilates Workout'
Description:
b"Watch more How to Do Pilates videos: http://www.howcast.com/videos/505877-What-Is-Pilates-Mat-Pilates-Workout



So, what is Pilates Mat? Well, Pilates Mat is really where Pilates began. Joseph Pilates started his routine on the mat and then what grew out of that was the apparatus that he invented in order to strengthen a person's musculature in order to achieve and perform the exercises properly using core strength rather than just flailing their body about in haphazard, nonsensical ways. He developed a system that started lying down on the back, on the mat supine, completely supported by gravity. Because it's the easiest thing for your body. He was really an innovator with the mat at the time, and still is today because he's all about efficiency in the work out rather than doing 50,000 reps of everything and burning your body. He starts you where you need to begin to find where you are at with your musculature. Then progresses you from lying down, through seated, then to standing. So, you can take all that work out into the world with you. So, that's really the Pilates Mat. It's the heart of Pilates. It's both the entry point of Pilates because that's where it began, but it's also the goal. After you've learned all this apparatus work, then hopefully you take what you felt through the springs and the straps and you bring it to your mat work. And it's more accessible to people, both financially and just with time. You could get Pilates Mat videos and do it at home. You can do it on vacation. You can do it when you're traveling. It's not hard to, you can even put a towel down on the floor and use that as your mat if you're away and you don't have one with you. Cost-wise, the classes have more people in it, so it's a great way to try Pilates to see if you like it and to see if you want to commit to possibly working on the apparatus. Pilates Mat class is a really great place to start because that's where Joe started."

b"http://www.priceplow.com/ans-performance/diablo
Mike and CJ welcome special guests Dylan and Missy to test out ANS Performance's fat burning drink, DIABLO. In one word: HOT.

There's no secret - we love this brand. This video ran long so a lot was edited, including our rant on ANS here:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SBxAk9_vaQs

Unfortunately, the electric lime taste was not our favorite. It's tough to mask the crazy amount of stimulants and focus factors that are in these fat burning drinks when you have no sugar.

That said, as CJ kept using it, he came to love it, and replaced his coffee with it in the mornings. We recommend this over coffee *any* day of the week for someone who is on a diet.

The appetite suppression and mood burst is good, and this can even be used as a pre workout. CJ is in bulking mode though, so he had to plan his diet accordingly. If you're looking to kick that sweet tooth, this will help.

This is a top of its class product. I edited out some ranting, but in another review we did, there was a GREAT tasting fat burning drink, but each little scoop had 4g of sugar! That's unacceptable and we'd rather have this.
