Title: b'My Opinion of "Flexible Dieting" and Bodybuilding Nutrition'
Description:
b'This is my personal review about Flexible Dieting & IIFYM.

Free Bodybuilding Diet: http://leehayward.com/diet

Total Fitness Bodybuilding App: http://leehayward.com/app

TFB Facebook Page: http://leehayward.com/go/facebook.htm

IIFYM - if it fits your macros or Flexible Dieting is becoming more and more popular, but it's really nothing new in terms of bodybuilding nutrition.

Virtually all bodybuilding diet plans are based around counting macro-nutrients (i.e. protein, carbohydrates, and fats). Rather than most traditional weight loss diets that only focus on counting calories.

Counting macro-nutrients is a vastly superior method of tracking your nutrition compared to just counting calories because if your macros add up, your calories will add up automatically. Each gram of protein has 4 calories, each gram of carbohydrate has 4 calories, and each gram of fat has 9 calories.

Where the flexible dieting part comes into play is realizing that different foods can meet your macro-nutrient needs. You don't have to restrict yourself to eating nothing but chicken, rice, and broccoli for months on end in order to lose fat and get ripped.

Now don't get me wrong, I've seen some incredible physiques that have come about as a result of eating a very limited diet. So being super strict with your food choices certainly does "work". But I don't believe that it's necessarily the best approach for long term dieting success.

There are dozens of foods that are good sources of protein, we don't need to limit ourselves to just dry boiled chicken.

There are dozens of foods that are good sources of carbohydrates, we don't need to limit ourselves to brown rice.

And there are dozens of foods that are good sources of veggies, healthy fats, etc.

You can mix and match different types of foods to make up your bodybuilding diet plan and still get just as good (if not better) results and enjoy the process. 

If you would like help in planning out your bodybuilding diet plan and getting a list of acceptable food choices for protein, carbs, and fats - then I recommend downloading the Total Fitness Bodybuilding App at: http://leehayward.com/app

In addition to workout and training info, the app includes acceptable bodybuilding food lists, healthy recipes, and sample bulking as well as cutting diets that you can follow.

Download the Total Fitness Bodybuilding App at: http://leehayward.com/app'

Description:
b"For more basketball strength training exercises make sure to visit: http://theunguardables.com. 

Basketball strength training has become the norm for players these days. With basketball being played at a fast and physical pace, strength training is a MUST! Exercises for basketball players have evolved too. 10-15 years ago a basketball strength training program may have consisted of the usual: bench press, squat, and dead lift. Today's strength training exercises for basketball players are much more advanced and much more basketball specific.

The new game of basketball is dominated by strength, speed, and quickness. Players like Lebron James, Kobe Bryant, and Derrick Rose have reinvented how basketball players should train. Basketball strength training now consists of much more functional exercises than it used to. These functional exercises are designed to help basketball players move quicker laterally; jump higher to dunk; and be strong enough to finish around the rim even with contact. Functional exercises, like sandbag exercises, do all of the previously mentioned. Sandbag exercises for basketball players will help a player improve their leg strength, upper body strength, and core all at the same time. In addition, a players grip strength and ball handling ability will improve from gripping the sandbag.

Building a sound basketball strength training program around the proper exercises is a must. In order to compete in today's game, you need to have your program made up of exercises that won't slow you down. If you want a training program that has already taken out all of the guess work for you, make sure to check out my 12-week basketball program http://unguardablevolume1.com. It's been proven by players just like yourself from all over the world. In addition, make sure to sign up for my free quickness tips: http://theunguardables.com"

Title: b'Boxeo: Selecci\xc3\xb3n qued\xc3\xb3 lista para los Bolivarianos'
Description:
b'La selecci\xc3\xb3n nacional de boxeo se encuentra lista para competir en los Juegos Bolivarianos 2013. Los integrantes del seleccionado de los pu\xc3\xb1os,\xc2\xa0tras rigurosos 15 d\xc3\xadas de\xc2\xa0entrenamiento en Cuba, qued\xc3\xb3 preparada para afrontar\xc2\xa0este torneo el pr\xc3\xb3ximo 16 de Noviembre; fecha en que inician los Juegos.

Una de las cartas principales de este joven seleccionado, es el talentoso y experimentado Luis Miranda quien, a diferencia de sus compa\xc3\xb1eros, lleva cinco a\xc3\xb1os con la selecci\xc3\xb3n y asume este reto teniendo como base la preparaci\xc3\xb3n que ha tenido fuera del pa\xc3\xads.

Otra de las figuras y esperanzas en esta justa Bolivariana es la joven boxeadora, Lucy Valdivia que, con apenas dos a\xc3\xb1os en el deporte, logr\xc3\xb3 adjudicarse la medalla de plata en un Centroamericano disputado a principios de a\xc3\xb1o en Dominicana.

As\xc3\xad mismo, los 11 pugilistas que integran la selecci\xc3\xb3n, conf\xc3\xadan en hacer un buen papel cuando les toque enfrentar a rivales como Colombia y Venezuela, pa\xc3\xadses que sin duda, ser\xc3\xa1n los m\xc3\xa1s duros de vencer para conseguir el ansiado podio.

Ellos son: \xc2\xa0Lucy Valdivia (51 kg), Isaac Herrera (49 kg), Enoc Hualinga (52 kg), Joel Luis (56 kg), Tyson de Dios Mart\xc3\xadnez (60), C\xc3\xa9sar D\xc3\xadaz (64 kg), Luigi Miranda (69), C\xc3\xa9sar Leturia (75 kg), Jos\xc3\xa9 L\xc3\xbacar ((81 kg) y Luis Mu\xc3\xb1oz (91 kg a m\xc3\xa1s).'

Title: b"Jack Oliver - Britain's Olympic Weightlifting hopeful"
Description:
b"http://www.winkball.com/blogs/QsObAmWX3r-S/jack-oliver-team-gb-weightlifter

Jack Oliver is a British weightlifter, competing in the 77kg class. 

Similar to Zoe Smith, he started weightlifting, aged 14, at the suggestion of his gymnastics coach. Oliver took to it well and succeeded through the different ranks; he earned several junior national titles on his way to competing in the 2010 Commonwealth Games in Delhi, where he placed eighth.

Oliver achieved a personal best and broke two national records at the 2011 Weightlifting World Championships in Paris. 

Oliver will be watching all the other lifting events at 2012 and hoping to see as many other events as he can, after he's done competing. He thinks the best thing about 2012 will be the home crowd -- the Chinese crowd in Beijing were amazing, and he is hoping for the same support here in the UK. 

As he will only be 21 in 2012, Jack Oliver hopefully has a lot more to give to weightlifting after the London Games -- lifters tend to reach their peak around age 26.

Bagpipes are a class of musical instrument, aerophones using enclosed reeds fed from a constant reservoir of air in the form of a bag. Though the Scottish Great Highland Bagpipe and Irish uilleann pipes have the greatest international visibility, bagpipes of several varieties can be found in use throughout Europe, Northern Africa, the Persian Gulf, and the Caucasus.

The term is equally correct in the singular or plural, although in the English language, pipers most commonly talk of "pipes."

Evidence of pre-medieval bagpipes is uncertain, but several textual and visual clues may possibly indicate ancient forms of bagpipes. In the second century AD, Suetonius described the Roman Emperor Nero as a player of the tibia utricularis.[2]. Dio Chrysostom, who also flourished in the first century, wrote about a contemporary sovereign (possibly Nero) who could play a pipe ("aulein") with his mouth as well as with his "armpit". [3] From this account, some believe that the tibia utricularis was a bagpipe.

In the early part of the second millennium, bagpipes began to appear with frequency in European art and iconography. The Cantigas de Santa Maria, compiled in Castile in the mid-13th Century, depict several types of bagpipes. [4] Though evidence of bagpipes in the British Isles prior to the 14th Century is contested, bagpipes are explicitly mentioned in The Canterbury Tales (written around 1380): A baggepype wel coude he blowe and sowne, /And ther-with-al he broghte us out of towne.[5]

Actual examples of bagpipes from before the 18th century are extremely rare; however, a substantial number of paintings, carvings, engravings, manuscript illuminations, and so on survive. They make it clear that bagpipes varied hugely throughout Europe, and even within individual regions. Many examples of early folk bagpipes in Continental Europe can be found in the paintings of Brueghel, Teniers, Jordaens and Durer.[6]

Evidence of the bagpipe in Ireland occurs in 1581, when John Derrick's "The Image of Irelande" clearly depicts a bagpiper. Derrick's illustrations are considered to be reasonably faithful depictions of the attire and equipment of the English and Irish population of the 16th Century[7] In 1760, the first serious study of the Scottish Highland bagpipe and its music was attempted, in Joseph MacDonald's 'Compleat Theory'. Further south, a manuscript from the 1730s by a William Dixon from Northumberland contains music which fits the Border pipes, a nine-note bellows-blown bagpipe whose chanter is similar to that of the modern Great Highland Bagpipe. However the music in Dixon's manuscript varied greatly from modern Highland bagpipe tunes, consisting mostly of extended variation sets of common dance tunes. Some of the tunes in the Dixon manuscript correspond to tunes found in early 19th century published and manuscript sources of Northumbrian smallpipe tunes, notably the rare book of 50 tunes, many with variations, by John Peacock.

Title: b'#ActiveBodyFit - Challenge Gym Workout 2'
Description:
b"Our fitness expert Samantha Clayton shows you how to do our convenient and customizable Herbalife24 certified fitness routines. Grab a friend, watch the videos at home or on the go, perform the exercises and progress through the series until you achieve your desired fitness level.

The Active Body Fit workout program helps you achieve an improved level of fitness through exercises that provide repetition, gradual progression and periods of rest. You\xe2\x80\x99ll achieve maximum benefits from the program when combined with a smart nutrition plan that helps you to build, repair and r[eplenish your body. Performing these safe and fun exercises as part of a healthy, active lifestyle will help you take the guess work out of planning your fitness routine. 

Each week, we provide you with three workouts routines consisting of five exercises each, all designed to keep your mind engaged and your body progressing. You can customize each workout to your needs by doing standard or modified exercises. You\xe2\x80\x99ll progress through Foundation, Interval and Endurance workout routines each week and at the end of each month you can test your fitness level with a Challenge workout. The best part is you can start the program anytime, do the workouts alone or with friends, and do them at home or anywhere you want. Now let\xe2\x80\x99s get to it and have some fun!

Visit Herbalife24.com for the full series: Herbalife24.com/Active
#ActiveBodyFit #Herbalife24

About Samantha Clayton:

Samantha Clayton is responsible for all activities relating to exercise and fitness education for Herbalife\xe2\x80\x99s independent Members and employees. Through in-person training sessions, educational tools and materials and her blog (www.discovergoodfitness.com), she ensures that the important role of exercise as part of a healthy active life is understood by all. She also helps create, organize, and promote employee fitness programs and activities as an integral part of the company's corporate wellness program. 
A native of Liverpool, England, Samantha initially worked as a consultant for Herbalife for two years and led the Herbalife24-Fit program, the company\xe2\x80\x99s first comprehensive fitness training program and DVD series. 
Before joining the corporate ranks, Samantha was a professional athlete. She represented Great Britain in the 2000 Sydney Olympics in both the 200m and the 4x100m relay events. Prior to the Olympics, she won two medals in the Olympic AAA trials - a silver medal for the 200m and a bronze for the 100m - as well as a silver medal in the 4x100m relay during the European Junior Championships in 1997. Her personal records include an 11.40 seconds in the 100m and 23.02 seconds in the 200m. 
Samantha is a personal trainer and group exercise coach through the American Fitness and Aerobics Association (AFAA) and International Sport Science Association (ISSA).


Statement: 

Here at Herbalife we believe that in order to achieve an improved level of fitness, an exercise series should provide you with an element of repetition, follow a gradual progression and be combined with a period of rest. To achieve the maximum benefits from your exercise plan it should always be combined with a smart nutrition plan that provides your body with the essential nutrients it needs to build, repair and replenish your body.

The aim of our Active Body Fit workout series is to provide you with safe, fun exercise ideas, and healthy active lifestyle tips to help you take the guess work out of planning your fitness routine.

We have provided you with three workouts to do each week. Each workout contains 5 key exercises that follow a variety of different progressions throughout the month, my aim is to keep you engaged and keep your body progressing. 
For each exercise provided we offer an advanced and modified version so that the workout can be tailored to fit people with all levels of fitness.

At the end of each month there is a challenge week so you can test your fitness level and have fun with your group of friends.

Watch the video for the workout on your chosen day, familiarize yourself with the moves, equipment needed and safety considerations then you are ready to go. You can do your workout anywhere, in a gym a park or at the beach you choose. Do it alone or invite your friends.

Each month I will provide with exciting and dynamic new moves to try.
Have fun and remember to share your experiences on social media with the tag #ActiveBodyFit #Herbalife24

Title: b'Como Ganar Masa Muscular. Ejercicios Para Antebrazo.'
Description:
b'http://tinyurl.com/musculos84

Como Ganar Masa Muscular. Ejercicios Para Antebrazo.

Ejercicio f\xc3\xadsico 1. Curl de antebrazo en supinaci\xc3\xb3n. 
Sentado,con los antebrazos apoyados en los muslos, sostenemos una barra con las palmas de las manos hacia arriba, en supinaci\xc3\xb3n, y flexionamos las mu\xc3\xb1ecas hacia arriba. luego descendemos el peso a la posici\xc3\xb3n inicial, para comenzar nuevamente la flexi\xc3\xb3n, y as\xc3\xad consecutivamente. Recuerda que \xc3\xbanicamente realizar\xc3\xa1s el movimiento a nivel de las mu\xc3\xb1ecas y no deber\xc3\xa1s levantar los antebrazos de los muslos durante cada ejecuci\xc3\xb3n. Con este ejercicio, trabajar\xc3\xa1s la regi\xc3\xb3n anterior de los antebrazos.

Ejercicio fisico 2. Curl invertido para antebrazo.
De pie, sosteniendo una barra con las palmas de las manos hacia atr\xc3\xa1s, levantamos el peso hacia adelante con una flexi\xc3\xb3n de ambos codos, realizando el movimiento \xc3\xbanicamente a nivel de los antebrazos sin mover los brazos. Luego descenderemos la barra de forma lenta hasta su posici\xc3\xb3n inicial, siempre con desplazamiento solo de los antebrazos. Toda persona deber\xc3\xada incluir este ejercicio, ya que es uno de los mejores para trabajar la regi\xc3\xb3n posterior del antebrazo.

Ejercicio fisico 3. Curl de antebrazo en pronaci\xc3\xb3n.
Sentado, con los antebrazos apoyados en los muslos, sostenemos una barra con las palmas de las manos hacia abajo, en pronaci\xc3\xb3n, extendemos las mu\xc3\xb1ecas hacia arriba, elevando el peso, para luego descenderlo con el desplazamiento contrario. Recuerda que \xc3\xbanicamente realizar\xc3\xa1s el movimiento a nivel de las mu\xc3\xb1ecas y no deber\xc3\xa1s levantar los antebrazos de los muslos durante cada ejercicio. Con este ejercicio trabajar\xc3\xa1s la regi\xc3\xb3n posterior de los antebrazos.

Ejercicio fisico 4. Flexi\xc3\xb3n Extensi\xc3\xb3n Lateral.
Sentado, sostenemos una barra sin peso o con m\xc3\xadnimo peso, y apoyamos nuestro antebrazo en el muslo, realizamos el movimiento de flexi\xc3\xb3n, hacia abajo, y extensi\xc3\xb3n, hacia arriba, de la mu\xc3\xb1eca. Trabajar\xc3\xa1s los lados del antebrazo. Este ejercicio es ideal para toda persona que desee incrementar el grosor y la fuerza del antebrazo, ya que es una zona que frecuentemente no se entrena.'

Title: b'What Does Your Favorite Yoga Posture Mean? - LexiYoga'
Description:
b"No matter how much experience you have with yoga, either a beginner or advanced, have you ever noticed that you tend to favor a specific yoga posture more than other? Or one that you keep wishing your yoga teacher would call out next?
In this video, I'll explain to you what a propensity for a certain yoga posture might have to say about you.

Twists
Twists are a natural draw for those who find nourishment and joy from connecting to people and places while staying firmly grounded. You like to know who and what's going on around you and behind you. You don't see things in black or white but are stimulated by multi-dimensional situations and are not afraid of tension. 

Forward Bends
Sitting or standing, a love of folding forward indicates that you are introspective and not afraid to let yourself get quiet so you can hear you own thoughts. Forward bending is also associated with looking to the past. So be sure you don't spend so much time folding forward that you forget to be open to the present or anticipate the future.

Backbends
A propensity toward backbends indicates an open heart, loving nature, and excitement about the future. Be careful that your exuberance doesn't lead to injury\xe2\x80\x94if your quads, abdomen, chest and shoulders aren't open in your backbends, you could tweak your back. Translated to daily life, if you aren't as flexible as you are strong, you could wind up with too much on your shoulders.

Balancing Postures
If you enjoy balancing postures, than you are more curious about precision than perfection. For you, nothing is more fun than figuring out how to sway like a tree and stay upright. You don't even mind falling over because you always get back up and try again, understanding that is truly the heart of practice anyway.

Hip Opening Postures
If you enjoy hip opening postures, than you're not intimidated by a little discomfort, and crave the release that comes from working your edges. You also tolerate emotionally charged situations well. The hips are often storehouses for unprocessed emotions, and many people shy away from these poses because they aren't comfortable with accessing the hidden feelings they may have. Just remember that boundaries are healthy. You don't want to overextend yourself, making you either overly vulnerable emotionally or prone to muscle pulls physically.

Inversions
Creative types who see things from all sides are drawn to inversions and so are those of us who just like to shake things up! You're interested in building your intuition and learning how to maintain a sense of trust in the face of a scary situation. You're also not afraid of a challenge. You're open to seeing things from multiple points of view. Your challenge is to learn how to find your center even when your world is turned upside down.

Corpse Pose
If you love corpse pose, then you are likely tired, over-scheduled, and craving some profound rest. Our society may prize people who can keep up a furious pace, but some part of you knows that there's a time and a place for stillness, quiet, and reflection. Indulge in a few moments of rest each day, always keeping in mind that the true challenge of the pose is to allow your mind to quiet without falling asleep or planning what you're going to have for dinner.

Title: b'Off-Ice Goalie Training - Static Balance Competency Test'
Description:
b"http://www.HockeyTrainingPro.com - hockey strength and conditioning specialist Maria Mountain has a simple balance test for you...

Can you pass this balance test for hockey players?

You know that I do not think players under 13/14 years of age should be doing sport specific off-ice training, but this post is for the little guys and gals who are just starting to develop their passion for hockey.

I had a question a few months ago from a Dad asking for some drills that would help his son keep his blades on the ice -- apparently they were getting away from him occasionally and he would end up on his rear in the crease.

I am guessing that some of it has to do with the bulk and weight of the equipment, so with time and more time on the ice, his body will start to recognize the pads as an extension of his body.

I hope his coach or goalie coach take some time to get him moving in different ways on the ice, ways that challenge him to expand his skating skill. I love tag or 'Simon Says' for this type of thing.

For off-ice, I think it is reasonable to work on both static and dynamic balance.
Static Balance Drills For Hockey

A good static balance progression is:

 Single Leg Balance x 60s each leg
 Eyes Closed Balance Single Leg Balance x 60s each leg
 Single Leg Balance with Hand Tracing

Learn more about other balance training exercises for hockey players at - http://hockeytrainingpro.com/wordpress/2013/05/skate-side-down-balance-test/ 

Get hundreds of free hockey training videos at http://www.YouTube.com/RevolutionCondition"

Title: b'Behind the Scenes With Fitness Model Monica Brant- Part 1!'
Description:
b"The one and only fitness super model Monica Brant.
www.monicabrant.com/

If you've ever picked up a fitness magazine, it's likely you'll have seen Monica Brant's picture in it.
She's one of the biggest names in Fitness, and has helped shape the fitness industry as we know it today.

Hollywood extra was invited behind the scene's of Monica's latest competition - the Europa show of Champions, in Orlando Florida in mid April, and an all access pass with Monica and her husband, Scott, backstage of the competition, on an exclusive photo shoot with Hard Bodies photographer - Isaac Hayes, even sharing a personal prayer with Monica on the night before the competition.

Monica talks openly about how she first broke into world of fitness and modelling, and motivates and inspires many of the other top names in fitness, including how she got her first fitness cover and took that to promoter herself to the international fitness icon she is today.

In the first of this 3-part mini series, watch as Monica arrives in Orlando and how she prepares during the night before the competition.If your a fan of Monica or fitness in general, you do not want to miss this.

Stay tuned for parts two and three, and follow Monica as she steps on stage beside many of girls who she first inspired to get into fitness."

Title: b'Boghall & Bathgate takes 2012 British Drumming Championship at Annan'
Description:
b"Boghall and Bathgate Pipe Band under Pipe Major Ross Walker at the 2012 British Pipe Band Championships held in Annan on 30 June 2012. The band played the following March, Strathspey and Reel [MSR] set in the Grade One competition:

March: Brigadier General Ronald Cheape of Tiroran [composer: PM William Ross MBE 1879 -1965]
Strathspey: Dora MacLeod [composer: Peter R. MacLeod Jr. 1918 - 1972]
Reel: The Smith of Chilliechassie [composer: PM William Ross MBE]

Weather conditions for the band's performance were ominous, dark clouds, spots of impending rain and a strong blustery wind. The band seen playing in the distance can be heard until about 2:05 minutes in.

Boghall and Bathgate Caledonia took first place in drumming and fourth place overall."

Title: b'My 16 Weeks Journey To Six Pack Abs - Week 9'
Description:
b'Arpil 16, Week 9 - M, W, F (3x per week)
Workout Routine:

RESISTANCE TRAINING

Instructions:

All exercises are done in a superset between upper body and lower body.
For example, explosive pushups(upper body) are supersetted with Squat with the bodylatics (lower body). Do NOT rest within the superset (between the upper body and lower body), but rest 30 seconds after the lower body before repeating the superset again. Repeat for a total of 2-3 rounds total. Proceed to the next superset. 

A1: Explosive Pushups
A2: Ball Squat with bands

B1: Band Fly
B2: One Leg Hamstring Curl

C1: Pullup or Chin up
C2: Reverse Lunges with free weights (e.i. plates)

D1: Band Row (Seated on the Floor)
D2: Wall Squat Hold with Calf Raises

E1: Front Lateral Raise
E2: Ball Crunch with bands for resistance

-Aim for higher reps: 15-30 reps
-Aim for 2-3 rounds for each superset (Alternating between upper body to lower body)
-Again, take no more than 30 seconds rest in between. 

INTERVAL TRAINING TIPS

If you want to maximize your results even more, I suggest that you also incorporate
my 16 week interval training with your exercise routine. The article can be found here:
http://www.iwantsixpackabs.com/my_video_tips/interval_training.html

For example:
Monday: Resistance Training (from the fitness video journal)
Tuesday: Interval Training: Cardio
Wednesday: Resistance Training (from the fitness video journal)
Thursday: Interval Training: Cardio
Friday: Resistance Training (from the fitness video journal)
Saturday: Interval Training: Cardio
Sunday: Rest

EATING TIPS

Make sure to keep following my simple eating tips:
http://www.iwantsixpackabs.com/articles/eating.html

Basic Rules:
Rule #1: Eat smaller meals throughout day. 
Rule#2: Consume enough high quality protein every day. 
Rule#3: Consume 25-35 grams of fiber each day
Rule#4: Avoid refined sugars and refined grains.
Rule#5: Consume an adequate amount of fat.
Rule#6: Keep yourself hydrated all day.'

Title: b'Sugar Boy Boxing Sparring at NYC Fight Factory Gym'
Description: b'http://www.FightFactoryNY.com Welcome to the Fight Factory Gym, home of Boxing and Martial Arts.\n\nFight factory gym invites everybody to learn and continue training. Our gym is located in the heart of Brooklyn and has a unique layout; it is divided in six zones. Each zone is dedicated to its unique disciplines and trainings run simultaneously by different instructors, who only specialize in one particular discipline. Three full size boxing rings are assigned to boxing and Muay Thai training, and are surrounded by a large variety of punching bags made by Everlast, Cleto Reyes and Grant. Judo classes and College Wrestling classes occupy the far left corner of the Gym and take up approximately 3000 sq. feet and are covered with Tiffin, dollamur wrestling mats. Our martial arts gym is fully equipped with free weights, variety of exercise machines and cardio vascular fitness equipment (treadmills, elliptical, bicycles). For more information about our Boxing and martial art classes you can check out the links on the website or call us directly at (646) 401 5657'

Title: b'WHY I STARTED CROSSFIT After Bodybuilding & Powerlifting for Years'
Description:
b"Sometimes you just need change and thats the driving reason for my starting CrossFit. I look forward to diving into something new while still holding on to my roots of bodybuilding and powerlifting. 

MY CROSSFIT GYM: http://www.cft9000.com

T-Nation Article: https://www.t-nation.com/training/bodybuilder-goes-crossfit

VLOG CHANNEL: http://www.youtube.com/channel/UCpVenD6NqonyYsm1Y1GekBA
BigBroLilBro CHANNEL:https://www.youtube.com/user/BigBroLilBroKnowBest

Please SHARE, LIKE, COMMENT, and even FAVORITE THIS VIDEO if you found it useful or if you know somebody who it may benefit. Thank you. 
 
DEPRESSION SCREENING TEST: http://healingfromdepression.com/depression-screening-test.htm 
 
My Story

My name is Noah and on May 18 2011, I had a rare reaction to a vaccine called VIVITROL and consequently spiraled into a major, agitated, suicidal depression with depersonalization. I lost 25 lbs in 4 weeks and was in full panic or near panic for 8 weeks straight mixed with the darkest most painful depression I cold have ever imagined. I immediately could not work and had to move in with my parents who along with many siblings and friends had to watch me 24/7 as I was so suicidal. I was eventually hospitalized. Getting through each day seemed truly unbearable and I knew I would surely die. I have been put on many many different SSRI's SNRI's Tricyclics, Mood stabilizers, anti psychotics, holistic meds, acupuncture and even a form of shock therapy called RTMS. I barely saw any improvement in my condition for a full year. It was decided I had treatment resistant depression and I spent nearly every moment in tears. Weeks after starting my newest round of medications (Seroquel & Nortryptaline) as a last ditch effort, I had my blood drawn for possible hormone imbalances and my Testosterone levels came back 200 ng/Dl and 150 ng/Dl. The average 25 year old male has 750 ng/Dl. With this discovery I for the first time had any type of possible explanation as to why I was not getting better and why I might be so so sick. The symptoms of such Low T are very similar to those of major depression. I started Testosterone replacement therapy soon after and have been checking in with the world and documenting my experience with treatment as well as giving my insight and perspective on various topics of mental health. I am blessed to say that I have slowly, over the last year and 10 months, been improving and becoming more stable which I never thought to be possible. My low T manifested itself in the form of Major depression, anxiety, and depersonalization/ derealization for over a year. Gaining some mental stability back is nothing short of a miracle as I was near death for what felt like forever. I do not consider myself to be totally healed yet but I am closer now then ever before and aim to use what I have been through to help or at least offer support to others in need I was able to successfully come off my Seroquel and Pamelor.

I work out all the time as a part of my mental health recovery!!! Weight training and all kinds of cardio rule much of my free time!"

Title: b'Can Anyone Do Pilates? | Pilates Workout'
Description:
b"Watch more How to Do Pilates videos: http://www.howcast.com/videos/505878-Can-Anyone-Do-Pilates-Pilates-Workout



So, a lot of people wonder, can anyone do Pilates? Yes. Everyone can do Pilates. A lot of times people think that they have to be in shape before they come to Pilates to get into shape. But, really it doesn't matter. You want to have a starting point. You want to just come in and get it going. I used to teach this mat class at an apartment building. These guys have probably heard this story so many times before. But, there used to be this man who came. He would come in and it was like he had never been in class before, and it was really odd to me. And I thought, is he listening to me, I don't understand. Because I would tell him to do The Hundred, which is one of the foundation exercises of Pilates, and he would look at me like he didn't know what I was talking about. So, I thought, he keeps coming, so he must be getting something out of this. Okay. Every time he came in, after six months, I treated him like it was the first time because you want to be encouraging. You don't want people to feel like they can't do it. So, even though kind of, in the back of my head I thought I don't really know what's going on, but he keeps showing up, so he thinks he can do it. Until month six, the week after, he comes into class and all of a sudden he's sitting up so super straight and tall. And his body just changed. And whether he was really paying attention to it or not, or coming in to the class as a first time person every time or not, the system just works. And it worked on his body and it got his spine straight where he could just sit up tall. And I remember I stopped the whole class and I said, Oh my god. You're sitting up tall. That's amazing. Do you realize it? Do you feel a difference? And he did feel the difference. Maybe he didn't know why there was a difference, but he made the commitment and he kept coming, and the system just works somehow. It's a little bit of magic So, yes, Pilates is for everybody but that doesn't mean everyone does Pilates the same way. The way Madeline might do Pilates today might be different than say, someone just starting on the mat or if you are, have a certain body condition. But, in no way is age something or gender something that limits you to certain exercises or other exercises. There are more and more men coming to Pilates. More and more athletes coming to Pilates for its benefit of stretching and to provide an alternative to the workouts that they do. I had a client who came to Pilates, her first time was in her later 60's, and she had been with us for 10 years. And this woman, at 75 years old, could do a teaser that rivaled my own. She was truly magnificent. And her posture, you see it in people with this posture. The term little old lady, absolutely not. She was fierce and she really thought it was Pilates. And that was great to hear as a teacher, but I know for her it was how she approached her work. And there were things she couldn't do because she did have some medical issues, but she wasn't discouraged by it. She just sorta learned to accept her body to find out what worked in her body, and then it integrated in a really authentic way that made her really blossom. And so I think that's the best you can hope for in Pilates and it's really there. And it's really important to come to Pilates with an open mind and not expect that if you're very strong or flexible in some other practice, that Pilates will come easily to you or that everything will instantly look like you're an advanced Pilates practitioner. Often times, with men or dancers who, dancers are used to being able to have larger ranges of motion and they're very flexible. And they come to Pilates and they realize it isn't all about stretching up as high as you can. It's about using your core to challenge yourself and then building upon that. And also, with men, people think, okay, I'm already strong. A lot of guys will come into our studio and you'll see them, they're working through it as if it's the first time they've ever done this kind of ab workout because it's totally different than what you're doing at the gym. And it's important that you keep an open mind and really listen to what your instructors are telling you. Because there's a special way of thinking about your abdominals and your core as you're doing Pilates. That's what makes it accessible to everybody, if you really pay attention and build from the beginning and all the way through advanced."

Title: b'Ejercicio 100 en Pilates Reformer - Prof. Alejandro Diaz'
Description:
b'- Este ejercicio trabaja: Abdominales, gluteos, piernas y hombros -
- Pilates: Fortalece las articulaciones. Permite alcanzar la armon\xc3\xada entre el cuerpo y la mente. Corrige las malas posturas. Mejora la agilidad, la coordinaci\xc3\xb3n, el control, la destreza, el equilibrio corporal y la flexibilidad, 
Estimula la circulaci\xc3\xb3n sangu\xc3\xadnea y el retorno venoso. Desarrolla la concentraci\xc3\xb3n. Modela el cuerpo. Tonifica. Sirve para rehabilitar lesiones.
El m\xc3\xa9todo Pilates es una t\xc3\xa9cnica de movimiento muy completa, trabaja el cuerpo en su totalidad. 
Es una combinaci\xc3\xb3n de movimientos basados en t\xc3\xa9cnicas de gimnasia, yoga, ballet y kinesiolog\xc3\xada..
Trabaja los m\xc3\xbasculos de adentro hacia fuera, contrariamente a lo que sucede con la gimnasia tradicional.
Forma cuerpos longil\xc3\xadneos, esbeltos, flexibles y fuertes por dentro.
Oxigena correctamente con la respiraci\xc3\xb3n tor\xc3\xa1xica lateral.
Puede ser practicado por personas de la tercera edad, embarazadas y gente con problemas f\xc3\xadsicos (Patolog\xc3\xadas).
Es un entrenamiento intenso muy utilizado por los bailarines. 
Mantiene en todo momento el control desde el power-house (faja abdominal y lumbar) hacia las extremidades. 
- La t\xc3\xa9cnica de Pilates Mat b\xc3\xa1sicamente es la misma que Pilates en Camas, en mat se trabaja sobre una colchoneta con la fuerza del propio cuerpo, aunque se pueden incorporar elementos (mancuernas, bandas el\xc3\xa1sticas, pelotas) mientras que en reformer se utiliza una camilla con un sistema de poleas y resortes de distintas intensidades.
Pilates mat se puede realizar en clases grupales, personalizadas o en tu propio hogar.

- Nota emitida en el programa Todos Los Gimnasios TV, para ver el programa completo de esta semana ingres\xc3\xa1 a: www.todoslosgimnasios.com.ar.

- Para ver m\xc3\xa1s videos de fitness visit\xc3\xa1 nuestro canal: www.youtube.com/user/estudio8032

- Suscribite y recib\xc3\xad todos los nuevos videos.

- Si te gust\xc3\xb3 el video clicke\xc3\xa1 en el pulgar levantado, muchas gracias!!!'

Description:

Scott Damman of Myotest tests himself to show a 13.8 inch vertical jump height versus a 11.6 inch static jump height, resulting in a 1.19 EUR.

Title: b"Hugh Jackman's THE WOLVERINE WORKOUT REVIEW- Abs & Legs"
Description:
b"Hi guys, Derek again. In this vid, I review Hugh Jackman's workout program that he used for his latest movie, The Wolverine 2013. More specifically, this is the LEGS & ABS workout.

At the top of Hugh Jackman's trainer's priority list, was ensuring that Hugh Jackman's strength was trained directly so that The Wolverine could pack on as much muscle mass as possible, simply from training with heavy weights. Which is why you'll notice a Strength Training exercise at the beginning of every workout of this program.

Here's the breakdown of this Legs & Abs workout:

1. BB Back Squat - 4 sets, *varying reps
The Staple exercise for building quality muscle on your upper legs, aka the Quads. Always keep a neutral back so that any risk to sprain the lower back is minimised as much as possible, and squat lower for a deeper contraction of the Quads. 

2. Front Squat - 4 sets
When performing the Front Squats, make sure the BB does not move within your grasp so that you don't injure yourself...

3. Single-Leg Press - 4 sets
Unless you have a pretty awesome Home gym, this exercise requires the use of a Leg Press machine. Start light and perfect your form before going heavier.

4. Calf Raise - 4 sets, 12 reps
Calf Raises can be performed seated or standing, depending on the exercise machine you use/have. Well developed calves have become a real point of difference in people's physiques as of late.

5. Hanging Leg Raises - 4 sets, 12 reps
These target the lower portion of your Abs. I've always found that having the knees bent and locked throughout the exercise, hits the lower Abs much harder than having them straight, where I'd often feel it working towards my hips.

6. Ab Wheel Roll-Outs - 4 sets, 10 reps
This exercise may look simple, but it's a killer. If you're like me and you don't have access to the right equipment, you can make-do with a DB with the weight plates left free to spin.

Things I liked about this workout:
- It's a well rounded Leg workout using big squat movements
- The number of sets and number of reps are ideal for muscle development.

The only thing I didn't like about this workout was the Calves component. I would most definitely pack in more calf exercises or sets as the calves are quite stubborn b*stards and 4 sets of 12 reps might not cut it. I know for me personally, they would just be getting started! But apart from that, that's about it - this would be pretty close to one of my own legs and abs workouts.

So what did I think of this workout as a whole? This is a great workout that just about anybody could do, men and women alike. As I said before, this workout would resemble a workout that I would do were I to train Legs and Abs. Definitely worth a shot here.


*Correction - It's been pointed out to me that the Variable Rep Scheme of this particular program isn't actually intra-workout, but actually varies on a weekly basis. So for e.g. week 1 would be 5 reps, week 2 would be 4 reps, week 3 would be 3 reps, and week 4 would be 10 reps.


**Please note that this workout was not designed by me; all credit should be forwarded to Hugh Jackman's trainer. Please see his workout program for full details."

Title: b'Landmine Barbell Training For Core Power'
Description:
b'Check out more videos like this, please visit http://www.MovementTheory.com
Personal Trainer, Theo Simon from San Diego, demonstrates a tutorial on Landmine Barbell Training For Core Power. The benefits of using a barbell landline are building core strength, maximizing fast twitch muscle function and integrating full body muscle systems to leverage the weight. The landline has one end grounded to the floor providing a circular range of motion for all planes of motion to be conquered. This video I demonstrate how to properly perform a 3 exercises circuit with the landline. The exercises I chose are designed around training for core power by using the summation of forces through hip flexion and external rotation. The exercises are a Single Arm Row, Oblique Twist and a Clean Stepping Press.

Title: b'Curl combinato con distensioni di spalle con manubri o kettlebell - Terry Fitness'
Description:
b"Come si esegue il Curl combinato con distensioni di spalle con manubri o kettlebell, esercizio per allenare le braccia (bicipiti) e le spalle

Esecuzione del Curl combinato con distensioni di spalle con manubri:

1. Rimani in posizione eretta con i piedi alla larghezza delle spalle girati leggermente in fuori

2. Mantieni il corpo dritto e impugna due manubri che andrai a posizionare ai lati del corpo, tieni il palmo rivolto in avanti, il gomito poco piegato e gli avambracci leggermente verso l'esterno

3. Tira entrambi i manubri verso le spalle e, in contemporanea, ruota il palmo delle mani avanti spingendo i manubri sopra la testa fino a quando le braccia saranno completamente distese

4. Riporta i gomiti vicino al tuo corpo, tieni il palmo delle mani rivolto verso il petto e torna lentamente alla posizione di partenza.

Errori comuni nel Curl combinato con distensioni di spalle con manubri:

\xe2\x80\xa2 Inarcare la schiena in fase di distensione sopra la testa
\xe2\x80\xa2 Non controllare la discesa e la risalita dei manubri in fase del movimento curl.

Bonus Article: Healthy Tricks for Traveling
How many times have we arrived home from vacation and realized that we were completely derailed from our healthy regimen of working out and eating well? It then takes several days to get back into the swings of things and before we know it, two weeks of skimping on workouts and eating out way too much catches up with us. But with a little planning, you too can learn healthy tricks for traveling.
The healthiest trick when traveling is to plan ahead. You wouldn't randomly show up at the airport and pick which flight you want to take, would you? Of course not-you plan ahead. You want to do the same thing when it comes to working out and eating pretty well during your vacation. Do some research online and see if the place you are staying at has a fitness facility. View any photos available to ensure it has the equipment you need to get a decent workout in. If not, search nearby to find local fitness clubs and call to find out daily rates. Some hotels offer specials with local gyms if they do not have a fitness facility onsite. Then plan out how and when you will be able to squeeze your workouts in throughout your vacation.
As for nutrition, a great travel trick is to pack plenty of snacks. You may find yourself at the airport for at least half a day or more depending on your original itinerary and flight changes. Having granola bars, mixed nuts, apples and packets of oatmeal can be a saving grace when you least expect it. Grab a bottle of water after you go through security, and refill it as you continue to travel. If you have time for a complete meal, find a balanced salad with grilled chicken or something similar (with dressing on the side!). Snacking definitely combats binging on the overwhelming fast food-type options at airports. It is a good idea to find out what restaurants you will be near while on vacation as well. You can often view complete menus online at home-even before you leave for your trip!
With a little preparation and research, you will be well on your way to enjoying your vacation. It is such a great feeling to enjoy good food, maybe some wine, and conversations with friends-all while leaving the familiar feeling of guilt from the past long behind. These healthy tricks for traveling will make your trip an energizing and refreshing experience."

Title: b'KILLER Total Back Training - In-Set Supersets For a Bigger Upper Back'
Description:
b"http://www.madscientistmuscle.com - This technique is designed to target a single muscle group (in this case the upper back) with TWO different movements in one set.

In this case, you'll be alternating overhand wide-grip barbell rows and overhand straight bar deadlifts. The muscles of the upper back are the common denominator between the two exercises (and these exercises also share the same start position making it easy to transition between them).

You'll start by alternating reps of barbell rows and deadlifts until you can no longer do rows with good form. Then you'll rep out with deadlfits, since it's the stronger movement.

This will push your upper back HARD, putting massive muscle-building tension on it. This is pre-exhaust and post-exhaust training worked into a single set."

Title: b'The Box Pistol Squat...GREAT bodyweight leg exercise for building strength'
Description:
b'Guest Video by Forest Vance
Master of Science, Human Movement, Certified Progressive Calisthenics Instructor
Author, Body Weight Strong
http://www.fitstep.com/goto/11/bodyweight-strong.htm

Up until about three and a half years ago, I had never done a pistol squat in my life. 

I thought that because I'm a "big guy", because I've had two knee surgeries, and a whole host of other reasons, pistols weren't for me ...

Long story short - I was wrong! The pistol is a great bodyweight-only exercise for building strength; it's not hard on your knees if you do it right, and big guys can and should do pistol squats.

However, performing pistol squats correctly is key to getting the most out of them and staying injury free. And the fact of the matter is, the pistol is a difficult move. It requires a unique combination of strength, flexibility, balance and more to do.

There are a lot of different ways and progressions that you might find to help you work up to doing a pistol. You name it, I've tried it - using partner assistance, holding a couterweight in front of you, elevating the back heel ...

The one that has really helped me the most to 1) work up to doing one pistol squat and 2) refine the move and work up to doing multiple reps is what I call the "box pistol".

For this move, you'll need an elevated object, like a box or a bench.

The great thing about the exercise is it takes OUT the off leg and the hard flexion in the hip flexors etc that are required to do it. And when folks are first starting, that can be very challenging.

So for the basic version of the exercise, you'll do a move that is like a pistol squat, but your off leg will go to the side of the box.

Then you can start working the off leg up in front of you as you get better and stronger.

Eventually, you'll be able to do the move with your off leg right out in front of you, like a regular pistol squat.

The best way to work this into your routine is to do it frequently, for just a few reps and sets at a time. Think of it more like practice than exercise. 

So, before or after your regular workout, you might do one or two sets of one or two reps on each leg, three to five times per week.

Get practicing, and you'll be busting out a pistol squat in no time! ;)

Thanks, train hard, and talk soon -

- Forest Vance
Certified Progressive Calisthenics Instructor

---

Body Weight Strong is a 12 week body weight only training plan designed to help you gain size and strength...with just your own bodyweight! 

Instead of the typical high-rep, conditioning-based fat loss stuff, this program will help you get STRONG, lean, and work up to cool moves like the pistol squat, one arm push ups, handstand push ups, and more. Check it out HERE.

- Ankle Marching

- Ankle Circles: Elevate your foot off of the ground through either sitting in a chair, standing and balancing on one leg or lying on your back and lifting your leg into the air. b'http://www.YogaBody.com \xe2\x80\x93 Ignite your at-home practice with this fun 20-Day Yoga Challenge. 

Yoga classes are an amazing place to learn, but at-home practice is where students often have the biggest breakthroughs. You learn techniques in class, and you refine and experiment at home.

But as you might have experienced, practicing by yourself can feel lonely and even boring - and this is why we've grown to love yoga challenges, they bring everyone together.

Here's How it Works:
\xe2\x80\xa2 Watch the video, do the pose (as best you can), snap a photo
\xe2\x80\xa2 Share your photo with hashtag #YogaBodyChallenge on Facebook or Instagram 

NOTE: this is not a competition, it's intended for motivation and education. We love learning new poses and sharing what we're learning with you. Plus, it's just really cool to see thousands of photos from around the world, everyone learning the same pose each day.

Title: b'How to Breathe and Squat'

Title: b'Gain Muscle and Lose Fat with TT 2K9 Fusion Warmup'
Description:
b"CLICK HERE FOR A FREE WORKOUT!!
http://www.turbulencetraining.com 

This is the 2K9 Fusion Fat Loss workout. This is the updated version of the 2K6 program, so you'll discover new exercises and new ways of doing things.

You'll start out with a total body warm up using only your bodyweight and really focusing on the hips. This will eliminate a lot of the pain from your lower body as well as allow you to perform the exercises much more easily.

The first exercise in the warm-up will be running in place for 20 repetitions in total. 

Next up is an exercise called the Duck Under. So, from a standing position, step out, push your hips back and slide across while ducking under. 

After that exercise you'll do Step Overs. So imagine you are stepping over something and bring your knee up in front and then outward over a tall invisible object. Then bring your other leg up and over as well, then go back the other way.

So you're really trying to loosen up your hips in a whole bunch of different directions. 

Next up is a dynamic flexibility exercise for the hamstrings called Leg Swings. So, hold onto something for support, and then swing your leg in front and behind you. Start out nice and slow as you don't want to stretch the hamstring too much on the first couple swings, and then slowly increase the range of motion with each swing. Do 20 repetitions on one side and then 20 on the other.

Then you're going to go into an exercise called the Pull Down Push up. So, spread your fingers out and get in the push up position, as you go down, tuck your elbows in and squeeze your shoulder blades together. As you come down act as if you're pulling yourself down and then pop up. Really try to focus on bringing your shoulder blades together as you go down in the push up. 

You'll finish off the warm up with a Prisoner Lunge. So, place your hands behind your head and step out and drop down, then drive back up. 

Rest for one minute, and then go through the circuit one more time and then you'll find your hips are nice and loose and ready for the workout.

Title: b'335 lbs x 7 Bench Press & Weighted Pullups Chinups (at 210 lbs)'
Description:
b"Weighted Pullup/Chinup workout today....

Started off by warming up the upper body with the bench. I hit a relatively easy PR with 335 lbs (still feeling weak from the flu and hitting bench yesterday). 

The weighted pullups/chinups all felt pretty good, so hopefully it won't take me too long to hit my goal of 5 reps with 100 lbs. 

Another goal of mine is to be able to do a Muscle Up. So, I used some band assistance at the end of the workout to practice those. I need to try these on a straight bar, as my bar bends in at the middle so I have nothing to muscle up to. I'll try it at the park next time...

I finished the workout how I started it....on the bench. I wanted to see if I could hit 10 reps with 3 plates (315 lbs) with one breath. It wasn't too bad actually...a fun little test. 

Thanks for watching..."

Title: b'315 lbs x 11 & 225 lbs x 25 Bench Press (at 225 lbs)'
Description:
b"Well.....I had to make a choice today.....hence the song....ha, ha....

I felt weak as hell on my warm up sets (325 lbs felt REALLY heavy!). So, it was either fail at this week's Ed Coan scheduled lifts or succeed at hitting a small PR with a lighter weight.....I decided to succeed!

315 lbs x 11 is a 1 rep PR, while the 25 reps with 2 plates was very easy....even with my feet up. That's all I did....now it is time to recover....

I really like the Ed Coan program, but I think I need to tweak it a bit to fit my lifting style. I really need to build up my endurance on the heavier weights....I have some thinking to do before next week...

Oh, and I am thinking I have 12 reps in me on a good day with 3 plates. We'll see...."

Title: b'Leucine Supplementation Enhances Skeletal Muscle Protein Synthesis a New Study Finds'
Description:
b'Please like, subscribe, comment and share!

SUBSCRIBE: https://www.youtube.com/user/DrJohnKiel
FACEBOOK: https://www.facebook.com/medicinelifestyle
TWITTER: https://twitter.com/LifestyleMedYou

The purpose of this study was to investigate the effect of the supplementation of a lower protein mixed macronutrient beverage with varying doses of leucine or a mixture of branched chain amino acids (BCAAs) on myofibrillar protein synthesis (MPS) at rest and after exercise. Essentially, they wanted to know more about the influence of leucine on skeletal muscle growth.

The provision of a complete mixture of amino acids increases myofibrillar protein synthesis rates through the activation of the target of rapamycin complex-1

This effect on myofibrillar protein synthesis is primarily attributable essential amino acids because nonessential amino acids do not stimulate myofibrillar protein synthesis

The relation between amino acid and protein intakes and myofibrillar protein synthesis is dose dependent and saturable. 

Of essential amino acids, the branched chain amino acid leucine is a key determinant of the postprandial stimulation of myofibrillar protein synthesis after protein intake in rodents. 

In vivo animal studies have shown that the independent administration of leucine, but not isoleucine or valine, can stimulate myofibrillar protein synthesis rates to the same extent as complete mixtures of essential amino acid or complete protein. 

Although some studies have shown increased rates of myofibrillar protein synthesis with leucine administration, other studies have not. 

The addition of branched chain amino acids, and in particular leucine, to stimulate myofibrillar protein synthesis in a less than optimally effective dose of protein may represent an effective strategy to increase myofibrillar protein synthesis after feeding or under the influence of the markedly anabolic stimulus of resistive exercise.'

Title: b'Body Bands CrossFit Advanced Resistance Band'
Description:
b'http://gg.gg/Body-Bands-CrossFit-Advanced-Resistance-Band
Body Bands CrossFit Advanced Resistance Band

This Set includes the Red 1/2", Black 3/4", Purple 1 1/8", & Green 1 3/4" Bands with resistance levels ranging from 10 to 120 lbs.
This a Great Set for Beginners and Intermediates to use for Strength Training, Resistance Training, Isometric Training, P90X, and Pull Up Assistance
Each Band has a 41" Lay Flat Length and has 82" Circular Circumference
Body Bands Basic Training Series are Layered Loop Bands which are Ideal for Individual Users from Beginners to Athletes
These Bands are Made by Layering a Continuous Sheet of Natural Rubber Latex which gives it Added Strength and Durability

Body Bands CrossFit Advanced Resistance Band

I've seen the exact same set, same colors and everything, with only the logo changes for twice the cost. These are very straightforward items so as long as they are as advertised, no reason to spend more. Completely satisfied and it is great to have the multiple tension levels available for different exercises or mobility movements.

Body Bands CrossFit Advanced Resistance Band

 recently started crossfit and I hate push-ups!!! These bands are great, I originally started with the green band because i couldn't do it with the other but now after a month I'm up to the purple bands and can do 1 pull-up with out any bands. I also use them to stretch!

Body Bands CrossFit Advanced Resistance Band

I was at the gym the other day and this guy is always using these to do pullups. I suck at pullups due to getting fat and lazy and I wanted to get back into rockin out 30 of them. These will definetly help you do that. Just be sure to be careful mounting and dismounting these bands on your foot. Its very likely to smack yourself in the face with these. Start with the big band if its not enough help add another band, do pullups. I see myself being able to do weighted pull ups very soon with the help of these. They also work great for all the band work outs, and doing dips. To use for pullups throw the band over the bar, slip one end through the other , stand on box or chair put foot in band, place other foot on top of foot in band rock out pullups all day long. I've seen people complain about these not working, or not convient of thier bar all I can say is they are most likely fat cry babies that cant suck it up.

Title: b'Smashing Old PRs!'
Description:
b"Hey guys!! Sorry if I haven't posted in a while! This video is just a compilation of all my recent PRs so far and I'm very proud of myself, which is why I wanted to share it with you all! :) 

For squats, I did 2 cycles of Smolov Jr. and I wasn't able to deadlift at all throughout those two cycles. When I sumo deadlifted, that was my first time in a long time, which is why I was so happy that I was able to hit 225! I was only able to hit 225 because my squats got stronger, and naturally, if your squats are stronger, your deadlift will be even more strong. 

However, my bench is super weak and I need to work on it!! I have to work on my form so if you guys have any tips, I would really appreciate it if you let me know in the comments!

Title: b'#ActiveBodyFit - Interval Gym Workout 3'
Description:
b"#ActiveBodyFit - Interval Gym Workout 3

Our fitness expert Samantha Clayton shows you how to do our convenient and customizable Herbalife24 certified fitness routines. Grab a friend, watch the videos at home or on the go, perform the exercises and progress through the series until you achieve your desired fitness level.

The Active Body Fit workout program helps you achieve an improved level of fitness through exercises that provide repetition, gradual progression and periods of rest. You\xe2\x80\x99ll achieve maximum benefits from the program when combined with a smart nutrition plan that helps you to build, repair and r[eplenish your body. Performing these safe and fun exercises as part of a healthy, active lifestyle will help you take the guess work out of planning your fitness routine. 

Each week, we provide you with three workouts routines consisting of five exercises each, all designed to keep your mind engaged and your body progressing. You can customize each workout to your needs by doing standard or modified exercises. You\xe2\x80\x99ll progress through Foundation, Interval and Endurance workout routines each week and at the end of each month you can test your fitness level with a Challenge workout. The best part is you can start the program anytime, do the workouts alone or with friends, and do them at home or anywhere you want. Now let\xe2\x80\x99s get to it and have some fun!

Visit Herbalife24.com for the full series: Herbalife24.com/Active
#ActiveBodyFit #Herbalife24

About Samantha Clayton:

Samantha Clayton is responsible for all activities relating to exercise and fitness education for Herbalife\xe2\x80\x99s independent Members and employees. Through in-person training sessions, educational tools and materials and her blog (www.discovergoodfitness.com), she ensures that the important role of exercise as part of a healthy active life is understood by all. She also helps create, organize, and promote employee fitness programs and activities as an integral part of the company's corporate wellness program. 
A native of Liverpool, England, Samantha initially worked as a consultant for Herbalife for two years and led the Herbalife24-Fit program, the company\xe2\x80\x99s first comprehensive fitness training program and DVD series. 
Before joining the corporate ranks, Samantha was a professional athlete. She represented Great Britain in the 2000 Sydney Olympics in both the 200m and the 4x100m relay events. Prior to the Olympics, she won two medals in the Olympic AAA trials - a silver medal for the 200m and a bronze for the 100m - as well as a silver medal in the 4x100m relay during the European Junior Championships in 1997. Her personal records include an 11.40 seconds in the 100m and 23.02 seconds in the 200m. 
Samantha is a personal trainer and group exercise coach through the American Fitness and Aerobics Association (AFAA) and International Sport Science Association (ISSA).


Statement: 

Here at Herbalife we believe that in order to achieve an improved level of fitness, an exercise series should provide you with an element of repetition, follow a gradual progression and be combined with a period of rest. To achieve the maximum benefits from your exercise plan it should always be combined with a smart nutrition plan that provides your body with the essential nutrients it needs to build, repair and replenish your body.

The aim of our Active Body Fit workout series is to provide you with safe, fun exercise ideas, and healthy active lifestyle tips to help you take the guess work out of planning your fitness routine.

We have provided you with three workouts to do each week. Each workout contains 5 key exercises that follow a variety of different progressions throughout the month, my aim is to keep you engaged and keep your body progressing. 
For each exercise provided we offer an advanced and modified version so that the workout can be tailored to fit people with all levels of fitness.

At the end of each month there is a challenge week so you can test your fitness level and have fun with your group of friends.

Watch the video for the workout on your chosen day, familiarize yourself with the moves, equipment needed and safety considerations then you are ready to go. You can do your workout anywhere, in a gym a park or at the beach you choose. Do it alone or invite your friends.

Each month I will provide with exciting and dynamic new moves to try.
Have fun and remember to share your experiences on social media with the tag #ActiveBodyFit #Herbalife24

Visit Herbalife24.com for the full series: Herbalife24.com/Active"

Description: b'Free Exercise Videos for Knee Injuries series part 3. Free Exercise Videos to Prevent Knee Injuries, is a free exercise video tutorial to help prevent knee injuries. This free exercise video can help you recover and avoid knee injuries by performing corrective knee exercises. Most knee injuries are usually due to poor biomechanics such as squatting or even walking up and down stairs incorrectly. Performing incorrect knee movements can put too much stress on the knee joint. If the muscles of the knee are not strong enough to withstand the pressure then a knee injury may result. This video will teach you how to do a corrective lunge exercise using no equipment. This exercise is beneficial for people who want to strengthen the muscles of the knee and build muscle endurance and strength to help recover and avoid knee injuries. This video is the 3rd knee exercise progression in our series of knee injuries. For more knee exercise progressions or other rehab video exercises please visit my channel and subscribe. Thanks for watching.\n\nOscar Sanchez, C.S.C.S.'

Title: b'Home Gym Pro 3000 Focus Fitness - Betersport'
Description:
b"Te koop bij Betersport:


De Focus Fitness Pro 3000 Home Gym
https://www.betersport.nl/home-gym-focus-fitness-pro-3000.html


De Pro 3000 Home Gym is een allround fitnesstoestel. Het zeer uitgebreid krachtstation gecombineerd met een Chin-dip en Pull up bar zorgt er voor dat dit unieke multifunctionele krachtstation aan alle wensen voldoet. De thuissporter heeft de keus om met zijn eigen lichaamsgewicht te trainen en/of gebruik te maken van het krachtstation met de bijgeleverde gewichtsblokken.

Gevarieerde spiergroepen en oefeningen

De Chin-Dip en Pull up Bar worden gezamenlijk ook wel de Power Tower genoemd.

Het gewicht dat u inzet tijdens de training is uw lichaamsgewicht. De voordelen van trainen met uw eigen lichaamsgewicht zijn: minder snel last van blessures, gewrichten worden minder snel belast, u traint meerdere spieren tegelijk en doordat u voor veel oefeningen uw co\xc3\xb6rdinatievermogen gebruikt zult u een stabieler lichaam krijgen. De voornaamste spieren die u traint met de Power Tower zijn de: triceps, biceps, rugspieren en de core. (Core: buik, onder rug en bekken.)

Een aantal voorbeelden van oefeningen die u kunt doen zijn: 

Buik:

Vertical knee raise en vertical legg raise.

Armen:

Close grip front lat pullup en dipping.

Rug:

Wide grip pull up en close grip pullup.

 Met het krachtstation van de Pro 3000 kunt u meer dan 45 verschillende oefeningen trainen. Het grote voordeel in vergelijking met vele andere Home Gym's is dat u geen kabels of pinnen hoeft te verleggen of om te steken, wanneer u de ene naar de anderen oefening uitvoert. Enkele oefeningen zijn:

Borst:

Chest press, Bench Press en Butterfly.

Rug:

Front en Back Lat Pulldown.

Armen:

Tricep pushdown, triceps extension en standing cable curl.

Benen:

Leg extension en Leg curl.

Buik:

Ab crunch en Cable crunch with twist.

Schouders:

Cable upright row en Cable front raise.

 Standaard bijgeleverd

Het krachtstation is voorzien van 60 KG gewichtsblokken. Mede dankzij het katrollersysteem kunt u bepaalde oefeningen tot 120 KG trainen. Ook de Pro 3000 is voorzien van een lange en korte Pully stand. Ook de vernieuwde en verstelbare chest press is van absolute meerwaarde. 

Mogelijkheid tot uitbreiden

Om nog meer voordelen uit de Focus Fitness Pro 300 te halen en profijt te hebben van de mogelijkheden zijn er een aantal producten die uitstekend geschikt zijn om de Home Gym uit te breiden. Denk hierbij aan Lat Pully trekstang gebogen, Dubbele handgreep, het tricep touw en de single grip. Voor meer informatie kunt u terecht hieronder bij verwante producten.

Sterk materiaal 

Door de stabiele bouw van de Pro 3000 zal het toestel nauwelijks bewegen als u traint. Door de extra comfortabele rug en arm kussens kunt u zonder ergernissen trainen. De verstelbare handvaten zorgen ervoor dat u met hele gezin plezier heeft van de Home Gym. Zoals u gewent bent van Focus Fitness is ook deze Home Gym voorzien van een gehamerde coating, een stalen frame, kogellagers en verstevigde kabels die omkleed zijn met nylon.

 De Focus Fitness Pro 3000 Home Gym is de ideale multi-gym voor elke sporter. Zo kunt u afwisselend trainen met uw eigen lichaamsgewicht en aan de gewichten hangen in het krachtstation. Dit allround multistation zorgt ervoor dat u gericht uw doelen kunt verwezenlijken vanuit thuis.

 Niet geschikt voor personen boven de 190cm

Title: b'creatine stiz'
b'Back training 03/01/14'
Description: b'Back session from yesteday. I started out with deadlift but I was not sure what I would work up to because I have not pulled in a while. I was surprsingly able to work up to 675 for a single before my nagging forearm injury kicked in. I have no idea what or where the injury came from but it has been bothering me since my powerlifting meet on/off for about 6 weeks. I continued my session with 3 sets of pull ups, then 4 sets of dumbbell rows (last 2 sets in this video) and finished with 3 sets of incline T-bar row (set #2 in this video). I would have rather liked to finish with seated cable rows but it was occupied. \n\nThis was also the first time I trained without wraps until I really needed them such as my heaviest sets as suggested by my girlfriend. This is in effort to continue to improve my grip. It was also motivating watching her work up to 425 for 2 reps on the rack pull and 110lbs on the DB row!'

Description: b'Several variations on the biceps curl transfer some of the load from the biceps to other flexors of the elbow. Title: b'Dragon Gym BBQ 6'
b'Kettlebell Goblet Squat'
Description:
b'FUNK EXERCISE OF THE WEEK (FEOW): Kettlebell Goblet Squat
http://www.funkrobertsfitness.com

KETTLEBELL GOBLET SQUAT
-- Men 30 -- 50 pounds Women -- 15- 30 pounds
\xe2\x80\xa2 With both hands, grab the bottom of the kettlebell at your chest, and stand with your feet slightly beyond shoulder width (if you are using the dumbbell grasp it vertically by one end)
\xe2\x80\xa2 Sit back and down like you are sitting in a chair 
\xe2\x80\xa2 Keeping your back naturally arched, push your hips back, bend your knees, and lower your body until the tops of your thighs are at least parallel to the floor
\xe2\x80\xa2 Spread the knees with your elbows. As you reach your lowest point your elbows will be between your legs. Use your elbows to gently spread your knees a bit wider.
\xe2\x80\xa2 Pause, Stand back up. Drive your heels into the ground, squeeze your gluteus, and stand back up.

Title: b'Deadlift and OHP Mash Up Wendler 531 C113 W19 Cut RD2'
Description:
b'The finale session of Cycle 11 for Wendler 5/3/1 and it was a bit of a mash up of both OHP and Deadlift days. I just aimed for the main sets for the two lifts and did some extra OHP work. This was mainly to "catch up" due to my training pattern being all skew wiff after going to the Body Power Expo.

OHP of 75kg x 2 was more than pleased with this. Almost at a 1x BW for OHP which has been one of my "mini goals" so should have it soon!

Deadlifts - after speaking a while back with my friend Michael, I made the decision to drop out the plywood base I stand on because the plates that I have are 400mm diameter whilst proper plates are 450mm. This equates for a 25mm / inch deficit ever since I have been training at home... lol

I switched the board so now even though still at a very slight deficit it is closer to the right height if I was using competition plates.

Check out Michaels channel here: https://www.youtube.com/user/littleRKOrton

Title: b'Tsunami Bar\xc2\xae'
Description:
b"The Tsunami Bar\xc2\xae (US Pat. No. 7,951,051 and other patents pending) is a flexible barbell that is made from a combination of special composite materials that provides an extraordinary training stimulus. This stimulus is based off two factors that are known as amplitude and oscillatory actions.

 The dual action of the bar that includes amplitude and oscillatory movement creates a rolling wave that stimulates the sensory receptors, which are scientifically known as proprioceptors. When these sensory receptors are stimulated at a higher degree than a standard barbell this allows for greater muscle activation and stabilization. In fact, EMG testing data suggests that muscle activation is approximately 20% greater, and that stabilizer muscles are three times more active using the Tsunami Bar\xc2\xae compared to a standard barbell.

 All lifts performed on a standard barbell can be performed with the Tsunami Bar\xc2\xae -- and then some. Today's athlete is looking for a power reservoir inside them that they can pull from at any moment in time and be fit to perform any task that is thrown at them from a power, speed, conditioning and functional standpoint. The Tsunami Bar\xc2\xae will help build this power reservoir to meet the needs of a modern-day athlete. What separates the Tsunami Bar\xc2\xae is that it comes to life, not based on weight added to the bar, but according to forces and movements that are used against the bar. This is what makes it unlike any training bar or device out there."

Coach Mark Milstead"

Title: b'Carve Up Your Pecs with Push-In Bench Push-Ups (massive peak contraction exercise)'
Description:
b'This version of the push-up is going to focus on achieving a MASSIVE peak contraction of the pecs, similar to a pec deck machine or cable-crossover exercise only using just a bench...

... yes, literally just a bench.

And it'll actually give you just as good (if not better!) contraction on your pecs than those machines will!

---
http://www.thebestchestexercises.com
---

Now, even though the exercise LOOKS like a regular push-up, the key here is HOW you perform the exercise.

Set your hands on the bench, gripping around the SIDES of it. Just the "meat" of your hands on the thumb side should be on top...(we do want a little vertical support). Keep your body relatively straight and stiff during the exercise.

Now lower yourself to the bottom position.

CRITICALLY IMPORTANT!!!! At the bottom, rest your chest COMPLETELY on the bench so that you take ALL the elastic tension out of the upper body.

Eliminating this tension is also going to help you reduce the action of the triceps during the "up" phase.

The hips will bend a bit here in order to achieve the flat chest position on the bench (that's what I mean by relatively straight body position...you do want to keep a stiff body during the exercise, though).

You'll see in the video that I actually move my arms a bit at the bottom to ensure I've taken all the tension out of the upper body at the bottom.

Now...DO NOT push up...that's not the muscle action we're looking for.

Instead, try to MASH your hands together as though squeezing the bench.

This will just happen to move your body up as a side effect...

Keep trying to push/squeeze your hands together until your elbows are fully locked out at the top of the exercise.

Then repeat, coming back down and resting your chest fully on the bench.

Then SQUEEZE in to move your body back up.

Remember, the real key here is NOT trying to complete a certain number of "reps" with this one...I'm not even going to give you a rep-range guideline for this.

The key is FEEL.

We're trying to achieve a MASSIVE contraction in the pecs and if you're trying to count to a certain number of reps, you're going to lose focus on trying to FEEL the pecs contracting hard during the exercise.

So bottom line, drop the concept of "reps" for this exercise...just take your time and get your mind into the muscle to focus on that peak pec contraction.

And, above all, think "push in" instead of "push up".'

Title: b"George Watson's College Pipe Band: Juvenile European Champions 2012"
Description:
b"While setting up my camera at Belfast I was able to catch the pipe band of George Watson's College, Edinburgh, playing its medley in the Juvenile Grade competition at the 2012 European Pipe Band Championships. All members of a juvenile band must be under 18 years of age other than one adult, usually the pipe major, here Iain Simpson.

That being so, this band produces a great sound and is a regular participator and winner at pipe band competitions. The band has already taken the 2012 Scottish and British Juvenile Championships and this performance added the European Championship.

The band is playing a medley comprising the following tunes:

Twelve Torlum, composed by Peter Graham
John Paterson's Mare, traditional
The Music Man, composed by James D Nisbet
Seonaidh's Tune, composed by Fred Morrison
Mrs MacLeod of Raasay, traditional
with a reprise of The Music Man at the end.

This is not a great video technically. The camera shake was caused by the wind, the gusts really were that strong!"

Title: b'Allie Slowik Boxing 2010'
Description:
b'Hi! My name is Allie Slowik and I am a 17 year-old senior in high school. After I waved goodbye to my varsity basketball career, I discovered the fighting sports of boxing and muay thai. I immediately fell in love with the two and now aspire to actively compete in both. I have been training in these fighting sports for approximately 10 months and entered the 'sparring stage' of the two about 4-5 months ago. I would die without my boxing/muay thai in college and so I have compiled this video of my training thus far to present to the various colleges I am interested in hopes of becoming part of their competitive boxing teams. So, here it is, I am humbly open to any tips/criticism (as i know I still have a long way to go :) ), and I hope you enjoy!


Special thanks to my parents, my coaches, and my sparring partners for making this all possible and allowing me to reach for my dreams :)!!

Further note: The girl I am sparring with is Gillian "Saltz" (incorrect spelling in the video). She is a wonderful boxer who has been training for 2 years and is also looking to compete. Always a pleasure to get my healthy doses of punches in the face from you girl ;D!!'
