Title: b'FISICAMENTE - CORSO DI CHAIR'
Description:
b"Il Pilates \xc3\xa8 un metodo che incorpora movimenti e principi di allineamento che una volta compresi e messi in atto nel proprio schema motorio aiutano noi e i nostri clienti a\xc2\xa0mantenere\xc2\xa0il benessere articolare - muscolare\xc2\xa0e prevenire e ritardare tutta una serie di disfunzioni.
In questo weekend di 16 ore \xc3\xa8 possibile acquisire le basi didattiche necessarie a\xc2\xa0trasferire ai nostri clienti abilit\xc3\xa0 e correttezza motoria\xc2\xa0in tutte le tipologie di movimento, nel modo pi\xc3\xb9 funzionale possibile e in maniera pi\xc3\xb9 profonda, dettagliata e scientifica.
Partendo da un'analisi dei Principi che sono alla base del Methodo Pilates, il Master Trainer Balanced Body University, Anna Maria Vitali analizzer\xc3\xa0 nel dettaglio quali sono le fascie muscolari, articolari e connettivali che intervengono in ogni movimento base del Pilates.
Sono\xc2\xa0previste\xc2\xa0due classi di Mat (esercizi base introduttivi) per capire con il movimento del proprio corpo i concetti base come: l'allineamento assiale corretto e/o disfunzionale, il Core (il Centro), il neutral spine, la stabilit\xc3\xa0 lombopelvica, mobilit\xc3\xa0 e stabilit\xc3\xa0 della colonna vertebrale, stabilit\xc3\xa0 e mobilit\xc3\xa0 del cingolo omero scapolare, la respirazione. Gli stessi concetti vengono supportati dall'analisi\xc2\xa0anatomica e biomeccanica dei vari esercizi grazie ai supporti in video, foto e modelli in scheletro, e l'osservazione del corpo dei partecipanti stessi\xc2\xa0.
L'allievo ricever\xc3\xa0 quindi, sia nozioni per come impostare una classe base preparatoria al Mat che nozioni\xc2\xa0approfondite e specifiche dell'Anatomia e Biomeccanica\xc2\xa0applicate al Pilates.
La frequenza del weekend \xc3\xa8 obbligatoria per chi \xc3\xa8 iscritto o intende iscriversi ai percorsi di formazione per Istruttori Pilates Matwork e/o Reformer e/o Studio."

Title: b'SickFit: Fit In 15 #1 15 Min. Bodyweight Bootcamp Real Time Workout'
Description:
b'This is a 5 exercise, full body, bodyweight circuit combing full body cardio, strength and core exercises. The Tutorial video breaks down each of these exercises, including modifications based on your fitness level. I am using a 50/10 interval, where I work out for 50 seconds and then take a 10 second break before moving to the next exercise. Obviously, if a 50 second interval is too much for you because you are building a fitness base, you can use a 30/30 or 40/20. The bottom line, find a modification and a Level that will allow you to get an optimal workout. 

I recommend that you do a 5-10 minute warm-up and a stretching cool-down after this workout. Remember, form is #1 therefore it is very important that you modify according to your fitness level.

The workout:
1. Criss Cross Jacks
2. Push Up Jacks
3. Legs Crossed Crunches
4. Prison Squats
5. Floor to Ceiling Jumps

Please comment below and let me know how the workout worked for you. 

Shot at AnyTime Fitness in Santa Clara.'

Title: b'Standing Squat Exercise Video'
Description:
b'Stand holding a weight in each hand, arms down at your sides. Keep your feet shoulder-width apart and knees slightly bent. Keeping your torso straight, head up and weight toward your heels, lower your body as far down as you can while maintaining good balance. Hold, then return to the start position. Important: When lowering your body, do not let your knees extend beyond your toes.

If using water bottles as weights, be sure caps are fully tightened.

The information in this video is not intended to take the place of your doctor or other healthcare professionals. Title: b'Vegan For Fit - 30 Tage Challenge - Tag 18: K\xc3\xb6rperfett und Squat Challenge Aufruf'
Description:
b"Den vollst\xc3\xa4ndigen Post, sowie eine Tabelle, an der ihr den f\xc3\xbcr euch idealen K\xc3\xb6rperfett-Anteil ablesen k\xc3\xb6nnt findet ihr hier: http://bit.ly/VeganTag18

Ich habe mein K\xc3\xb6rperfett letztes Jahr zum ersten Mal messen lassen (in einer relativ aktiven Phase) hatte ich einen (lt. dieser Tabelle) mittelm\xc3\xa4\xc3\x9figen bis guten Wert. Meine neue Waage, die ich seit gestern besitze zeigte mir, etwas \xc3\xbcber ein Jahr sp\xc3\xa4ter, einen mittelm\xc3\xa4\xc3\x9figen bis schlechten Wert. Ich muss sagen ich bin etwas geschockt. Ich kann aber die Ursachen nat\xc3\xbcrlich nicht genau finden, da ich meine Werte vor der Challenge nicht kannte. Ich kann es also nicht blindlings auch meine geliebten Nussmuse schieben ;) In dem letzten Jahr habe ich zwar auch ab und zu Sport getrieben, aber nichts regelm\xc3\xa4\xc3\x9figes...

Aber ich will hier auch gar nicht viel jammern, sondern die Sache in die Hand nehmen und mein K\xc3\xb6rperfett mit eurer Hilfe nochmals ordentlich nach unten treiben. We're bringing sexy back! ;)

Meine Idee ist es, dass ich f\xc3\xbcr jeden Video Aufruf den dieses Video am 25.7.2013 um 12h mittags hat werde ich einen Squat (=Kniebeuge) machen. Das hei\xc3\x9ft f\xc3\xbcr euch: teilen, teilen, teilen. Schickt dieses Video an so viele Freunde wie m\xc3\xb6glich und bringt meine Oberschenkel damit so richtig zum Gl\xc3\xbchen :D

Nat\xc3\xbcrlich wird es dann auch noch ein Video dazu geben wie ich meine pers\xc3\xb6nliche Squat-Challenge absolviere.. Damit ihr das nicht verpasst, abonniert doch meinen YouTube Kanal :)

Title: b'Homemade Bulgarian Bag complex'
Description:
b"This is my Bulgarian Bag Complex

This is really hard on your grip, so if you've got bad forearms I suggest you start with a lighter bag and then progressively move up in weight.

This is One Round

10 Spins
10 Tricep Extensions
10 Snatches
10 Swings
10 Woodchops
10 Good Mornings
10 Squats
10 Lunges
10 Front Raises
10 Bent Rows
10 Spins

3-6rounds
1minute rest in between rounds

Bag Weight :- 10Kg/22lb

By the end of the Woodchops your forearms want a rest, with a heavier bag you could drop the Swings to help prevent forearm fatigue. Well that's what I'd do."

Title: b'Rutinas de ejercicios para aumentar masa muscular. #MICROCICLO6 Semana18 a 21 MUSCULOTUBE'
Description:
b'Llegamos a uno de los microciclos m\xc3\xa1s "puros" de aumento de masa muscular . Al contrario de lo que mucha gente piensa, la hipertrofia (aumento de volumen) requiere entrenamientos cortos y potentes. Es decir, se debe intentar agotar el m\xc3\xbasculo en el menor tiempo posible. 

Entrenamientos muy largos, de muchos ejercicios con muchas series es muy dif\xc3\xadcil que sean los m\xc3\xa1s \xc3\xb3ptimos para conseguir ese objetivo. El asunto est\xc3\xa1 en que para llegar a estos tipos de entrenamiento se debe haber conseguido una t\xc3\xa9cnica y un desarrollo previo de la fuerza adecuados para conseguir objetivos \xc3\xb3ptimos con el menor riesgo posible para tejidos "involuntarios" (huesos, tendones, ligamentos, etc...) 

Para eso hemos estado 17 semanas allanando el terreno, prepar\xc3\xa1ndonos para \xc3\xa9sto. Ahora ya est\xc3\xa1s aqu\xc3\xad, Con una rutina de ejercicios que busca entrenamientos cortos en los que cada grupo muscular quede agotado en 3 ejercicios de series de 8 repeticiones cada uno. 

El descanso de 3 minutos entre series es primordial para que los niveles de energ\xc3\xada se repongan. Dicho todo esto, imagino que queda claro que la carga (el peso) en cada serie debe ser el que, de la forma m\xc3\xa1s ajustada posible, nos permita hacer 8 repeticiones. 

Para cualquier duda o comentario, me tienes aqu\xc3\xad o en cualquiera de las siguientes redes sociales:

Title: b'Queensland Police Pipes and Drums Whitsunday Christian College'
Description:
b'Kops in Kilts perform to school audiences

The squeeze of bagpipes, the beating of drums and the swish of kilts can only mean one thing -- the Queensland Police Pipes and Drums are in town.

This week the Pipes and Drums will be performing their Kops in Kilts tour in schools in the central and northern regions from November 15 to November 19.

The Kops in Kilts program is a 40 minute concert that combines traditional and modern Pipe Band music as well as children's favourites including Bob the Builder, Limbo Rock and the Mexican Hat Dance.

Queensland Pipes and Drums Officer in Charge Senior Sergeant Peter Flexman said part of the performance would be interactive.

"We will give some of the students an opportunity to be involved in providing additional percussion to music when we play," Senior Sergeant Flexman said.
"It is a great way for the kids to get involved and an insight into playing with a pipe band."

The Police Pipes and Drums wear traditional Highland dress and a member of the band will provide an explanation of the uniform, the reason behind its use as well as the history and operation of the bagpipes and drums.

The Queensland Police Pipes and Drums has been performing the 'Kops-In-Kilts' program since the programs inception in 1998 and has performed at numerous Primary Schools ranging from locally based schools in Brisbane, regional areas including Cunnamulla, St. George, Cairns, Charleville and Osaka Japan in 2008.

The Pipes and Drums will be performing for the following schools:

Yesterday
Whitsunday Christian College, 10.15am to 10.55am
Cannonvale State School, 2pm to 2.40pm

Today
Calen District State School, 10.15am to 10.55am
Bloomsbury State School, 1.15pm to 1.55pm

Wednesday November 17
Proserpine State School, 12pm to 12.40pm
St. Catherine's State School, 2pm to 2.40pm

Thursday November 18
Queens Beach State School, 10.15am to 10.55am
Bowen State School 1pm to 1.40pm

Friday November 19
Hamilton Island State School 10am to 10.40am'

Title: b'Fat Loss Workouts with TT Hot Zone Workout Warmup'
Description:
b"CLICK HERE for a FREE WORKOUT!!
http://www.turbulencetraining.com

This is the August 2008 Hot Zone Workout. The 4 hot zones of the body are the pressing muscles and the chest, the torso/abdominal area, the back of the legs and the upper back area. If you train and exercise for one of those areas, everything else will get trained and boost your metabolism. Those are the 4 hot zone areas were going to be going after in each workout (A, B & C) and even the warmup workout.

This is the bodyweight warmup for the Hot Zone Workout. We're going to start with 4 exercises and make sure we hit the chest, abdominals, the back of the legs and the upper back.

Start with a Y-Squat. Put your hands up in the Y position and keep your shoulder blades back. This will work the upper back and the back of the legs.

Next is elevated pushups which will work the upper chest and abdominals. Place one hand on a dumbbell or something about 4-6 inches off the floor. Do all reps on one side and then switch to the other side.

1-Leg Romanian Deadlifts are next. This is one of my favourite exercises to really get my hamstrings warmed up for squats. Stand on one leg, keeping a slight bend to it. Push the other leg straight back and feel a nice strong stretch in your hamstring and come back up. You will also use your glute when you come back up. You can use the wall for balance if you need to. Do 8-10 reps on each side.

Your next warmup exercise is a Stick-Up. Keep your heels about 6-inches from the wall and press your back, butt, shoulder blades, elbows, wrists, hands and head against the wall the entire movement. Tuck your elbows down into your sides and raise your hands into a stick-up position. Keep all of those points against the wall the entire movement.

Go through these 4 exercises, rest for 30 seconds and repeat this circuit one more time and this will get you ready for the Hot Zone Workout A.

Title: b'Muscle Building Tip to Build Size and Get Lean'
Description:
b"Grab your free ebook here: http://joecarabase.com
How do you build size and stay lean?

I get asked this question often...and it's a loaded question but today I'm going to share my OCD Method which will help get you started.

To get ripped, your training program needs to have a mix of heavy lifting, bodyweight training, higher rep sets and a metabolic tempo.

However when lifting heavy, you simply can not superset unless you're training opposing muscle groups. Even then, depending on how heavy and what lifts you are doing, you don't want to expend too much energy.

My OCD Method: In between heavy sets, do one of the following:
1. PAce side to side and hydrate with water
2. Walk the length of the gym and back
3. Perform an active stretch of the working muscle

This method allows you to keep your mind focused on your lifts and conserve energy while keeping your muscles active. 

DO NOT engage with gym rats...save conversations for after your workout. The more your mind is focused on lifting, the better results you will see.

#killit

JC

Title: b'Pilates Exercise: SI Stabilization'
Description:
b"Okay so we're going to do SI stabilization, some people call it half butterfly. This exercise is for the stabilization of the pelvis. We usually give this out as homework when we see our clients have a rotation in the pelvis because we know it has to do with some SI pathology. This is a really great exercise is strengthen the muscles around the SI joint and stabilize the pelvis, it's also very challenging. 

We want to start with the feet together, knees bent, and what I call mountain top position. Cara is going to prepare the movement by exhaling and tapping into the core, pulling the belly deep and wide, bearing down into the pelvic floor and transverse abs and deflating the diaphragm. At the end of the exhale she's going to open one knee out to the side as she keeps her pelvis completely still and then on the inhale she'll bring it back in. 

I suggest doing the same side just so you get a really good feeling for it. The movement is simple but what's challenging about this exercise is the subtlety of it. What you really want to feel working is the contralateral side of the core from the leg that's opening. For example, Cara's working the left leg, she should be feeling the left side of her core 

We want to feel grounded to the first and fifth metatarsal and heel of the standing leg and feel the inner thigh connection of the standing leg because that ties into the pelvic floor.

Cara's focusing on the breath, really tapping into the core and making sure she's feeling that left side of the core really working. Noticing how she's fully deflating the diaphragm so she can get those rectus abs in as well. She's got a solid trunk going here it's very nice. Feeling grounded through that first and fifth meditarcel of the standing leg and feeling that inner thigh connection with is connected to the pelvic floor. 


Remember the purpose of the exercise is to keep the pelvis completely still so if you're moving the pelvis we're defeating the purpose of the exercise."

Title: b'SMR Methods for Joint Mobilization and the DIY Voodoo Band Mod'
Description:
b'http://www.JWFitnessSystems.com 

Jameson Wolff shows how you can use some of Kelly Starrett's SMR (self myo-fascial release) techniques to break up surrounding joint scar tissue, improve joint mobilization, and promote blood flow to unsaturated tissues. 

Kelly uses terms such as "Smashing" to represent self myo fascial release, "Gapping" to promote flexion rang-of-motion (ROM), and "Flossing" to represent the use of Voodoo bands or tire tubes to compress and shear scar tissue around surrounding joints and joint capsules. 

DIY Voodoo Band:

You can buy Kelly's voodoo bands for 24 bucks here: 
http://www.roguefitness.com/voodoo-floss-bands.php

But you can easily and affordably buy a 29" x 1.9-2.3" bicycle tube (brand: Axiom) and cut it width wise once and then length wise along the seam twice to get two homemade bands. Then just soak and wash them. This costs around 7-10 bucks.

Disclaimer: 
Stretching and fascial specific theories lack scientific evidence for its effectiveness in improving long term flexibility, extensibility, and injury prevention. Neuromuscular ideas like Trigger points MAY provide a better theory for why such techniques work (See references below)
1) Azevedo DC. Uninvolved versus target muscle contraction during contract: relax proprioceptive neuromuscular facilitation stretching. Phys Ther Sport. 2011 Aug;12(3):117-21. doi: 10.1016/j.ptsp.2011.04.003. Epub 2011 Jun 2.
2) J. C Andersen. Stretching Before and After Exercise: Effect on Muscle Soreness and Injury Risk J Athl Train. 2005 Jul-Sep; 40(3): 218--220.
3) Weppler CH. Increasing muscle extensibility: a matter of increasing length or modifying sensation? Phys Ther. 2010 Mar;90(3):438-49. doi: 10.2522/ptj.20090012. Epub 2010 Jan 14.
4) Shrier I. Stretching before exercise does not reduce the risk of local muscle injury: a critical review of the clinical and basic science literature. Clin J Sport Med. 1999 Oct;9(4):221-7.
5) Daniel Pereles1, MD. A Large, Randomized, Prospective Study of the\xc2\xa0
Impact of a Pre-Run Stretch on the Risk of Injury in\xc2\xa0
Teenage and Older Runners; 1CAQ Sports Medicine, 2USATF, 3Simon Fraser University
6) Chaudhry H. Three-dimensional mathematical model for deformation of human fasciae in manual therapy.
\xc2\xa0J Am Osteopath Assoc. 2008 Aug;108(8):379-90.
7)E. C. Falvey. Iliotibial band syndrome: an examination of the evidence behind a number of treatment options
\xc2\xa0Scand J Med Sci Sports 2010: 20: 580--587 doi: 10.1111/j.1600-0838.2009.00968.x
8)Elena P Calandre. Myofascial trigger points in cluster headache patients: a case series
Head Face Med. 2008; 4: 32. Published online 2008 December 30. doi:\xc2\xa0 10.1186/1746-160X-4-32
9) Weppler CH. Increasing muscle extensibility: a matter of increasing length or modifying sensation? Phys Ther. 2010 Mar;90(3):438-49. doi: 10.2522/ptj.20090012. Epub 2010 Jan 14.

Title: b'Squat training for USAPL 2010 MD State Powerlifting Championships'
Description:
b"Rather than upload a new video for each week, I've decided to group all of my heavy squats for this years MD States. Week one was directly off another sucessful 6 months of 5/3/1 training, ending at 355x7.

The meet was announced with only eight weeks to prepare, so not only did I start using wraps (and a belt, for that matter) earlier than usual, the weight ramped up MUCH quicker than usual. Week one went well, but the jump to 405 on week two was a bit of a shock to the system.

I adjusted quickly, and kept throwing more & more weight on the bar, and I'm glad to say I responed well. I am thrilled to end the cycle with a 525 PR, which beats my unofficial meet PR of 523. It is unofficial because it was done a the 2009 SSPT Snowmeggedon meet, held the day the MD States were cancelled due to two feet of snow. My true meet PR is 507, from the Navy Open in February 2010.

If you want to know what my planned 3rd attempt is, you'll have to come to the meet. I'm fairly certain it will be a new PR."

Title: b'Hit All Your Muscle Fiber Types in Your Back With Range-of-Motion Triple Add Sets'
Description:
b"This is a GREAT technique for hitting all the muscle fiber types in a target muscle. If you're familiar with a Triple Drop Set, this is a similar concept, however instead of dropping, we're going to get a little more complex...

First, it's a Triple ADD Set, which means we're going to be making the exercise HARDER as we go through...however, it's NOT going to be by adding weight.

We're going to use the same weight all the way through, just changing the rep ranges and the range of motion in order to target the different muscle fibers.

First, we'll hit the slow-twitch fibers with a short range of motion in the peak contracted position of the wide-grip barbell row. This will be a fast movement, focusing on the contraction at the top. Got for at least 30+ reps on this set (make sure you use a weight that allows you to get these reps - I'm using 135 lbs).

Be sure you're not bobbing up and down with your upper body and make sure you're keeping your core tight and your lower back arched. This will help protect the lower back and help you feel the musles of the upper back working.

When you've done as many reps as you can, set the bar down, rest ten seconds, then pick it up again. This next set is for 6 to 8 reps done in a half range of motion, staying above the sticking point of the exercise.

This part of the set should be done with a very deliberate movement - no bouncing at all, keeping tension on the muscles of the back all the way through. This is going to target the type 2b fast twitch fibers.

When you've finished that, set the bar on the floor and rest 10 seconds. It's time for FULL range reps.

These are going to be done Pendlay Row style, setting the bar on the floor on every rep to ensure proper positioning.

Use a strong, POWERFUL movement and get a complete contraction at the top.

Repeat this for 1 to 3 reps (this will be about all you'll be able to get with that weight at this point).

You're done! That's one Range of Motion Triple Add Set.

Now do this 2 more times and that's your back workout (rest 2 to 3 minutes between each full 3-part set)."
